(5, 'Long-necked dinosaurs grew to be giants in more ways than one', 'Fossils suggest some early sauropod relatives grew massive using a previously unknown method', 'Carolyn Gramling', '2018-07-10', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/long-necked-dinosaurs-grew-be-giants-more-ways-one?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'long-necked-dinosaurs-grew-be-giants-more-ways-one', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070918_CG_gigantic-dino_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Fossils suggest some early sauropod relatives grew massive using a previously unknown method</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-389979d1487d15dbdec3a2fdacfd7310">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/carolyn-gramling">Carolyn Gramling</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">11:49am, July 10, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070918_CG_gigantic-dino_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070918_CG_gigantic-dino_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070918_CG_gigantic-dino_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="giant long-necked sauropod" title="GETTING BIGÂ  Some early relatives â€“ such as Ingentia prima, illustrated â€“ of giant long-necked sauropods may have had a unique way of growing to such a large size. ~~ Jorge A. GonzÃ¡lezÂ " /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070918_CG_gigantic-dino_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="giant long-necked sauropod" title="GETTING BIGÂ  Some early relatives â€“ such as Ingentia prima, illustrated â€“ of giant long-necked sauropods may have had a unique way of growing to such a large size. ~~ Jorge A. GonzÃ¡lezÂ " /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070918_CG_gigantic-dino_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><b>GETTING BIG</b>Â  Some early relatives â€“ such as <i>Ingentia prima</i>, illustrated â€“ of giant long-necked sauropods may have had a unique way of growing to such a large size.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Jorge A. GonzÃ¡lezÂ </p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>For sauropods â€” the largest animals known to have walked on Earth â€” there may have been more than one way to get gigantic.</p><p>Most early relatives of the herbivorous dinosaurs have a suite of features once thought to be the essential blueprint for gigantism, such as sturdy pillarlike legs, elongated necks and forelimbs, and bones that grew continuously rather than in seasonal spurts. But an analysis of fossils of sauropodomorphs â€” a group that includes sauropods and some ancestors and similarly shaped relatives â€” suggests that some of the dinos may have had <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41559-018-0599-y">a different strategy for becoming behemoths</a>, researchers report online July 9 in <em>Nature Ecology and Evolution</em>.</p><p>Paleontologist Cecilia Apaldetti of the Universidad Nacional de San Juan in Argentina and colleagues examined four sauropodomorphs, including one newly identified species that the team dubbed <em>Ingentia prima</em> and three already known specimens of a sauropodomorph called <em>Lessemsaurus sauropoides</em>. Dating to the Late Triassic, between 237 million and 201 million years ago, these â€œLessemsauridaeâ€ were far from puny: The animals weighed in at an estimated 7 to 10 metric tons, larger than an African elephant.</p><p>All four specimens showed a combination of features that was distinct from sauropods as well as from other sauropodomorphs. Instead of upright, pillarlike legs, the dinos had crouched hind limbs and flexed front limbs, with elbows splayed slightly outward. Patterns of bone growth in the fossils also suggest that the animals grew in cyclical spurts rather than continuously. However, their bone growth was extremely rapid, a feature unique to this group, Apaldetti says. â€œThey grew in a cyclical but extremely accelerated growth, at a speed even higher than that of the giants that grew continuously.â€</p><p>Like later sauropods, <em>I. prima</em> and <em>L. sauropoides</em> also appear to have had a birdlike respiratory system, the researchers found. Air sacs within the animalsâ€™ vertebrae provided large reserves of oxygenated air, helped keep their bodies cool despite their large size, and lightened the weight of their vertebrae.</p><p>Martin Sander, a vertebrate paleontologist at UniversitÃ¤t-Bonn in Germany, says that <em>I. prima</em> presents the best proof yet that these sauropodomorphs had this birdlike respiratory system, a fact that wasnâ€™t previously determined. However, he says he is not convinced that the Lessemsauridae were on a separate track toward gigantism. â€œFor me, itâ€™s more of an intermediate stage,â€ Sander says.</p><p>That sentiment is echoed by Jeffrey Wilson, a vertebrate paleontologist at the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor. Lessemsauridae bone growth was cyclical, but that doesnâ€™t necessarily mean the cycles were seasonal; there may have been long time lags in between growth spurts, part of a transition to more sauropod-like growth patterns, Wilson says. â€œOne of the things I think future work will do is help resolve the ambiguity over whether the Lessemsauridae were taking their own adventure into gigantism.â€</p><p>The Lessemsauridae may have developed their growth strategy some 30 million years earlier than Jurassic sauropods, such as <em>Brachiosaurus</em> and <em>Diplodocus</em>, Apaldetti notes. But ultimately, the Jurassic giants â€œwere more successful,â€ she says â€” they outweighed the sauropodomorphs by as much as 60 tons, and outlasted them by tens of millions of years.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>C. Apaldetti <em>et al</em>. <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41559-018-0599-y">An early trend towards gigantism in Triassic sauropodomorph dinosaurs</a>. <em>Nature Ecology and Evolution</em>. Published online July 9, 2018. doi:10.1038/s41559-018-0599-y.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>M. Rosen. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/new-analysis-cuts-massive-dino%E2%80%99s-weight-half">New analysis cuts massive dinoâ€™s weight in half</a>. Science News Online, June 9, 2015.</p><p>M. Rosen. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/world%E2%80%99s-largest-dinosaur-discovered">Worldâ€™s largest dinosaur discovered</a>. Science News Online, September 4, 2014.</p><p>A. Yeager. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/science-ticker/fragments-long-bodied-dino-found-argentina">Fragments of long-bodied dino found in Argentina</a>. Science News Online, May 15, 2014.</p><p>S. Perkins. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/small-ancestor-giant-sauropods-unearthed">Small ancestor of giant sauropods unearthed</a>. Science News Online, November 10, 2009.</p><p>S. Perkins. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/dinosaur-neck-size-reaches-new-extreme">Dinosaur neck size reaches new extreme</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 169, April 29, 2006, p. 270.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Long-necked dinosaurs grew to be giants in more ways than one" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(6, 'Congratulations to Intel ISEF 2018 Winners!', '', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sponsored/congratulations-intel-isef-2018-winners?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'congratulations-intel-isef-2018-winners', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/2018%20Intel%20ISEF%20Top%20Three%20.jpg', '     <div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/2018%20Intel%20ISEF%20Top%20Three%20.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/2018%20Intel%20ISEF%20Top%20Three%20.jpg" width="840" height="583" alt="Intel ISEF 2018 top three (from left): Meghana Bollimpalli, Oliver Nicholls, and Dhruvik Parikh celebrate in Pittsburgh." /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/2018%20Intel%20ISEF%20Top%20Three%20.jpg" width="840" height="583" alt="Intel ISEF 2018 top three (from left): Meghana Bollimpalli, Oliver Nicholls, and Dhruvik Parikh celebrate in Pittsburgh." /></noscript></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Intel ISEF 2018 top three (from left): Meghana Bollimpalli, Oliver Nicholls, and Dhruvik Parikh celebrate in Pittsburgh. Photo courtesy of Society for Science &amp; the Public/Chris Ayers Photography.</p></div></div></div><span property="dc:title" content="Congratulations to Intel ISEF 2018 Winners!" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span><p><img alt="Oliver Nicholls, 19, of Sydney, Australia, with his award-winning autonomous robotic window-cleaner prototype." class="caption" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/ROBO053_Nicholls_Oliver_Australia_09_KR.jpg" style="width: 840px; height: 559px;" title="Oliver Nicholls, 19, of Sydney, Australia, with his award-winning autonomous robotic window-cleaner prototype. ~~  Photo courtesy of Society for Science &amp; the Public/Chris Ayers Photography." /></p><p>At this year&rsquo;s Intel International Science and Engineering Fair (ISEF), <strong>Oliver Nicholls</strong>, 19, of Sydney, Australia, was awarded first place for designing and building a prototype of an autonomous robotic window cleaner for commercial buildings. In essence, a flying dronelike device is tethered to the roof of a building and equipped with a powerful spray nozzle and rotating scrubbers. The $2,300 device can withstand 28-mile-per-hour winds and could replace traditional methods that can exceed $11,000 per cleaning, as well as reduce injuries in this high-risk occupation. Nicholls received the Gordon E. Moore Award of $75,000, named in honor of the Intel cofounder and fellow scientist.</p><p><strong><img alt="Meghana Bollimpalli, 17, of Little Rock, Ark., with her project board during the Intel ISEF 2018 Public Day." class="caption" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/CHEM025_Bollimpalli_Meghana_USA_54_KR.jpg" style="width: 840px; height: 559px;" title="Meghana Bollimpalli, 17, of Little Rock, Ark., with her project board during the Intel ISEF 2018 Public Day. ~~  Photo courtesy of Society for Science &amp; the Public/Chris Ayers Photography." />Meghana Bollimpalli</strong>, 17, of Little Rock, Ark., received one of two Intel Foundation Young Scientist Awards of $50,000 for her novel, low-cost approach for synthesizing materials that could greatly cut the production and energy costs of making electrodes for devices like supercapacitors. She found that combining common substances like tea and molasses with nitrogen and phosphorus in a commercial microwave formed a powder that could be used as a coating for electrode-like materials, giving the materials properties similar to more expensive metals like platinum.</p><p><img alt="Dhruvik Parikh, 18, of Bothell, Wash., with his project board during the Intel ISEF 2018 Public Day. " class="caption" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/EGCH022_Parikh_Dhruvik_USA_36_KR.jpg" style="width: 840px; height: 559px;" title="Dhruvik Parikh, 18, of Bothell, Wash., with his project board during the Intel ISEF 2018 Public Day. ~~  Photo courtesy of Society for Science &amp; the Public/Chris Ayers Photography." /></p><p><strong>Dhruvik Parikh</strong>, 18, of Bothell, Wash., received the other Intel Foundation Young Scientist Award of $50,000 for his development of less expensive yet more robust ion exchange membranes for use in large, industrial-scale batteries for storing solar- or wind-generated electricity for later distribution. His composite membrane has 10 times the proton conductivity of the industry&rsquo;s standard membrane, while reducing production costs by about 30 percent.</p><p>Intel ISEF is a program of Society for Science &amp; the Public and is the world&rsquo;s largest international pre-college science competition. This year&rsquo;s competition featured nearly 1,800 young scientists selected from 420 affiliate fairs in 81 countries, regions and territories. In addition to the top winners, approximately 600 finalists received awards and prizes for their innovative research, including 22 &ldquo;Best of Category&rdquo; winners, who each received a $5,000 prize in addition to a $3,000 first-place award. The Intel Foundation also awarded a $1,000 grant to each winner&rsquo;s school and to the affiliated fair that the winner represented.</p><p>View the full list of Grand Award winners at <a href="http://www.societyforscience.org/2018-ISEF-Winners">www.societyforscience.org/2018-ISEF-Winners</a>.</p>  '),
(7, 'Surprise! This shark looks like a male on the outside, but itâ€™s made babies', 'Bigeye houndsharks found off Indiaâ€™s coast had female reproductive systems', 'Yao-Hua Law', '2018-07-10', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/surprise-shark-looks-male-outside-its-made-babies?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'surprise-shark-looks-male-outside-its-made-babies', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Bigeye houndsharks found off Indiaâ€™s coast had female reproductive systems</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-0958dfcfc4217024665f70e6cd02e916">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/yao-hua-law">Yao-Hua Law</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">10:00am, July 10, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="Male bigeye houndshark" title="BOY BITSÂ  Male bigeye houndsharks have reproductive organs called claspers on their underbellies (inset), which have always been an easy way to distinguish them from females. ~~ R. Hariprasath" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="Male bigeye houndshark" title="BOY BITSÂ  Male bigeye houndsharks have reproductive organs called claspers on their underbellies (inset), which have always been an easy way to distinguish them from females. ~~ R. Hariprasath" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>BOY BITS</strong>Â  Male bigeye houndsharks have reproductive organs called claspers on their underbellies (inset), which have always been an easy way to distinguish them from females.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>R. Hariprasath</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Itâ€™s easy to tell a male from a female shark. Flip it over. If it has a pair of claspers â€” finger-like extensions jutting from the end of the pelvic fins â€” it is male; no claspers means female. Like a penis, claspers deliver sperm inside the female.</p><p>That was marine biologist Alissa Barnesâ€™ understanding until she dissected seven bigeye houndsharks (<em>Iago omanesis</em>) with claspers and found a complete female reproductive system in each. <a href="http://programme.exordo.com/imcc5/delegates/presentation/477/">None of the seven sharks had any internal male sex organs</a>. Six were pregnant. Barnes, of the Dakshin Foundation, shared her findings June 25 at the 5<sup>th</sup> International Marine Conservation Congress in Kuching, Sarawak, Malaysia.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_inline1_730.jpg" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_inline1_730.jpg" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 436px;" title="&lt;b&gt;SURPRISE&lt;/b&gt;  This hermaphrodite sharks had its digestive tract removed to expose reproductive organs. This shark had external claspers, a male-specific sexual organ, but also ovaries (red disks) with eggs inside, plus several pups (two shown at arrows). ~~ R. Hariprasath " /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_inline1_730.jpg" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 436px;" title="&lt;b&gt;SURPRISE&lt;/b&gt;  This hermaphrodite sharks had its digestive tract removed to expose reproductive organs. This shark had external claspers, a male-specific sexual organ, but also ovaries (red disks) with eggs inside, plus several pups (two shown at arrows). ~~ R. Hariprasath " /></noscript> </div> <p>Barnes stumbled upon these hermaphrodite sharks at a port in Odhisa in eastern India in 2017. She was surveying local fishers to see if <a href="http://programme.exordo.com/imcc5/delegates/presentation/582/">changes in their practices might explain a decline in hauls of sharks and rays</a>. When she checked what the fishing vessels brought in, Barnes noticed two oddities. Male bigeye houndsharks greatly outnumbered females. And though males of this deepwater species are smaller than females, she saw immature males as large as female adults. Sensing something amiss, she took some sharks back to her lab for dissection.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_inline2_370.jpg" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_inline2_370.jpg" alt="" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 250px; height: 291px;" title="&lt;b&gt;SHARK INVESTIGATOR&lt;/b&gt;  Marine biologist Alissa Barnes found hermaphrodite sharks off Indiaâ€™s northeast coast and intends to figure out why. ~~ R. Hariprasath " /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/070318_YHL_hermaphrodite-sharks_inline2_370.jpg" alt="" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 250px; height: 291px;" title="&lt;b&gt;SHARK INVESTIGATOR&lt;/b&gt;  Marine biologist Alissa Barnes found hermaphrodite sharks off Indiaâ€™s northeast coast and intends to figure out why. ~~ R. Hariprasath " /></noscript> </div> â€œI was amazed,â€ says Barnes, who admits she squealed during the dissections. Even before opening the fish, she had pressed on the bellies of the "male"Â sharks and felt the pups inside.<p>â€œHermaphroditism is very uncommon in sharks,â€ says shark biologist Colin Simpdendorfer of James Cook University in Townsville, Australia. He calls Barnesâ€™ seven hermaphrodite sharks â€œone of the most unusual cases we have heard ofâ€ and says itâ€™s an obvious developmental anomaly. Scientists can still use claspers to identify male sharks, Simpdendorfer assures.</p><p>Barnesâ€™ finding isnâ€™t the first among sharks. A 2005 study in the <em>Journal of Fish Biology</em> reported <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/j.0022-1112.2005.00607.x">68 hermaphrodites among 80 longhead catsharks</a> (<em>Apristurus longicephalus</em>) from the Pacific and Indian Oceans. And surveys in the 1990s of bigeye houndsharks found more than 20 hermaphrodites among more than 60 sharks down the coast from where Barnes found hers.</p><p>With these other finds, Barnes is convinced â€œthere is something going onâ€ with the sharks. She suspects it might be pollutants in the water or hormonal changes â€” human-caused or otherwise â€” and is keen find out.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>A. Barnes, M. Manoharakrishnan and N. Namboothri. <a href="http://programme.exordo.com/imcc5/delegates/presentation/582/">Detecting drastic declines in a poor elasmobranch fisheries region</a>. 5<sup>th</sup> International Marine Conservation Congress, Kuching, Sarawak, Malaysia, June 27, 2018.</p><p>A. Barnes, R.W. Jabado and N. Namboothri. <a href="http://programme.exordo.com/imcc5/delegates/presentation/477/">Elasmobranchs through the looking glass</a>. 5<sup>th</sup> International Marine Conservation Congress, Kuching, Sarawak, Malaysia, June 25, 2018.Â </p><p>S. P. Iglesias, D.Y. Sellos and K. Nakaya. <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/j.0022-1112.2005.00607.x">â€œDiscovery of a normal hermaphroditic chondrichthyan species:Â Apristrus longicephalus.â€</a> <em>Journal of Fish Biology</em>. Vol. 66, February 2005, p. 417. doi: 10.1111/j.0022-1112.2005.00607.x.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>S. Milius.Â <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/hermaphrodite-wildflower-has-its-own-battle-sexes">Hermaphrodite wildflower has its own battle of the sexes</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 192, August 5, 3017, p. 10.Â </p><p>S. Milius.Â <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/battle-hermaphrodites">Battle of the hermaphrodites</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 170, September 16, 2006, p. 186.Â </p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Surprise! This shark looks like a male on the outside, but itâ€™s made babies" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(8, 'Why humans, and Big Macs, depend on bees', 'Thor Hanson talks about his new book, Buzz', 'Erika Engelhaupt', '2018-07-08', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/why-humans-and-big-macs-depend-bees?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'why-humans-and-big-macs-depend-bees', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/072118_reviews_bee_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Thor Hanson talks about his new book, <em>Buzz</em></h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-f9d24d781c16360b6dbb21cff99d0ead">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/erika-engelhaupt">Erika Engelhaupt</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">8:00am, July 8, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/072118_reviews_bee_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/072118_reviews_bee_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/072118_reviews_bee_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="a bee on a flower" title="SWARM OF BEESÂ  Honeybees may be the most famous of their kind, but there are more than 20,000 species of bees, including more than 250 bumblebees. ~~ Eric Harrison/Flickr (CC BY-SA 2.0)" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/072118_reviews_bee_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="a bee on a flower" title="SWARM OF BEESÂ  Honeybees may be the most famous of their kind, but there are more than 20,000 species of bees, including more than 250 bumblebees. ~~ Eric Harrison/Flickr (CC BY-SA 2.0)" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/072118_reviews_bee_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>SWARM OF BEESÂ  </strong>Honeybees may be the most famous of their kind, but there are more than 20,000 species of bees, including more than 250 bumblebees.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Eric Harrison/Flickr (<a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0/">CC BY-SA 2.0</a>)</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-c4517dc623981655a94d13722ca7f5df">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">       </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p><a href="https://amzn.to/2MUxBIm"><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/072118_reviews_buzz_cover.jpg" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/072118_reviews_buzz_cover.jpg" alt="" style="float: left; width: 120px; height: 177px;" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/072118_reviews_buzz_cover.jpg" alt="" style="float: left; width: 120px; height: 177px;" /></noscript> </div> Buzz: The Nature and Necessity of Bees</a><br /><em>Thor Hanson</em><br /><em>Basic Books, $27</em></p><p>When you hear the word <em>bee</em>, the image that pops to mind is probably a honeybee. Maybe a bumblebee. But for conservation biologist Thor Hanson, author of the new book <em>Buzz</em>, the world is abuzz with thousands of kinds of bees, each as beautiful and intriguing as the flowers on which they land.</p><p>Speaking from his â€œraccoon shackâ€ on San Juan Island in Washington â€” a backyard shed converted to an office and bee-watching space, and named for its previous inhabitants â€” Hanson shares what heâ€™s learned about how bees helped drive human evolution, the amazing birds that lead people to honey, and what a Big Mac would look like without bees. The following conversation has been edited for length and clarity.Â </p><p><b>SN: This bee book is unusual â€” it isnâ€™t mainly about honeybees. Why did you write about lesser-known bees?</b></p><p><strong>Hanson:</strong> I made a deliberate decision because I thought the celebrity bees, the honeybees, would steal the show. It was high time to turn a stage light onto these 20,000 other species of bees, which have habits that are less familiar but just as fascinating. For example, most people think of hives when they think of bees, but actually most bees are solitary.</p><p><b>SN: You write that this book is an â€œexploration of how the very nature of bees makes them so utterly necessary.â€ So letâ€™s cut to the chase: Why are bees necessary?</b></p><p><strong>Hanson:</strong> First is the deep connection between bees and flowering plants. Theyâ€™ve had a partnership from an early stage; each spurs the other in terms of diversity. Itâ€™s an incredible role that bees have played in shaping the natural world. Theyâ€™re also important to our lifestyle, first for their role in the human diet. Itâ€™s often said that one of every three bites of food depends on bees.</p><p>But there are all these other connections that we donâ€™t think about: Bees have provided light from beeswax candles and sweetness from honey. Early industrial uses of wax included making bronze sculptures with wax molds, batiks in Indonesia and wax tablets to write on.</p><p>You can trace our relationship with bees back not hundreds, but <em>hundreds of thousands</em> of years. The role of honey in the human diet goes back into prehistory. That source of sugar may have even helped fuel the expansion of our brain size. It may have helped us become who we are.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/072118_reviews_buzz_inline_hanson_REV.jpg" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/072118_reviews_buzz_inline_hanson_REV.jpg" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 548px; float: right;" title="&lt;b&gt;BEE WHISPERER&lt;/b&gt;  Thor Hanson, shown here catching bees for identification, wants people to appreciate the diversity and importance of bees.  ~~ Noah Hanson" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/072118_reviews_buzz_inline_hanson_REV.jpg" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 548px; float: right;" title="&lt;b&gt;BEE WHISPERER&lt;/b&gt;  Thor Hanson, shown here catching bees for identification, wants people to appreciate the diversity and importance of bees.  ~~ Noah Hanson" /></noscript> </div> <p><b>SN: One of the most astonishing examples of our relationship with bees has to do with a bird called the honeyguide. Tell me about that.</b></p><p><strong>Hanson:</strong>Â <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/humans-birds-communicate-collaborate">Hunter-gatherers in Africa follow this bird to beesâ€™ nests</a>, and have for generations (<em>SN: 8/20/16, p. 10</em>). The honeyguide is very good at locating a hive. But on its own, it canâ€™t access the nest. So once it locates one, the next thing it does is look for people. It hops around on branches and makes a piercing cry to get attention, then leads a person to the honey. People climb the tree or dig out the nest, and honeyguides feed on the remains.</p><p>Whatâ€™s funny is how long it took biologists to figure out this relationship. The original explanation was that the honeyguide coevolved with the honey badger, which also raids nests for honey. Then a biologist pointed out that badgers are nocturnal, and the birds arenâ€™t. Also, no one has ever seen a honeyguide leading a badger. It makes more sense that the relationship evolved on the savannah with people out looking for honey every day.</p><p><b>SN: One of the bookâ€™s most hilariously geeky moments is when you go to McDonaldâ€™s and pick apart a Big Mac. Why did you do that?</b></p><p><strong>Hanson:</strong> I wanted to look for the significance of bees in an unexpected place. And you donâ€™t think of bees when you go into McDonaldâ€™s â€” you just donâ€™t! I didnâ€™t care how much people stared. I sat there with my tweezers, pulling all the seeds off the bun. I ended up with one pile you could have without bees [meat and bun] and one you couldnâ€™t [including not only the veggies, but also the cheese and special sauce]. We could still eat, but it would be pretty dull.</p><p><b>SN: Youâ€™re worried about bees. Why?</b></p><p><strong>Hanson:</strong> Itâ€™s the four pâ€™s: pesticides, pathogens, parasites and poor nutrition. Poor nutrition is one that people donâ€™t think of. We ship honeybees all over the place, and they get force-fed almond blossoms for three weeks, then theyâ€™re packed onto trucks and shipped off to pollinate apples. Itâ€™s not a healthy lifestyle, and not a varied diet.</p><p><b>SN: You say that bees are one of the few insects that inspire fondness instead of fear. Why do you think that is? </b></p><p><strong>Hanson:</strong> Bees have been with us from the beginning. Our primordial sweet tooth led us to follow these creatures, then we domesticated bees very early on, setting out hives and reusing good sites in baobab trees. I think we have a very deep connection to these creatures.</p><p><em>Buy </em><a href="https://amzn.to/2MUxBIm">Buzz: The Nature and Necessity of Bees</a><em> from Amazon.com. </em>Science News<em> is a participant in the Amazon Services LLC Associates Program. Please see our <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/frequently-asked-questions#amazon">FAQ</a> for more details.</em></p></span></div></div></div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Why humans, and Big Macs, depend on bees" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        ');
INSERT INTO `news` (`id`, `title`, `subtitle`, `author`, `date`, `url`, `slug`, `image`, `content`) VALUES
(9, 'Soaring spiders may get cues from electric charges in the air', 'In a lab test, arachnids did preflight maneuvers when an electric field was switched on', 'Laurel Hamers', '2018-07-05', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/soaring-spiders-may-get-cues-electric-charges-air?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'soaring-spiders-may-get-cues-electric-charges-air', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_LH_ballooning-spiders_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>In a lab test, arachnids did preflight maneuvers when an electric field was switched on</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-8ccdbbbf643ce7143f181df617b91be3">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/laurel-hamers">Laurel Hamers</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">4:48pm, July 5, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_LH_ballooning-spiders_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_LH_ballooning-spiders_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_LH_ballooning-spiders_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="spider in &quot;tiptoe stance&quot; " title="TIPPY TOESÂ  Before ballooning into the breeze, spiders adopt the â€œtiptoe stanceâ€ seen here, and release silk threads. New research suggests that spiders can sense electric fields and perhaps use them as a cue to balloon. ~~ Michael HutchinsonÂ " /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_LH_ballooning-spiders_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="spider in &quot;tiptoe stance&quot; " title="TIPPY TOESÂ  Before ballooning into the breeze, spiders adopt the â€œtiptoe stanceâ€ seen here, and release silk threads. New research suggests that spiders can sense electric fields and perhaps use them as a cue to balloon. ~~ Michael HutchinsonÂ " /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_LH_ballooning-spiders_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>TIPPY TOES</strong>Â  Before ballooning into the breeze, spiders adopt the â€œtiptoe stanceâ€ seen here, and release silk threads. New research suggests that spiders can sense electric fields and perhaps use them as a cue to balloon.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Michael HutchinsonÂ </p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Spiders may lack wings, but they arenâ€™t confined to the ground. Under the right conditions, some spider species will climb to a high point, release silk strands to form a parachute, and float away on the breeze. Buoyed by air currents, theyâ€™ve been known to <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/long-ignored-high-flying-arthropods-could-make-largest-land-migrations">drift kilometers above Earthâ€™s surface</a>, and even to cross oceans to reach new habitats (<em>SN: 2/4/17, p. 12</em>).</p><p>Now, new research suggests air isnâ€™t the only force behind this flight, called ballooning. Spiders can <a href="https://www.cell.com/current-biology/fulltext/S0960-9822(18)30693-6">sense electrical charges in Earthâ€™s atmosphere</a>, and the forces exerted by these charges might be a cue for them to alight, researchers suggest July 5 in <em>Current Biology</em>. That invisible signal could help explain why spidersâ€™ take-off timing seem a bit, well, flighty. Some days, arachnids balloon en masse; other days, they remain firmly grounded despite similar weather conditions.</p><p>Spiders with atmospheric aspirations do need a gentle breeze with speeds below around 11 kilometers per hour, past studies have shown. But those speeds alone shouldnâ€™t be strong enough to get some of the larger species of ballooning spiders off the ground, says Erica Morley, a sensory biologist at the University of Bristol in England.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_LH_ballooning-spiders_inline_730.jpg" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_LH_ballooning-spiders_inline_730.jpg" alt="a scanning electron microscope image of the fine hairs on a spider leg" class="caption" style="width: 400px; height: 315px; float: right;" title="&lt;b&gt;GOOD HAIR DAY  &lt;/b&gt;Fine hairs on spidersâ€™ legs respond to moving air and, new research shows, the presence of an electric field. A scanning electron microscope image shows these hairs close up. ~~ E.L. Morley and D. Robert/&lt;em&gt;Curr Bio&lt;/em&gt; 2018" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/070318_LH_ballooning-spiders_inline_730.jpg" alt="a scanning electron microscope image of the fine hairs on a spider leg" class="caption" style="width: 400px; height: 315px; float: right;" title="&lt;b&gt;GOOD HAIR DAY  &lt;/b&gt;Fine hairs on spidersâ€™ legs respond to moving air and, new research shows, the presence of an electric field. A scanning electron microscope image shows these hairs close up. ~~ E.L. Morley and D. Robert/&lt;em&gt;Curr Bio&lt;/em&gt; 2018" /></noscript> </div> So scientists have long wondered if some other force might be involved: Perhaps electrical charges in Earthâ€™s atmosphere push against the silken threads of airborne spidersâ€™ silk streamers to help them stay fanned out in a parachute. These electric charges form an electric field that attracts or repels other charged objects or particles. It varies in strength, becoming stronger around objects such as leaves and branches on trees, and also fluctuating with meteorological conditions.<p>In the first experimental test of whether spiders can sense these electric charges, Morley and Bristol sensory biologist Daniel Robert blocked out naturally occurring electric fields in a lab. They then created an artificial one mimicking what would-be arthropod aerialists would experience, and placed teeny-tiny spiders from the Linyphiidae family into that faux field. Under the electric field, even with no breeze, the spiders perched on the tips of their legs, a ballerina-like behavior that precedes ballooning. When the researchers switched off the artificial electric field, the behavior (which scientists call the â€œtiptoe stanceâ€) subsided.</p><p>Tiny hairs on the spidersâ€™ bodies react to both moving air and an electric fieldâ€™s presence, but differently, Morley found. The hairs stood on end as long as air was blowing on them. But when faced with an electric field, they stood on end most dramatically when the field was switched on and then gradually deflated to their resting position over about 30 seconds.</p><p>The study links the pre-ballooning tiptoeing behavior to the presence of an electric field, but actually taking off might require something more, suggests Moonsung Cho, an aerodynamics researcher at the Technical University of Berlin who wasnâ€™t involved in the study. While some spiders in the study did incidentally float away, that liftoff behavior wasnâ€™t actually measured.</p><p>And responding to electric fields probably isnâ€™t the full story when it comes take-off timing: A different genus of spider, <em>Xysticus</em>, or ground crab spiders, appears to sense wind speed with its legs before going aloft, <a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.2004405">wiggling one spindly appendage around to sense moving air</a> and determine whether wind conditions are favorable for lift-off, Choâ€™s team reported June 14 in <em>PLOS Biology</em>.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>E. Morley and D. Robert. <a href="https://www.cell.com/current-biology/fulltext/S0960-9822(18)30693-6">Electric fields elicit ballooning in spiders</a>. <em>Current Biology.</em> Vol. 28. July 23, 2018. doi:10.1016/j.cub.2018/05.057.</p><p>M. Cho. <a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.2004405">An observational study of ballooning in large spiders: Nanoscale multifibers enable large spidersâ€™ soaring flight</a>. <em>PLOS Biology</em>. Published online June 14, 2018. doi:10.1371/journal.pbio.2004405.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/long-ignored-high-flying-arthropods-could-make-largest-land-migrations">Long-ignored, high-flying arthropods could make up largest land migrations</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 191, February 4, 2017, p. 12.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Soaring spiders may get cues from electric charges in the air" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(10, 'North Americaâ€™s earliest dogs came from Siberia', '', 'Bruce Bower', '2018-07-05', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/science-ticker/north-america-earliest-dogs-came-siberia?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'north-america-earliest-dogs-came-siberia', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/blogposts/070518_bb_dog_ticker_feat_free.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-openpublish-related-content view-id-openpublish_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-247ff4638391d945594b8ba8f77d5b17">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-profile-photo">        <div class="field-content"><a href="/author/bruce-bower"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/styles/author_thumbnail/public/profiles/photos/BB_250.jpg?itok=PPpB8TYp" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/styles/author_thumbnail/public/profiles/photos/BB_250.jpg?itok=PPpB8TYp" width="50" height="50" alt="Bruce Bower" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/styles/author_thumbnail/public/profiles/photos/BB_250.jpg?itok=PPpB8TYp" width="50" height="50" alt="Bruce Bower" /></noscript></a></div>  </div>     <div class="views-field views-field-title">    <span class="views-label views-label-title">by</span>    <span class="field-content">  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/bruce-bower">Bruce Bower</a></span> </div> </span>  </div>     <div class="views-field views-field-published-at">        <span class="field-content">2:12pm, July 5, 2018</span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/blogposts/070518_bb_dog_ticker_feat_free.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/blogposts/070518_bb_dog_ticker_feat_free.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/blogposts/070518_bb_dog_ticker_feat_free.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="dog " title="LOST DOGSÂ  An ancient DNA study indicates that people brought dogs to North America at least 10,000 years ago. Modern American dogs share little ancestry with these ancient fidos, researchers say.Â Â  ~~ mujipanda/pixabay" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/blogposts/070518_bb_dog_ticker_feat_free.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="dog " title="LOST DOGSÂ  An ancient DNA study indicates that people brought dogs to North America at least 10,000 years ago. Modern American dogs share little ancestry with these ancient fidos, researchers say.Â Â  ~~ mujipanda/pixabay" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/blogposts/070518_bb_dog_ticker_feat_free.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>LOST DOGS</strong>Â  An ancient DNA study indicates that people brought dogs to North America at least 10,000 years ago. Modern American dogs share little ancestry with these ancient fidos, researchers say.Â Â </p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>mujipanda/pixabay</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-blog-post-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-blog-post-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-blog-post-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>North Americaâ€™s first dogs arrived with humans who crossed a land bridge from Northeast Asia around 10,000 years ago or earlier, an analysis of ancient dogsâ€™ DNA suggests.</p><p><a href="http://science.sciencemag.org/cgi/doi/10.1126/science.aao4776">Those early American dogs derived from a Siberian ancestor, not North American wolves</a> as some researchers have presumed, an international team reports in the July 6 <em>Science</em>. Genetic traces of ancient American dogs have nearly vanished from present-day pooches, possibly because European colonists selectively bred their own dogs starting around 500 years ago.</p><p>Researchers reached that conclusion based on analyses of 71 mitochondrial genomes and seven nuclear genomes of dogs excavated at ancient North American and Siberian sites. Those data were compared with DNA from modern dogs and wolves.</p><p><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/dogs-lived-and-died-humans-10000-years-ago-americas">Read more about the origins of the New Worldâ€™s first dogs</a>.</p></span></div></div></div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="North Americaâ€™s earliest dogs came from Siberia" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>                    '),
(11, 'Researchers create hybrid embryos of endangered white rhinos', 'The first-time feat offers a tiny glimmer of hope for saving the northern white rhinoceros', 'Leah Rosenbaum', '2018-07-04', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/researchers-create-hybrid-embryos-endangered-white-rhinos?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'researchers-create-hybrid-embryos-endangered-white-rhinos', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/060318_LR_rhino-embryo_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>The first-time feat offers a tiny glimmer of hope for saving the northern white rhinoceros</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-414e92cbb895abdb82e50d0e22daeefd">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/leah-rosenbaum">Leah Rosenbaum</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">2:50pm, July 4, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/060318_LR_rhino-embryo_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/060318_LR_rhino-embryo_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/060318_LR_rhino-embryo_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="white rhino" title="VANISHING ACT Â These two female northern white rhinos, seen here at the Ol Pejeta Conservancy in Kenya, are the only living members of their subspecies. ~~ J. Stejskal/Safari Park DvÅ¯r KrÃ¡lovÃ©" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/060318_LR_rhino-embryo_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="white rhino" title="VANISHING ACT Â These two female northern white rhinos, seen here at the Ol Pejeta Conservancy in Kenya, are the only living members of their subspecies. ~~ J. Stejskal/Safari Park DvÅ¯r KrÃ¡lovÃ©" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/060318_LR_rhino-embryo_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>VANISHING ACT</strong> Â These two female northern white rhinos, seen here at the Ol Pejeta Conservancy in Kenya, are the only living members of their subspecies.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>J. Stejskal/Safari Park DvÅ¯r KrÃ¡lovÃ©</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>The nearly extinct northern white rhino may not be completely lost.</p><p>For the first time, <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-018-04959-2">rhinoceros embryos have been made in the lab</a>. Scientists injected preserved sperm from a male northern white rhino into eggs of female southern white rhinos, a closely related subspecies. The embryos were incubated until the cells begin to differentiate, a stage at which they can be implanted into a surrogate mother, researchers report July 4 in <em>Nature Communications</em>.</p><p>The new feat is â€œone of the really crucial stepsâ€ to eventually producing new rhino calves, says study coauthor Jan Stejskal, coordinator of northern white rhino conservation efforts at the Safari Park DvÅ¯r KrÃ¡lovÃ© in the Czech Republic. Eventually, researchers hope to implant similar embryos into female southern white rhinos or hybrid northern-southern white rhinos.</p><p>If it works, it could provide hope for bringing back a species on the brink of extinction. Sudan, the last male northern white rhino, died in March. Only two females remain in Kenya, both in captivity and unable to reproduce naturally. In comparison, there are more than 20,000 southern white rhinos left.</p><p>In the new study, the scientists used eggs from female southern white rhinos and sperm preserved from three male northern white rhinos. While the new embryos are a hybridized northern-southern white rhino mix, the ability to create them is â€œa saving mechanism for the genes of the northern white rhinos,â€ says study coauthor Thomas Hildebrandt, a reproduction biologist at the Leibniz Institute for Zoo and Wildlife Research in Berlin.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/060318_LR_rhino-embryo_inline_730.jpg" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/060318_LR_rhino-embryo_inline_730.jpg" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 360px;" title="&lt;b&gt;INCOMING&lt;/b&gt;  A scientist uses artificial reproductive technology to inject a northern white rhino sperm cell into a southern white rhino egg, creating one of the first rhino embryos in a lab. ~~ T. Hildebrandt &lt;em&gt;et al&lt;/em&gt;/&lt;em&gt;Nature Communications&lt;/em&gt; 2018" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/060318_LR_rhino-embryo_inline_730.jpg" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 360px;" title="&lt;b&gt;INCOMING&lt;/b&gt;  A scientist uses artificial reproductive technology to inject a northern white rhino sperm cell into a southern white rhino egg, creating one of the first rhino embryos in a lab. ~~ T. Hildebrandt &lt;em&gt;et al&lt;/em&gt;/&lt;em&gt;Nature Communications&lt;/em&gt; 2018" /></noscript> </div> <p>Hybrid rhinos, if they are ever born, could serve two purposes. They may be more compatible surrogate mothers for an eventual pure northern white rhino embryo since they will share more DNA with the babies. And theoretically, the hybrids could be selectively bred for the northern rhino genes, eventually creating a pure northern white rhino â€” a process that would take many generations and span multiple decades.</p><p>In a potentially quicker way to birth a pure northern white rhino, researchers plan to harvest eggs from the two remaining females and combine them with preserved northern white rhino sperm. If successful, a northern white rhino calf could be born within the next three years, Hildebrandt says.</p><p>Stem cell technology may play an important role in saving the rhinos, too. The team was able to derive pluripotent stem cells, which can turn into any cell in the body including eggs and sperm, from two pure southern white embryos. Hildebrandt says that there are 12 frozen cell lines from northern white rhinos, six of which are genetically distinct â€“ important for avoiding inbreeding. If researchers can turn these skin cells first into pluripotent stem cells and then eggs and sperm, it would be another way to create a pure northern white rhino embryo.</p><p>For now, other scientists caution against too much optimism. â€œSaving a species or a subspecies takes a lot more than the science,â€ says Terri Roth, an animal reproductive physiologist at the Cincinnati Zoo and Botanical Garden. Africa is in the midst of a rhino-poaching epidemic, she says. In 2013, poachers killed 13 rhinos; in 2017, over 1,000 were killed. Any <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/protecting-wildlife-legal-hunting-complicated-issue">efforts to reestablish the northern white rhino population</a> will need to address this crisis, she says (<em>SN Online: 12/16/13</em>).</p><p>Hildebrandt agrees. The northern white rhino didnâ€™t go extinct because it failed at evolution, he says, â€œit failed because it is not bulletproof.â€</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>T. Hildebrandt et al. <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-018-04959-2">Embryos and embryonic stem cells from the white rhinoceros</a>. <em>Nature Communications</em>. Published online July 4, 2018. doi:10.1038/s41467-018-04959-2.</p><p>T.L. Roth and W.F. Swanson. From petri dishes to politics â€“ a multi-pronged approach is essential for saving endangered species. <em>Nature Communications</em>. Published online July 4, 2018. doi: 10.1038/s41467-018-04962-7.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>S. Zielinski. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/protecting-wildlife-legal-hunting-complicated-issue">Protecting wildlife with legal hunting is a complicated issue</a>. Science News Online, December 16, 2013.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Researchers create hybrid embryos of endangered white rhinos  " class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(12, 'Conversations with Maya: Kristina Johnson', '', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sponsored/conversations-maya-kristina-johnson?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'conversations-maya-kristina-johnson', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/Clinton-Community-College.jpg', '     <div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/Clinton-Community-College.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/Clinton-Community-College.jpg" width="1000" height="750" alt="Kristina Johnson Chancellor, The State University of New York." /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/Clinton-Community-College.jpg" width="1000" height="750" alt="Kristina Johnson Chancellor, The State University of New York." /></noscript></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Chancellor Kristina Johnson visits the Institute for Advanced Manufacturing at Clinton Community College, a member of The State University of New York system. Photo courtesy of State University of New York.</p></div></div></div><span property="dc:title" content="Conversations with Maya: Kristina Johnson" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span><p>Maya Ajmera, President &amp; CEO of Society for Science &amp; the Public and Publisher of <em>Science News</em>, sat down to chat with Kristina Johnson, Chancellor of The State University of New York and an alumna of the International Science and Engineering Fair. We are thrilled to share an edited version of their conversation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>You&rsquo;re an alumna of the 1975 International Science and Engineering Fair. How did the competition impact your life and are there any particular moments that still stand out for you? </strong></p><p>It was an amazing experience. In 1975, I became fascinated by holograms &mdash; I just thought they were magic. Although holograms are everywhere now, at the time they were not that well known. [Note: Johnson&rsquo;s project title was &ldquo;Holographic Study of the Sporangiophore of <em>Phycomyces</em>.&rdquo;]</p><p>I ended up building a little lab in our basement and was able to reproduce the lab in my physics classroom at school. That&rsquo;s the year I experienced my first all-nighter. I stayed up all night at my high school the night before the science fair. It was a little controversial to say the least.</p><p>My project did well, and it was exciting. As a result, I think competing at ISEF gave me confidence and enthusiasm about science.</p><p>At the time, I was really not aware that it was unusual to be a woman in science. It wasn&rsquo;t until I went to college that I realized that it was unusual. That&rsquo;s where doing well at ISEF gave me confidence. When I was told I didn&rsquo;t belong, I could just think back to succeeding at ISEF.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><img alt="Kristina Johnson Chancellor, The State University of New York. Photo courtesy ofÂ State University of New York." class="caption" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/SUNY_CKJohnson_4287-Medium.jpg" style="width: 300px; height: 375px; float: left;" title="Kristina Johnson Chancellor, The State University of New York. ~~ Photo courtesy ofÂ State University of New York." />I understand your high school did not have a girls&rsquo; lacrosse team so you practiced with the boys. At Stanford University, you started a women&rsquo;s lacrosse team that became the varsity team. We still experience a gender gap in a variety of fields, from athletics to engineering. What strategies do you think are working and not working to close the gender gap? </strong></p><p>Obviously, the biggest improvement for gender equity in sports was passing Title IX, wherein it became important to open up these opportunities for girls and women. When I got to Stanford, I learned that we didn&rsquo;t have a lacrosse team and thought, well, we should start one. So, we did. Over the course of my nearly eight years at Stanford as an undergraduate and graduate student, it went from being a club sport to a club varsity sport. I think that&rsquo;s maybe part of the answer: Leaders need to take charge when they see an opportunity to build something new. [Note: On the 40th anniversary of Title IX in 2012, Johnson was recognized as a 40 For 40 honoree by espnW and other organizations. The 40 For 40 event honored &ldquo;women who have made an impact&rdquo; after participating in high school and college sports.]</p><p>When I went into science and engineering at Stanford, I didn&rsquo;t have any science or engineering faculty that were women. I only had two women professors in eight years. Only two, though I had terrific male faculty including my Ph.D. adviser, Joseph Goodman. When I graduated, I did not think that women were professors in science and engineering. I didn&rsquo;t really think too much about it. It just was the way it was. One of the things that I&rsquo;m not as happy about today is that there hasn&rsquo;t been a significant increase in the number of women pursuing engineering. That needs to change.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Drawing on your experiences as chancellor of the SUNY system, dean of engineering at Duke University, an entrepreneur and a high-level government appointee in the Obama administration, what particular challenges do you think are keeping women in the sciences back? </strong></p><p>In the early 1990s, the National Science Foundation did an interesting study that said women will pursue careers in science and engineering and stay in them if they can align their vocation with their avocation to help others.</p><p>I think the more that we humanize the field, the more attractive these careers will be to all individuals.</p><p>I also think part of it is that when women don&rsquo;t see role models in their classrooms, they don&rsquo;t know they can do it. I&rsquo;m very passionate about bringing underrepresented minorities and women into the professoriate and the academy so we can inspire a new generation of diverse leaders. I think part of it really is when you are &ldquo;other,&rdquo; it is important to feel welcome.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>You&rsquo;ve reportedly said that there are three things you would never do. One is be a dean, two is start a company and three is write a book. You&rsquo;ve done two out of three. I&rsquo;m curious as to what has motivated you to take different turns in your career. </strong></p><p>So, it is true. I did say I never wanted to be a dean. I never wanted to start a company. I didn&rsquo;t want to write a book. I actually haven&rsquo;t written a book yet, but I have a title for a book. I was thinking just yesterday I probably need to write it. So, stay tuned on that one.</p><p>I wanted to become a dean because leadership to me is common sense. I felt that if I could make the lives better for my fellow faculty members, that I could have a bigger impact and just make it better for all.</p><p>When I was a young professor, we established an engineering research center. I helped cowrite the grant. As part of the grant, there was an expectation that we were going to create a new workforce and new industries. I took that mission very seriously, which led me to leave academia and try to create those new companies, products, processes and a different kind of educated workforce.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Did you enjoy your time as undersecretary of energy at the U.S. Department of Energy? </strong></p><p>You know, I did like it. It was a very intense period of time. Maybe it was because we had to invest $37 billion in energy and environment investments from the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act in addition to the broad $11 billion energy and environment portfolio. It was an honor to work for the Department of Energy. Every single individual I worked with was committed. We worked every weekend, every evening, to try and get funding out, so that we could create jobs, put people back to work and lower our greenhouse gas emissions.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>While you were at Duke you created a fellowship that supported about a third of undergraduates so that they could spend 18 months doing research in labs. Are you thinking of similar things at SUNY, or are there any plans to partner with New York high schools to promote STEM education?</strong></p><p>When I was at Duke, I saw that a lot of our engineering students were going to New York to join the financial industry, which is fine. But I thought it also would be great to introduce our students to a broader array of opportunities.</p><p>The program, called the Pratt Research Fellows, has students start work in research labs during the spring of their junior year, including the summer and all during their senior year. When those kids graduated, they were going to the financial sector, but they were also going on to graduate schools. It was exciting because they really caught the bug of innovation. So, yes, I&rsquo;d like to start that at SUNY.</p><p>We&rsquo;re also very excited about trying to link SUNY with high schools. One of the exciting things about SUNY is it&rsquo;s the largest comprehensive university system in the country. We have high schools that we charter. We have 30 community colleges. We have 13 comprehensive, unique four-year institutions with master&rsquo;s programs. We have technical-focused two- and four-year schools. Then, we have 14 doctoral-granting degree institutions, including five medical schools and three hospitals.</p><p>During my first State of the University System Address, I discussed four themes across our broad intellectual ecosystem. First, innovation and entrepreneurship. The second, individualized education. Third, energy and sustainability, and fourth, partnerships. Creating programs where all of our students are doing research and innovation together &mdash; I think that is very exciting.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>What advice do you have for young people just starting their higher education or careers?</strong></p><p>Get everything you can out of it. I played sports. I &ldquo;hashed&rdquo; at the French house to keep up my French. I worked in the labs. When you start in higher ed, it&rsquo;s important to find an area that you can carve out outside the classroom. I recommend that students look up faculty with similar interests and make an appointment and ask to work with the faculty member as an independent study student.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>What books are you reading now? </strong></p><p>So, there&rsquo;s a book George Packer wrote called <em>The Unwinding</em>, which talks about Youngstown when Delphi left and the real estate crash in Tampa. It weaves through these characters that we all know that were living at the time in those communities. <em>Janesville </em>by Amy Goldstein is by my bedside along with <em>Seeing What Others Don&rsquo;t</em> by Gary Klein.</p>  ');
INSERT INTO `news` (`id`, `title`, `subtitle`, `author`, `date`, `url`, `slug`, `image`, `content`) VALUES
(13, 'Mongolians practiced horse dentistry as early as 3,200 years ago', 'Equine tooth extractions evolved to make way for a riding bit, making mounted warfare possible', 'Bruce Bower', '2018-07-02', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/mongolians-practiced-horse-dentistry-early-3200-years-ago?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'mongolians-practiced-horse-dentistry-early-3200-years-ago', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_BB_horse-dentistry_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Equine tooth extractions evolved to make way for a riding bit, making mounted warfare possible</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-0cc106b501affae44f27baab36609c4e">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/bruce-bower">Bruce Bower</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">3:00pm, July 2, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_BB_horse-dentistry_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_BB_horse-dentistry_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_BB_horse-dentistry_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="Mongolian herder" title="EXTRACTION ACTIONÂ  A Mongolian herder removes a first premolar tooth from a young horse using a screwdriver. Mongolian herders invented a comparable procedure nearly 2,800 years ago so that horses could safely hold metal bits in their mouths while being ridden, a new report concludes. ~~ Dimitri Staszewski" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_BB_horse-dentistry_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="Mongolian herder" title="EXTRACTION ACTIONÂ  A Mongolian herder removes a first premolar tooth from a young horse using a screwdriver. Mongolian herders invented a comparable procedure nearly 2,800 years ago so that horses could safely hold metal bits in their mouths while being ridden, a new report concludes. ~~ Dimitri Staszewski" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_BB_horse-dentistry_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><b>EXTRACTION ACTION</b>Â  A Mongolian herder removes a first premolar tooth from a young horse using a screwdriver. Mongolian herders invented a comparable procedure nearly 2,800 years ago so that horses could safely hold metal bits in their mouths while being ridden, a new report concludes.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Dimitri Staszewski</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Mongolian pastoralists were trying to remove troublesome teeth from horsesâ€™ mouths almost 3,200 years ago, making those mobile herders the <a href="http://www.pnas.org/cgi/doi/10.1073/pnas.1721189115">earliest known practitioners of horse dentistry</a>, a new study finds.</p><p>Those initial, incomplete tooth removals led to procedures for extracting forward-positioned cheek teeth known as first premolars from young horses, say archaeologist William Taylor and his colleagues. That dental practice, which dates to as early as about 2,800 years ago, coincided with the appearance in Mongolia of metal bits that made it easier for riders to control horses, the researchers report the week of July 2 in the <em>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences</em>. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/how-asian-nomadic-herders-built-new-bronze-age-cultures">Long-distance travel and mounted warfare</a> with sedentary civilizations across Asia soon followed (<em>SN: 11/25/17, p. 16</em>).</p><p>â€œVeterinary dentistry was instrumental in the rise of horse warfare on the Eurasian steppes, allowing herders to use metal bits while avoiding behavior and health complications for horses that may have accompanied bit use,â€ says Taylor, of the Max Planck Institute for the Science of Human History in Jena, Germany. In particular, first premolars could interfere with a bitâ€™s movement and cause pain or damage to the tooth.</p><p>Taylorâ€™s group identified microscopic signs of cutting and sawing on frontal teeth from two of 10 Bronze Age Mongolian horses. These two teeth, which date to between around 3,200 and 2,900 years ago, apparently grew at odd angles that may have interfered with chewing. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/ancient-dna-bucks-tale-how-horse-was-tamed">Horseback riding became widespread</a> in Mongolia at that time (<em>SN: 5/27/17, p. 10</em>).</p><p>Of seven Mongolian horses dating to between around 2,800 and 1,650 years ago that had empty first premolar jaw sockets, six displayed bone regrowth in those sockets indicating that teeth had been extracted or lost due to other causes before the animals died.</p><div class="inline-content inline-content-left clearfix" style="width:100%; float:none;"><h4>Tooth be gone</h4><p>Evidence of first premolar extraction appeared in an empty tooth socket, right (black arrow), of a Mongolian horse from between around 2,300 and 2,700 years ago. A Mongolian horse from roughly 3,000 years ago, left, retains its first premolar (white arrow), indicating that the dental procedure was not yet in use.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062918_BB_horse-dentistry_inline_730.jpg" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062918_BB_horse-dentistry_inline_730.jpg" alt="premolar extraction" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 312px;" title="~~ W.T.T. Taylor &lt;em&gt;et al&lt;/em&gt;/&lt;em&gt;PNAS&lt;/em&gt; 2018" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062918_BB_horse-dentistry_inline_730.jpg" alt="premolar extraction" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 312px;" title="~~ W.T.T. Taylor &lt;em&gt;et al&lt;/em&gt;/&lt;em&gt;PNAS&lt;/em&gt; 2018" /></noscript> </div> </div></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>W.T.T. Taylor <em>et al</em>. <a href="http://www.pnas.org/cgi/doi/10.1073/pnas.1721189115">Origins of equine dentistry</a>. <em>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences</em>. Published online the week of July 2, 2018. doi:10.1073/pnas.1721189115.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>B. Bower. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/how-asian-nomadic-herders-built-new-bronze-age-cultures">How ancient nomadic herders built new Bronze Age cultures</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 192, November 25, 2017, p. 16.</p><p>T.H. Saey. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/ancient-dna-bucks-tale-how-horse-was-tamed">Ancient DNA bucks tale of how the horse was tamed</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 191, May 27, 2017, p. 10.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Mongolians practiced horse dentistry as early as 3,200 years ago" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(14, 'Koala genome may contain clues for helping the species survive', 'The marsupialâ€™s numbers are declining in the Australian wilderness', 'Tina Hesman Saey', '2018-07-02', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/koala-genome-may-contain-clues-helping-species-survive?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'koala-genome-may-contain-clues-helping-species-survive', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_TS_koala-genome_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>The marsupialâ€™s numbers are declining in the Australian wilderness</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-edf263ff2fe5d5581bc2275dea8b0926">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/tina-hesman-saey">Tina Hesman Saey</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">11:00am, July 2, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_TS_koala-genome_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_TS_koala-genome_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_TS_koala-genome_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="koalas" title="KOALA CUTENESS Â A detailed look at koalasâ€™ newly mapped genome may help researchers understand why the animals are dropping in number in the wild. ~~ Robyn Cox/Flickr (CC BY-SA 2.0)" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_TS_koala-genome_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="koalas" title="KOALA CUTENESS Â A detailed look at koalasâ€™ newly mapped genome may help researchers understand why the animals are dropping in number in the wild. ~~ Robyn Cox/Flickr (CC BY-SA 2.0)" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/07/main/articles/062918_TS_koala-genome_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>KOALA CUTENESS</strong> Â A detailed look at koalasâ€™ newly mapped genome may help researchers understand why the animals are dropping in number in the wild.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Robyn Cox/Flickr (<a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0/">CC BY-SA 2.0</a>)</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Koalas have joined the menagerie of creatures with fully deciphered genetic instruction books, or genomes. A large team of researchers <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41588-018-0153-5">published the detailed look at the koala genome</a> online July 2 in <em>Nature Genetics.</em></p><p><strong>Why do we care?</strong> Lots of people love koalas. The iconic animal draws at least $1.1 billion in Australian dollars in tourism every year, according to the New South Wales government. But the number of koalas in the wild is declining, and researchers are combing the genome for clues about how to save the creatures.</p><p>Already, scientists have found that some koala populations are less genetically diverse than others. The genetic diversity survey also showed that koalas from different sides of some geographic barriers donâ€™t mix often. Brisbane Valley and the Clarence River were already known to separate koala populations, but the new study found that a region called Hunter Valley is a barrier, too. Armed with that knowledge, conservationists may be able to devise new strategies for limiting inbreeding and keeping koalas genetically diverse.</p><p><strong>How many genes does a koala have?</strong> 26,558. Researchers had previously counted only about 15,000 koala genes, but new techniques allowed scientists find more.</p><p><strong>Is that a lot?</strong> Yes, depending on what organism youâ€™re comparing it with. Thatâ€™s more than <a href="https://www.biorxiv.org/content/early/2018/05/29/332825">the newest estimate</a> of 21,306 protein-producing genes in humans. But plants often have thousands more genes than animals do.</p><p>The koalaâ€™s genome is also bigger than the human genome. Humans have about 6.4 billion DNA base pairs (the chemical building blocks of DNA); koalas have about 7 billion DNA base pairs.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062918_TS_koala-genome_inline_370.jpg" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062918_TS_koala-genome_inline_370.jpg" alt="" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 493px;" title="&lt;b&gt;SLEEPY TIME&lt;/b&gt;  Koalas, like this female at Featherdale Wildlife Park in Sydney, spend most of their time sleeping, resting and eating. ~~ Rebecca Johnson" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062918_TS_koala-genome_inline_370.jpg" alt="" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 493px;" title="&lt;b&gt;SLEEPY TIME&lt;/b&gt;  Koalas, like this female at Featherdale Wildlife Park in Sydney, spend most of their time sleeping, resting and eating. ~~ Rebecca Johnson" /></noscript> </div> <strong>What else does the study reveal?</strong> Koalas eat eucalyptus, which makes toxic chemicals called terpenes. Eating eucalyptus would kill most other animals, but koalas have doubled up on detox genes, especially <em>CYP2C</em>-type genes. The extra copies of these genes make proteins in koala livers that break down terpenes into water-soluble molecules that can be flushed out of the body. Unfortunately, those genes may also break down the antibiotics used to treat koalas infected with chlamydia, a major health threat contributing to the decline of the species.<p>The study also sheds light on why koalas are such picky eaters. Even though there are more than 600 species of eucalyptus, koalas dine on only about 20. It turns out that koalas have 24 bitter taste receptor genes â€” useful for detecting terpenes and other toxic chemicals â€” more than any other type of Australian marsupial. Koalas also have six times as many genes involved in smell as other marsupials do. Together, the smell and taste genes may help koalas select species of eucalyptus with the most nutrients and fewest toxins.</p><p>Koalas also have dual copies of the aquaporin 5 gene, which may help the animals seek out the most succulent eucalyptus leaves. Most of a koalaâ€™s water intake comes from the leaves.</p><p><strong>Fun facts: </strong>On average, koalas spend 14.5 hours a day sleeping. Resting while awake takes up about four to eight hours. Eating consumes another four to seven hours. Only four minutes of the day is spent traveling.</p><p>Koalas have proteins in their milk that may help protect baby koalas in their mothersâ€™ pouches from chlamydia and other bacterial or fungal infections.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>R.N. Johnson et al. <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41588-018-0153-5">Adaptation and conservation insights from the koala genome</a>. <em>Nature Genetics</em>. Published online July 2, 2018. doi:10.1038/s41588-018-0153-5.</p><p>M. Pertea et al. <a href="https://www.biorxiv.org/content/early/2018/05/29/332825">Thousands of large-scale RNA sequencing experiments yield a comprehensive new human gene list and reveal extensive transcriptional noise</a>. bioRxiv.org. Posted May 29, 2018. doi:10.1101/332825.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/why-tree-hugger-koalas-are-cool">Why tree-hugger koalas are cool</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 186, July 12, 2014, p. 14.</p><p>B. Mole. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/how-koalas-sing-low">How koalas sing low.</a> <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 184, December 28, 2013, p. 16.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Koala genome may contain clues for helping the species survive" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(15, 'Finally, thereâ€™s a way to keep syphilis growing in the lab', 'Inspiration for the breakthrough came from the bacterium that causes Lyme disease', 'Leah Rosenbaum', '2018-07-02', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/finally-theres-way-keep-syphilis-bacteria-growing-lab?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'finally-theres-way-keep-syphilis-bacteria-growing-lab', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062618_LR_syphilis_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Inspiration for the breakthrough came from the bacterium that causes Lyme disease</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-acd26fcdca742d5c806dcd922627755e">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/leah-rosenbaum">Leah Rosenbaum</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">7:00am, July 2, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062618_LR_syphilis_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062618_LR_syphilis_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062618_LR_syphilis_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="Treponema pallidum" title="GROWTH SPURT Scientists have finally figured out how to culture curly syphilis-causing bacteria (shown, colorized) using rabbit epithelial cells and a special growth medium. ~~ Roinujs/Wikimedia Commons; Source: David Cox/CDC" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062618_LR_syphilis_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="Treponema pallidum" title="GROWTH SPURT Scientists have finally figured out how to culture curly syphilis-causing bacteria (shown, colorized) using rabbit epithelial cells and a special growth medium. ~~ Roinujs/Wikimedia Commons; Source: David Cox/CDC" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062618_LR_syphilis_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>GROWTH SPURT</strong> Scientists have finally figured out how to culture curly syphilis-causing bacteria (shown, colorized) using rabbit epithelial cells and a special growth medium.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Roinujs/Wikimedia Commons; Source: David Cox/CDC</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>For more than a century, scientists have tried to grow <em>Treponema pallidum</em>, the corkscrew-shaped bacterium that causes syphilis. But the stubborn spirochete has refused to thrive any place outside of a human or rabbit for more than 18 days. That doesnâ€™t give researchers much time to study it.</p><p>â€œIâ€™ve basically spent my entire career watching these organisms die,â€ says microbiologist Steven Norris, of the University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston. Until now. Norris and colleagues have cooked up <a href="https://doi.org/10.1128/mBio.01153-18">a new recipe that keeps the bacteria alive for months</a>, they report June 26 in <em>mBio</em>.</p><p>â€œWe know very little about the organism,â€ Norris says. Being able to study it long-term in a dish could lead to better treatments for <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/cdc-sounds-alarm-stds">the millions infected worldwide</a> and pave the way for the development of a vaccine to prevent the sexually transmitted disease (<em>SN: 11/26/16, p.5</em>).</p><p>The first ingredient, rabbit epithelial cells, was <a href="http://iai.asm.org/content/32/2/908.full.pdf">adapted from a 1981 method</a> that managed to grow the bacteria for about two weeks. But it needed a secret sauce, a medium that would encourage the bacteria to grow within the rabbit cells.</p><p>First, the team tried â€œthe kitchen sink approach,â€ testing between 10 and 20 mixes of nutrients and additives. No luck.</p><p>Then, inspiration â€” from the bacteria that causes Lyme disease â€” struck. Although <em>Borrelia burgdorferi</em> and <em>T. pallidum</em> behave differently and cause different diseases, the two have similar spiral structures. Maybe they would grow in the same medium. That logic paid off. CMRL 1066, a brothy complex of sugars and vitamins favored by the Lyme spirochete, has helped keep <em>T. pallidum </em>alive for almost eight months, Norris says.</p><p>Each week, he gets a thrill as he moves the multiplying bacteria to a fresh version of the medium. â€œItâ€™s still a surprise to us that the organisms are growing,â€ he says.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>D.G. Edmondson, B. Hu and S.J. Norris. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1128/mBio.01153-18">Long-term in vitro culture of the syphilis spirochete <em>Treponema pallidum</em> subsp. pallidum</a>. <em>mBio</em>. Published online June 26, 2018. doi: 10.1128/mBio.01153-18.</p><p>A. H. Fieldsteel, D.L. Cox and R.A. Moeckli. <a href="http://iai.asm.org/content/32/2/908">Cultivation of virulent <em>Treponema pallidum</em> in tissue culture</a>. <em>Infection and Immunity</em>. Vol 32, May 1981, p. 908.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>C. Martin. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/cdc-sounds-alarm-stds">CDC sounds alarm on STDs</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol 190, November 26, 2016, p. 5.</p><p>B. Bower. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/infectious-voyagers-dna-suggests-columbus-took-syphilis-europe">Infectious voyagers: DNA suggests Columbus took syphilis to Europe</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 173, January 19, 2008, p. 38.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Finally, thereâ€™s a way to keep syphilis growing in the lab" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(16, 'â€˜Spying on Whalesâ€™ dives into the story of true leviathans', 'A new book journeys through cetaceansâ€™ past, present and future', 'Sid Perkins', '2018-06-29', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/spying-whales-dives-story-true-leviathans?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'spying-whales-dives-story-true-leviathans', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_SP_reviews_whales_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>A new book journeys through cetaceansâ€™ past, present and future</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-879831fa8ecf21f6f5065f070217277e">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/sid-perkins">Sid Perkins</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">12:00pm, June 29, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_SP_reviews_whales_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_SP_reviews_whales_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_SP_reviews_whales_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="baleen whale" title="SEA GIANTSÂ  Some species of baleen whales, a group that includes southern right whales, are among the largest creatures that ever lived. Spying on Whales explores how the animals got so big and other aspects of cetacean evolution. ~~ wildestanimal/Shutterstock" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_SP_reviews_whales_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="baleen whale" title="SEA GIANTSÂ  Some species of baleen whales, a group that includes southern right whales, are among the largest creatures that ever lived. Spying on Whales explores how the animals got so big and other aspects of cetacean evolution. ~~ wildestanimal/Shutterstock" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_SP_reviews_whales_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>SEA GIANTSÂ  </strong>Some species of baleen whales, a group that includes southern right whales, are among the largest creatures that ever lived. <a href="https://amzn.to/2tEfs9M"><em>Spying on Whales</em></a> explores how the animals got so big and other aspects of cetacean evolution.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>wildestanimal/Shutterstock</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-660713c7833231d8a708f2bf0808af27">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/july-7-2018">Vol. 194, No. 1, July 7, 2018, p. 29</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p><a href="https://amzn.to/2tEfs9M"><strong><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_SP_reviews_whales_cover.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_SP_reviews_whales_cover.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" style="width: 150px; height: 226px; float: left;" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_SP_reviews_whales_cover.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" style="width: 150px; height: 226px; float: left;" /></noscript> </div> </strong>Spying on Whales</a><br /><em>Nick Pyenson</em><br /><em>Viking, $27</em></p><p>Just before humans evolved, whales and dolphins were, pound for pound, the brainiest creatures on Earth. Another cetacean superlative: Todayâ€™s biggest whales are heftier than the largest dinosaurs that ever lived. The evolutionary trends that produced big, brainy marine animals are just a few of the fascinating tales told in <em>Spying on Whales.</em></p><p>Paleontologist Nick Pyenson studies whale fossils, but heâ€™s also been known to cut up a few modern-day carcasses. As laid out in his new science-book-cum-midcareer-memoir, the anatomical info gained from both endeavors provides strong evidence for evolution in action. That process has transformed cetaceansâ€™ dog-sized, four-legged ancestors, which returned to the water around 50 million years ago, into todayâ€™s seafaring behemoths. Pyensonâ€™s research hasnâ€™t been all lab work, though: His field studies have taken him from whaling stations in Iceland to a site in South Americaâ€™s Atacama Desert where <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/algal-blooms-created-ancient-whale-graveyard?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">ancient whales repeatedly washed ashore</a> (<em>SN Online: 2/28/14</em>).</p><p>Blue whales are about 10,000 times as massive as their landlubber ancestors, Pyenson notes. One evolutionary innovation that enabled the immensity of blue whales and some of their close kin is baleen, the flexible sheets of fingernail-like keratin that hang by the hundreds from the roofs of these creaturesâ€™ toothless mouths. Using these frayed and overlapping sheets, baleen whales filter immeasurable numbers of tiny prey from mouthfuls of water the volume of a large living room.</p><p>For some baleen whale species, another undoubted asset is the sensory organ that Pyenson and colleagues discovered in the â€œchinsâ€ of fin whales, among others. That nerve-rich glob of goo helps the whales sense dense clouds of prey and better recognize the position of their own jaws as they open and close their mouths.</p><p>When Pyenson looks to whalesâ€™ future, thereâ€™s mixed news. Most countries have phased out commercial whaling, but collisions with ships still threaten cetaceansâ€™ long-term survival. On the other hand, Pyenson notes, <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/arctic-sea-ice-loss-top-science-stories-2016?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">a decline in summer sea ice in the Arctic</a> may be allowing gray whales to stray over the pole from the North Pacific to the North Atlantic and beyond, possibly setting up new populations (<em>SN: 12/24/16, p. 23</em>).</p><p>All in all, <em>Spying on Whales</em> is a delight to read, from the authorâ€™s descriptions of the sights, sounds and smells of the lab and field to the joys of hunting fossils, whether with his colleagues or his young son.</p><p><i>Buy </i><a href="https://amzn.to/2tEfs9M">Spying on Whales</a><i>Â from Amazon.com.Â </i>Science News<i>Â is a participant in the Amazon Services LLC Associates Program. Please see ourÂ </i><a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.sciencenews.org%2Ffrequently-asked-questions%23amazon&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AFQjCNEBQxgMOSJY09CnGv17b84dw2ddbg"><i>FAQ</i></a><i>Â for more details.</i></p></span></div></div></div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="â€˜Spying on Whalesâ€™ dives into the story of true leviathans " class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        ');
INSERT INTO `news` (`id`, `title`, `subtitle`, `author`, `date`, `url`, `slug`, `image`, `content`) VALUES
(17, 'This invasive tick can clone itself and suck livestock dry', 'In its native East Asian range, the longhorn tick spreads potentially fatal human diseases', 'Leah Rosenbaum', '2018-06-29', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/invasive-longhorned-tick-can-clone-itself-suck-livestock-dry?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'invasive-longhorned-tick-can-clone-itself-suck-livestock-dry', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062718_lr_tick_feat_REV.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>In its native East Asian range, the longhorn tick spreads potentially fatal human diseases</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-7b98dc5d778c0a49e0622817018c66c4">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/leah-rosenbaum">Leah Rosenbaum</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">7:00am, June 29, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062718_lr_tick_feat_REV.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062718_lr_tick_feat_REV.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062718_lr_tick_feat_REV.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="longhorned tick adult and nymph next to a dime" title="BLOOD SUCKER Scientists have discovered the longhorned tick, an East Asian species of cloning tick (like this adult and nymph pictured next to the rim of a dime), in four continental U.S. states this year. ~~ J. Occi/Rutgers Center for Vector Biology" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062718_lr_tick_feat_REV.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="longhorned tick adult and nymph next to a dime" title="BLOOD SUCKER Scientists have discovered the longhorned tick, an East Asian species of cloning tick (like this adult and nymph pictured next to the rim of a dime), in four continental U.S. states this year. ~~ J. Occi/Rutgers Center for Vector Biology" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062718_lr_tick_feat_REV.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>BLOOD SUCKER</strong> Scientists have discovered the longhorned tick, an East Asian species of cloning tick (like this adult and nymph pictured next to the rim of a dime), in four continental U.S. states this year.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>J. Occi/Rutgers Center for Vector Biology</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Tadhgh Rainey has seen his share of bloodsuckers. As an entomologist at the Hunterdon County Health Services in Flemington, N.J., heâ€™s the person to talk to about all things mosquitoes and ticks. But he had never seen anything like the infestation on a pet sheep in September 2017.</p><p>When he and his colleague entered the sheepâ€™s enclosure, â€œwe almost immediately got covered in ticks,â€ he says. â€œI couldnâ€™t believe this sheep was alive.â€ It was covered in hundreds, maybe thousands, of ticks.</p><p>Unable to identify the ticks, Rainey sent samples to labs across the country. One went to Andrea Egizi, an entomologist at Rutgers School of Environmental and Biological Sciences in New Brunswick, N.J. Egizi analyzed the tickâ€™s DNA, and was shocked when the identification came back as <em>Haemaphysalis longicornis</em>, a native of East Asia.</p><p>Known as <a href="https://www.smsl.co.nz/site/southernmonitoring/files/NZB/Ha%20longicornis%20Profile.pdf">the longhorned tick</a> or bush tick, <em>H. longicornis </em>is ubiquitous in Japan, China and the Korean Peninsula. The New Jersey sheep was the first documented sighting in the continental United States, say Rainey and Egizi, <a href="https://academic.oup.com/jme/article/55/3/757/4840594">who published their findings online</a> February 19 in the <em>Journal of Medical Entomology</em>.</p><p>Scientists say that it is rare to find an invasive tick species in the wild. And this one seems to be spreading. It has been discovered in at least three more states â€” Virginia, West Virginia and Arkansas â€” and warnings have been issued for Maryland.Â </p><p>Here are five reasons why scientists are keeping an eye on this sneaky invader.</p><h4>1. This tick can clone itself.</h4><p>After a female longhorned tick feeds, she will lay up to 2,000 genetically identical eggs. Two to three months later, the eggs hatch without any male fertilization, and become mini copies of their mom. It is unclear how many ticks practice this rare form of asexual reproduction called parthenogenesis; so far, scientists have found fewer than 20 that reproduce this way, out of more than 800 tick species worldwide.</p><p>The process is â€œpretty alarming,â€ says medical entomologist Neeta Connally at West Connecticut State University in Danbury. Thatâ€™s because parthenogenesis happens faster than traditional mating â€” about six months for the longhorned tick, compared with the two-year reproduction cycle of common American ticks such as the deer tick and lone star tick.Â  Researchers worry that this rapid cloning could lead to heavier tick infestations in short periods of time. The female longhorned tick can focus on feeding, reproducing and traveling, without worrying about finding a mate. â€œSheâ€™s one of the first feminists,â€ jokes Allen Heath, a parasitologist at the Hopkirk Research Institute in Palmerston North, New Zealand.</p><h4>2. Itâ€™s not a picky eater.</h4><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062718_lr_tick_sheep_inline_370.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=76" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062718_lr_tick_sheep_inline_370.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=76" alt="" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 290px;" title="&lt;b&gt;GETTING AN EARFUL&lt;/b&gt; Hundreds of ticks in all stages of life were found latched on to the ear of a sheep in New Jersey. ~~Tadhgh Rainey/Hunterdon Country Health Services" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062718_lr_tick_sheep_inline_370.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=76" alt="" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 290px;" title="&lt;b&gt;GETTING AN EARFUL&lt;/b&gt; Hundreds of ticks in all stages of life were found latched on to the ear of a sheep in New Jersey. ~~Tadhgh Rainey/Hunterdon Country Health Services" /></noscript> </div> Some ticks, like the rabbit tick or moose tick, have specialized hosts and wonâ€™t feed on other animals. Other ticks, like the longhorned tick, rarely meet a blood type they donâ€™t like. The longhorned tick will chow down on any bird or mammal it can get its hooks into â€” <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/how-ticks-get-under-your-skin?mode=topic&amp;context=76">including humans</a> (<em>SN: 11/16/13</em>).<h4>3. It can carry human diseases.</h4><p>While no human bites have been reported in the United States yet, the longhorned tick is a significant public health threat in its native East Asia. In China, Japan and Korea, the tick is a known carrier of several viruses and bacteria that can infect humans. Recently, it has been linked to a disease called severe fever with thrombocytopenia syndrome (SFTS), which causes severe hemorrhaging and has a mortality rate of more than 5 percent.Â </p><p>SFTS isnâ€™t in the United States, but researchers worry that the longhorned tick may be able to adapt to <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/ticks-here-stay-scientists-finding-ways-outsmart-bloodsuckers?mode=topic&amp;context=76">transmit local tick-borne diseases</a>. Of particular concern is Lyme disease, but other potentially fatal diseases that cause neurological problems are also worrying, including ehrlichiosis, anaplasmosis, Rocky Mountain spotted fever and Powassan virus (<em>SN: 9/16/17, p. 8</em>).Â </p><h4>4.Â  Itâ€™s a big threat to livestock.</h4><p>At least for now, it seems cows and sheep should be more afraid of the tick than people. The longhorned tick is great at transmitting the deadly cattle disease theileriosis. Heavy infestations of the critters have also been known to suck so much blood from a single animal that it dies, a vampiric practice called exsanguination.</p><p>â€œKeep an eye on your animals,â€ warns Denise Bonilla, an entomologist at the U.S. Department of Agriculture Animal and Plant Inspection Service in Fort Collins, Colo. Farmers in affected areas should keep their animals on tick treatments if needed, she says.</p><h4>5. This tick is probably more widespread than we realize.</h4><p>Researchers have no idea how the tick got to the United States, or how itâ€™s been traveling within the country. Theories include hitching rides on birds or horses. We do know the tick had been in the country for several years before it was discovered last September. After that, a Rutgers graduate student tested an old tick from a 2013 sample found in New Jersey. It also turned out to be a longhorned tick, misidentified at the time as a native rabbit tick. The similar-looking longhorned tick and rabbit tick are from the same <em>Haemaphysalis </em>genus.</p><p>Egizi says she is not surprised the longhorned tick has been found in multiple places, considering it had gone undetected for years. â€œThe more we look for it, the more weâ€™ll find it,â€ she says.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>T. Rainey <em>et al</em>. <a href="https://academic.oup.com/jme/article/55/3/757/4840594">Discovery of Haemaphysalis longicornis (Ixodida: Ixodidae) parasitizing a sheep in New Jersey, United States.</a> <em>Journal of Medical Entomology</em>. Vol. 55, May 4, 2018, p. 757. doi: 10.1093/jme/tjy006.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/ticks-here-stay-scientists-finding-ways-outsmart-bloodsuckers?mode=topic&amp;context=76">Ticks are here to stay. But scientists are finding ways to outsmart them</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 192, August 19, 2017, p. 16.</p><p>A. Cunningham. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/new-tool-could-one-day-improve-lyme-disease-diagnosis?mode=topic&amp;context=76">A new tool could one day improve Lyme disease diagnosis</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol 192, September 16, 2017, p. 8.</p><p>E. Engelhaupt. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/how-ticks-get-under-your-skin?mode=topic&amp;context=76">How ticks get under your skin</a>. Science News Online, November 1, 2013.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="This invasive tick can clone itself and suck livestock dry" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(18, 'Hard-to-burn â€˜smartâ€™ wallpaper even triggers alarms', '', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sponsored/hard-burn-%E2%80%98smart%E2%80%99-wallpaper-even-triggers-alarms?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'hard-burn-%E2%80%98smart%E2%80%99-wallpaper-even-triggers-alarms', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/052318_society_inline2_370.jpg', '     <span property="dc:title" content="Hard-to-burn â€˜smartâ€™ wallpaper even triggers alarms" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span><p><strong><em>Science News for Students </em></strong><strong>(<a href="http://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org">www.sciencenewsforstudents.org</a>)</strong> is an award-winning, free online magazine that reports daily on research and new developments across scientific disciplines for inquiring minds of every age &mdash; from middle school on up.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img alt="" class="caption" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/052318_society_inline2_370.jpg" style="width: 370px; height: 222px; float: right;" title=" ~~ Photo courtesy of Scovad/Istockphoto." /><strong>Hard-to-burn &lsquo;smart&rsquo; wallpaper even triggers alarms</strong></p><p>Wallpaper can transform the look of a room. A new type can also do double duty as a 24/7 fire sentry. This wallpaper is all but unburnable, and when it gets really hot, it can trigger warning lights and sound an alarm. One added benefit: It&rsquo;s nontoxic. Key to the new wallpaper is a network of nanowires inside it. The wires are made from hydroxyapatite, a mineral found in bones and teeth that is flexible on a nanoscale level. Researchers in China described their new wall covering March 13 in <em>ACS Nano</em>. The team hopes the product&rsquo;s traits will make it attractive for use in homes. <em>&mdash; Alexandra Taylor</em></p><p><strong>Read more: <a href="http://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/wallpaper">www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/wallpaper</a></strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><img alt="" class="caption" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/052318_society_inline1_370.jpg" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 240px;" title="~~ Photo courtesy of John Sibbick." />Living Mysteries: Meet Earth&rsquo;s simplest animal</strong></p><p>In the 1880s, scientist Franz Eilhard Schulze was one of the world&rsquo;s top experts on ocean sponges. Today, he is best known for discovering a drab animal no larger than a sesame seed. The animal had been hiding in one of Schulze&rsquo;s fish tanks. To this day, <em>Trichoplax adhaeren</em>s remains the simplest animal known. A flat sheet three cells thick, it has no mouth, stomach, muscles, blood or veins. Yet <em>T. adhaerens </em>interests scientists because it shows what the very first animals on Earth might have looked like. The critter is even providing hints about how simple animals later evolved &mdash; with mouths, stomachs and nerves. <em>&mdash; Douglas Fox</em></p><p><strong>Read more: <a href="http://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/simple-animal">www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/simple-animal</a></strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><img alt="" class="caption" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/052318_society_feat.jpg" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 193px;" title="~~ Photo courtesy of Lanaby/Istockphoto." />Dirty air can harm your brain and stress the body</strong></p><p>Emerging data show that air pollution can pose serious risks to anyone, including healthy children and teens. Pollutants too small to see can alter brain function. The pollutants can make it hard for kids to concentrate and can throw hormones &mdash; those chemical messengers that direct the body&rsquo;s activities &mdash; out of whack. In short, air pollution can seriously damage young minds and bodies. And over many years, scientists worry, these pollutants could place healthy young people at risk of developing high blood pressure, diabetes or even heart disease and strokes. <em>&mdash; Lindsey Konkel</em></p><p><strong>Read more: <a href="http://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/dirty-air">www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/dirty-air</a></strong></p>  '),
(19, 'Why some mammal species donâ€™t have descended testicles, but most do', 'Several mammal species have lost the genes needed for a ligament that controls testes location', 'Angus Chen', '2018-06-28', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/why-some-mammal-species-dont-have-descended-testicles?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'why-some-mammal-species-dont-have-descended-testicles', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_AC_testicles_feat_option-b.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Several mammal species have lost the genes needed for a ligament that controls testes location</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-4179a08188d4ba8faba5e6b7f0fd3cdc">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/angus-chen">Angus Chen</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">2:00pm, June 28, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_AC_testicles_feat_option-b.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_AC_testicles_feat_option-b.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_AC_testicles_feat_option-b.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="vervet monkey" title="AIRING OUTÂ  A vervet monkey displays descended blue balls in a thin, unprotected scrotum. The male ancestor of placental mammals also sported descended testicles, rather than undescended ones like a few mammal species, a new study suggests. ~~ Jez Bennett/Shutterstock" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_AC_testicles_feat_option-b.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="vervet monkey" title="AIRING OUTÂ  A vervet monkey displays descended blue balls in a thin, unprotected scrotum. The male ancestor of placental mammals also sported descended testicles, rather than undescended ones like a few mammal species, a new study suggests. ~~ Jez Bennett/Shutterstock" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_AC_testicles_feat_option-b.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>AIRING OUT</strong>Â  A vervet monkey displays descended blue balls in a thin, unprotected scrotum. The male ancestor of placental mammals also sported descended testicles, rather than undescended ones like a few mammal species, a new study suggests.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Jez Bennett/Shutterstock</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Scientists have long wondered what the earliest mammalsâ€™ balls were like. After all, a few species today live with theirs swaddled safely up by the kidneys, like elephants do. Most other mammals drop their testes to the lower abdomen to a spot under the skin â€” like seals â€” or into an extra-abdominal sack called the scrotum â€” like humans. What style came first has been a topic of debate.</p><p>Now, new research on the genetic underpinnings of testes locations suggests that the male ancestor of placental mammals <a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.2005293">sported one of the descended modes</a>. â€œFor sure, the [ancestorâ€™s] testes wouldnâ€™t be close to the kidneys,â€ says Michael Hiller, a computational biologist at the Max Planck Institute of Molecular Cell Biology and Genetics in Dresden, Germany.</p><p>The evidence comes from comparing the genetic instruction books, or genomes, of 71 mammalian species, scientists report June 28 in <em>PLOS Biology</em>. Hiller, a coauthor of the study, says the team wasnâ€™t looking for DNA evidence of ancient testicles, but kept seeing broken versions of two genes, <em>INSL3</em> and <em>RXFP2</em>, popping up just in the lineage that includes golden moles and manatees. These genetic fossils, vestiges of once active code, suggested that certain Afrotherians, a grouping of mammals that includes elephant shrews, aardvarks and elephants, had lost <em>something</em>.</p><p>Those genes program the development of the gubernaculum, a ligament that holds dropped testes. â€œ[Itâ€™s] necessary for testicular descent to happen,â€ Hiller says. As it turns out, all of the species with nonfunctioning versions of the two genes also had undescended testes. â€œYou only see remnants of the genes required for testicular descent in species with no descent. The only way to explain that is that this is an ancestral trait that was later lostâ€ in these species, Hiller says. Otherwise, the genetic fossils shouldnâ€™t exist.</p><p>Hiller doesnâ€™t think that there was one Afrotherian ancestor that lost descended testes and passed on the trait to subsequent species in its lineage. Rather, because different Afrotherians have different <em>INSL3</em> and <em>RXFP2</em> mutations, the shift happened at different times for different species, he says. Rock hyraxes and elephants still have completely intact copies of the genes but no descended testicles, for instance. Hiller says that means the animals probably lost the trait relatively recently.</p><p>Rock hyraxes and elephants may still use the genes for some other function. â€œSometimes genes have multiple functions. If one [function] is no longer necessary, that doesnâ€™t mean the gene will become inactivated,â€ says Mark Springer, an evolutionary biologist at the University of California, Riverside. Itâ€™s also possible that thereâ€™s another, shared mutation in a third gene that inactivates testicular descent that researchers havenâ€™t spotted yet, he says.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/062818_AC_testicles_feat.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=76" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/062818_AC_testicles_feat.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=76" alt="an African bull elephant" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 390px;" title="&lt;b&gt;OUT OF SIGHT&lt;/b&gt;  Male elephants like this African bull elephant do not drop their testes in their body during development. Rather, their testes rest up by their kidneys. ~~ Bebedi/iStockphoto" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/062818_AC_testicles_feat.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=76" alt="an African bull elephant" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 390px;" title="&lt;b&gt;OUT OF SIGHT&lt;/b&gt;  Male elephants like this African bull elephant do not drop their testes in their body during development. Rather, their testes rest up by their kidneys. ~~ Bebedi/iStockphoto" /></noscript> </div> <p>Still, Springer says he applauds the study authors. Such genetic sleuthing is one way to tackle the evolution of soft body parts that donâ€™t preserve well in the fossil record. â€œThe study attacked this problem from a new angle we havenâ€™t seen before,â€ Springer says. But whether that ancestorâ€™s descended testes rested in a scrotum or in the lower abdomen under the skin â€œis still an open question.â€</p><p>Somewhat surprising, too, is why a species would evolve to have its testicles in such a vulnerable position. â€œCan you imagine having descended ovaries in a thin, unprotected sack?â€ asks Gordon Gallup, an evolutionary psychologist at the University at Albany in New York who has studied testicular evolution â€œItâ€™s unthinkable. Itâ€™s equally unthinkable for testes. Protection of the gonads is paramount.â€</p><p>But sperm need a signal telling them theyâ€™re in a female reproductive organ. That signal is temperature, Gallup says. Sperm begin swimming vigorously when the heat goes up â€” when, say, they move from a cool descended testicle into a warm vagina.</p><p>Before descended testicles evolved, Gallup thinks that the temperature signal came largely from a rise in female body temperatures during ovulation. â€œItâ€™s referred to by vets as an animal in heat,â€ he says. Keeping semen stored a bit cooler would make that change in body temperature more dramatic and help activate the sperm even more after coitus, Gallup says. â€œThat may have led to the evolution of descended testicles in the first place,â€ he says. â€œIt makes for a much more efficient use of semen.â€</p><p>At least two of the species with undescended testicles have work-arounds. Both tenrecs and golden moles keep their body temperatures below 37Â° Celsius, the cutoff temp for good sperm storage. And elephantsâ€™ and rock hyraxesâ€™ sperm ductwork detours close to the bodyâ€™s surface, which may act as a cooling mechanism. Researchers may soon get on the ball with exploring those mysteries.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>V. Sharma et al. <a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.2005293">Loss of RXFP2 and INSL3 genes in Afrotheria shows that testicular descent is the ancestral condition in placental mammals</a>. <em>PLOS Biology</em>. Published online June 28, 2018. doi:10.1371/journal.pbio.2005293.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>G. Gallup, M. Finn and B. Sammis. <a href="http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/147470490900700402">On the origin of descended scrotal testicles: The activation hypothesis</a><em>. Evolutionary Psychology.</em> Vol. 7, October 1, 2009, p. 517. doi: 10.1177/147470490900700402.</p><p>L. Werdelin and Ã…. Nilsonne. <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022519398908219">The evolution of the scrotum and testicular descent in mammals: A phylogenetic view</a>. <em>Journal of Theoretical Biology</em>. Vol. 196, January 7, 1999, p. 61. doi:10.1006/jtbi.1998.0821.</p><p>K. Kleisner, R. Ivell and J. Flegr. <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20413907">The evolutionary history of testicular externalization and the origin of the scrotum</a>. <em>Journal of Biosciences</em>. Vol. 35, March 2010, p. 27. doi:10.1007/s12038-010-0005-7.</p><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/genes-seem-link-unlikely-relatives?mode=topic&amp;context=76">Genes seem to link unlikely relatives</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 159, January 6, 2001, p. 4.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Why some mammal species donâ€™t have descended testicles, but most do" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(20, 'Leprosy lurks in armadillos in Brazilâ€™s Amazon', 'The South American country has the worldâ€™s second-highest number of cases of the disease', 'Tina Hesman Saey', '2018-06-28', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/leprosy-lurks-armadillos-brazil-amazon-may-threaten-people?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'leprosy-lurks-armadillos-brazil-amazon-may-threaten-people', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_TS_armadillo_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>The South American country has the worldâ€™s second-highest number of cases of the disease </h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-2303cee280264cda432f70e44896dc06">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/tina-hesman-saey">Tina Hesman Saey</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">2:00pm, June 28, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_TS_armadillo_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_TS_armadillo_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_TS_armadillo_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="nine-banded armadillo" title="ARMADILLO INFECTIONÂ  Nine-banded armadillos (one shown) may help spread leprosy to people in Brazil. ~~ USFWS" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_TS_armadillo_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="nine-banded armadillo" title="ARMADILLO INFECTIONÂ  Nine-banded armadillos (one shown) may help spread leprosy to people in Brazil. ~~ USFWS" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062818_TS_armadillo_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><b>ARMADILLO INFECTION</b>Â  Nine-banded armadillos (one shown) may help spread leprosy to people in Brazil.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>USFWS</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Brazilians who hunt or eat armadillos are at a higher risk of catching leprosy than people who donâ€™t interact with the animals, a new study finds.</p><p>More than 60 percent of armadillos tested in Brazilâ€™s Amazonian state of ParÃ¡ carry the leprosy bacterium <em>Mycobacterium leprae</em>. And about 63 percent of people tested in two villages in the region have antibodies against the bacterium, suggesting that they had been infected. <a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosntds/article?id=10.1371/journal.pntd.0006532">People who ate armadillos more often had more of these antibodies in their blood</a>, researchers report June 28 in <em>PLOS Neglected Tropical Diseases</em>. Â </p><p>The findings may settle a debate about whether armadillos are implicated in the spread of leprosy, also known as Hansenâ€™s disease, in Brazil. Knowing whether armadillos are involved in leprosyâ€™s spread could potentially help public health officials limit the spread of the debilitating disease, which can cause nerve damage and disfigurement.</p><p>Brazil has the second highest number of leprosy cases in the world. In 2016, <a href="http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/258841/WER9235.pdf?sequence=1">25,218 new cases of leprosy were diagnosed</a>. Only India had more, with 135,485 new cases, according to the World Health Organization.</p><div class="inline-content inline-content-right clearfix"><h4>Case counts</h4><div class="inline-content-copy"><p>Brazil is among the countries with the biggest leprosy problem in the world. In 2016, 214,783 people worldwide developed leprosy. Here are the five countries with the most new cases recorded in 2016.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062818_TS_armadillo_inline_370.png?mode=topic&amp;context=87" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062818_TS_armadillo_inline_370.png?mode=topic&amp;context=87" alt="graph showing number of new cases of leprosy in 2016" class="caption" style="width: 370px; height: 240px;" title=" ~~ C. Chang" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062818_TS_armadillo_inline_370.png?mode=topic&amp;context=87" alt="graph showing number of new cases of leprosy in 2016" class="caption" style="width: 370px; height: 240px;" title=" ~~ C. Chang" /></noscript> </div> <p><em>Source:Â World Health Organization 2017</em></p></div></div><p>Many cases of leprosy, which can be cured with antibiotics, are probably spread from person-to-person, says study coauthor and immunologist John Spencer of Colorado State University in Fort Collins. The leprosy bacterium can live in peopleâ€™s noses and may be shed in droplets when a person sneezes, coughs or breathes.</p><p>About 95 percent of the global population is immune to leprosy. But among those who are susceptible, itâ€™s not entirely clear how some get infected. Many people newly diagnosed with the disease say they never met anyone else who had leprosy, says Richard Truman, a leprosy researcher at Louisiana State University in Baton Rouge. Although the infection may take years to produce symptoms, people might remember encountering someone with the disease because transmission of leprosy seems to require close, long-term contact with an infected person, such as living with a family member. The source of those peopleâ€™s leprosy is a mystery.</p><p>Truman and colleagues reported in 2011 that nine-banded armadillos in the southeastern United States <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/armadillos-may-spread-leprosy?mode=topic&amp;context=87">carry the same strain of leprosy as people do</a> (<em>SN: 5/21/11, p. 9</em>), suggesting that people were being infected after contact with the burrowing animals. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/british-red-squirrels-serve-leprosy-reservoir?mode=topic&amp;context=87">Red squirrels in Great Britain</a> and some amoebae are the only other creatures known to harbor <em>M. leprae</em>. After the armadillo link was discovered in the United States, researchers wondered whether the animals were also contributing to the problem in Brazil. Several studies came up with mixed results.</p><p>The new research examined 16 armadillos that residents of SÃ£o Jorge and Corpus Christi had hunted in the forests surrounding the villages. Spencer and colleagues found <em>M. leprae</em> DNA in the spleens of 10 of the armadillos, and bacteria in some of the animalsâ€™ tissues. As for people, of 146 villagers, 96 had handled or cooked armadillo meat. And 91 people reported eating armadillo within the last year, with 27 of those people saying that they ate armadillo more than once a month. Those frequent armadillo eaters were at slightly higher risk of contracting the disease than people who didnâ€™t dine on armadillo, the team found.</p><p>Armadillo hunters were particularly threatened. Their risk of getting leprosy was nearly seven times greater than normal, the researchers say.</p><p>The evidence suggests that, people who come into frequent contact with armadillos may catch leprosy from the animals, Truman says. But to really establish the connection, researchers would need to show that the <em>M. leprae</em> bacteria in the armadillos are the same strains as those infecting people.</p><p>Getting a diagnosis of leprosy provokes anxiety in many patients, Truman says. â€œMany fear they are cursed and fear how their families will survive the stigma of the disease.â€ But understanding that the disease can come from something common like armadillos may help allay those fears and erase stigma. â€œThis gives them a plausible biological explanation for their disease,â€ he says.</p><p>Spencer isnâ€™t sure that his findings will stop people from hunting and eating armadillos. When he and his team told villagers they could get leprosy from armadillos, â€œthey said, â€˜we donâ€™t care. We love to eat them.â€™ It wasnâ€™t going to change their behavior,â€ Spencer recalls. Thatâ€™s not so different from anyone else, he says. After all, plenty of people eat sushi knowing that consuming raw fish puts people at risk of some parasite infections.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>M.B. de Silva et al. <a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosntds/article?id=10.1371/journal.pntd.0006532">Evidence of zoonotic leprosy in ParÃ¡, Brazilian Amazon, and risks associated with human contact or consumption of armadillos</a>. <em>PLOS Neglected Tropical Diseases.</em> Vol. 12, June 28, 2018. doi:10.1371/journal.pntd.0006532.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>L. Hamers. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/british-red-squirrels-serve-leprosy-reservoir?mode=topic&amp;context=87">British red squirrels serve as leprosy reservoir</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 190, December 10, 2016, p. 9.</p><p>N. Seppa. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/armadillos-may-spread-leprosy?mode=topic&amp;context=87">Armadillos may spread leprosy</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 179, May 21, 2011, p. 9.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Leprosy lurks in armadillos in Brazilâ€™s Amazon" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        ');
INSERT INTO `news` (`id`, `title`, `subtitle`, `author`, `date`, `url`, `slug`, `image`, `content`) VALUES
(21, 'Readers ponder geothermal power and more', '', 'Science News Staff', '2018-06-27', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/readers-ponder-geothermal-power-and-more?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'readers-ponder-geothermal-power-and-more', 'https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as', '             <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-cd5a19b736bc5075cb5d5cf07e93c317">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/science-news-staff-0">Science News Staff</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">7:15am, June 27, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-0636cc0bedd51c1ab298ba5bd51f8428">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/july-7-2018">Vol. 194, No. 1, July 7, 2018, p. 31</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><h4><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/cover_sm.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/cover_sm.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" style="float: left; width: 150px; height: 194px;" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/cover_sm.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" style="float: left; width: 150px; height: 194px;" /></noscript> </div> What lies beneath</h4><p><em>Liquid pumped into the ground to generate geothermal power may have triggered a large earthquake that shook part of South Korea last November, Carolyn Gramling reported in â€œ<a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/pumping-water-underground-power-may-have-triggered-south-korean-quake?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Pumping water underground for power may have triggered South Korean quake</a>â€</em> <em>(</em>SN: 5/26/18, p. 8<em>)</em>.</p><p>Reader Elizabeth McDowell asked if there may be a link between geothermal power generation at a plant in Hawaii and the ongoing Kilauea eruption.</p><p>â€œDid the geothermal plant inject so much water down those wells that it not only caused earthquakes but a huge eruption?â€ she asked. â€œMaybe the lava is pointing an accusatory finger at the cause by encroaching on the geothermal plant itself.â€¦ I think Hawaii should be the researchersâ€™ next case study!â€</p><div class="inline-content inline-content-right clearfix"><h4>Think before you spit</h4><div class="inline-content-copy"><p>Consumers are jumping on the genetic testing bandwagon. While the test results can be fun and informative, many people donâ€™t know what else might be in store.</p><p>As part of <em>Science Newsâ€™</em> special multipart series â€œ<a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/consumer-genetic-testing-ancestry-dna?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Genetic testing goes mainstream</a>â€ (<em>SN: 5/26/18, p. 20</em>), Cassie Martin reported on the potential privacy risks. Read â€œ<a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/science-public/privacy-and-consumer-genetic-testing-dont-always-mix?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Privacy and consumer genetic testing donâ€™t always mix</a>â€ on the Science &amp; the Public blog (<em>SN Online: 6/5/18</em>).</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/052918_CM_genetic-privacy_feat.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/052918_CM_genetic-privacy_feat.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 370px; height: 198px;" title="~~ Image Point Fr/Shutterstock" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/052918_CM_genetic-privacy_feat.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 370px; height: 198px;" title="~~ Image Point Fr/Shutterstock" /></noscript> </div> </div></div><p>South Koreaâ€™s geothermal plant is an â€œenhanced geothermal systemâ€ that involves injecting fluids at high pressures into the subsurface to produce energy. These high-pressure injections have been identified as likely culprits in earthquakes near enhanced geothermal plants in Switzerland as well.</p><p>But Hawaiiâ€™s geothermal power plant doesnâ€™t require any high-pressure injections; its location next to a volcano is no accident. The subsurface there is already fractured and very hot, well-suited for geothermal power generation, Gramling says. In other words, injections didnâ€™t cause Kilauea to erupt.</p><h4>Break it down</h4><p><em>Researchers created a new kind of plastic polymer that could, in theory, be infinitely recyclable, Laurel Hamers reported in â€œ<a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/plastic-polymer-recyclable?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">This plastic can be recycled over and over and over again</a>â€ (</em>SN: 5/26/18, p. 12<em>). </em></p><p>Online reader Mark S. wondered how the plastic could be commercialized.</p><p>â€œWithout an easy way to separate recyclable plastic from the mass of nonrecyclable plastic, it doesnâ€™t seem like there would be much [of a] market,â€ he wrote. He suggested embossing the new plastic with a bar code that would allow an artificial intelligence sorting system to separate it.</p><p>Throwing the new recyclable plastic in with your regular recycling pickup would probably be a waste of the plasticâ€™s unique properties, Hamers agrees. â€œThis isnâ€™t necessarily a barrier to commercialization. Existing biodegradable and compostable plastics face a similar challenge. Such plastics break down only under the right microbial conditions, but can end up in a landfill without those environments,â€ she says. A challenge will be to figure out how to divert these special recyclables into their own production streams, perhaps by using bar codes, as Mark S. proposes, or through a direct-to-manufacturer return process, she says.</p><h4>Bye-bye, birdie</h4><p><em>After human activities shrunk dusky seaside sparrowsâ€™ breeding grounds in 1968, the last of the species died in captivity nearly 20 years later at the Walt Disney World Resort in Orlando, Fla., Bethany Brookshire reported in â€œ<a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/50-years-ago-scientists-warned-sparrows-extinction?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">50 years ago, scientists warned of a sparrowâ€™s extinction</a>â€ (</em>SN: 5/26/18, p. 4<em>).</em></p><p>â€œInquiring minds want to know why the worldâ€™s last dusky sparrow suffered the indignity of dying at Disney World, amid thousands of parents who were wishing they were dead,â€ online reader Jan Steinman wrote.</p><p>The bird lived in captivity on Discovery Island, a now-defunct zoological park. Discovery Island housed a sparrow breeding program as part of Disneyâ€™s wildlife conservation efforts. â€œNo word from the birds on how they felt about it,â€ Brookshire says.</p></span></div></div></div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Readers ponder geothermal power and more" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(22, 'Why wonâ€™t this debate about an ancient cold snap die?', 'Despite mainstream opposition, a controversial comet impact hypothesis persists', 'Carolyn Gramling', '2018-06-26', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/younger-dryas-comet-impact-cold-snap?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'younger-dryas-comet-impact-cold-snap', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_CG_dryas_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Despite mainstream opposition, a controversial comet impact hypothesis persists</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-da042dcbcc9009d8148f1d7a1478a397">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/carolyn-gramling">Carolyn Gramling</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">2:00pm, June 26, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_CG_dryas_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_CG_dryas_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_CG_dryas_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="illustration of bison and mammoths" title="WHEREâ€™D THEY GO? About 13,000 years ago, during the Pleistocene Epoch, bison, mammoths (illustrated) and other large mammals roamed North America.Â Researchers continue to argue over what caused their extinction. ~~ Victor O. Leshyk" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_CG_dryas_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="illustration of bison and mammoths" title="WHEREâ€™D THEY GO? About 13,000 years ago, during the Pleistocene Epoch, bison, mammoths (illustrated) and other large mammals roamed North America.Â Researchers continue to argue over what caused their extinction. ~~ Victor O. Leshyk" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/070718_CG_dryas_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>WHEREâ€™D THEY GO?</strong> About 13,000 years ago, during the Pleistocene Epoch, bison, mammoths (illustrated) and other large mammals roamed North America.Â Researchers continue to argue over what caused their extinction.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Victor O. Leshyk</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-4f3dcd89fcfc52e322c0501557ba2ddc">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/july-7-2018">Vol. 194, No. 1, July 7, 2018, p. 18</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Around 13,000 years ago, Earth was emerging from its last great ice age. The vast frozen sheets that had covered much of North America, Europe and Asia for thousands of years were retreating. Giant mammals â€” steppe bison, woolly mammoths and saber-toothed cats â€” grazed or hunted across tundra and grasslands. A Paleo-Indian group of hunter-gatherers who eventually gave rise to the Clovis people had crossed a land bridge from Asia hundreds of years earlier and were now spread across North America, hunting mammoth with distinctive spears.</p><p>Then, at about 12,800 years ago, something strange happened. Earth was abruptly plunged back into a deep chill. Temperatures in parts of the Northern Hemisphere plunged to as much as 8 degrees Celsius colder than today. The cold snap lasted only about 1,200 years â€” a mere blip, in geologic time. Then, just as abruptly, Earth began to warm again. But many of the giant mammals were dying out. And the Clovis people had apparently vanished.</p><p>Geologists call this blip of frigid conditions the Younger Dryas, and its cause is a mystery. Most researchers suspect that a large pulse of freshwater from a melting ice sheet and glacial lakes flooded into the ocean, briefly interfering with Earthâ€™s heat-transporting ocean currents. However, geologists have not yet found firm evidence of how and where this happened, such as traces of the path that <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/new-pathway-proposed-ancient-flood?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">this ancient flood traveled to reach the sea</a> (<em>SN: 12/29/12, p. 11</em>).</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_1_globe.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_1_globe.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="Laurentide Ice Sheet" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 373px;" title="About 20,000 years ago, the Laurentide Ice Sheet covered much of North America. As ice melted about 12,800 years ago, a slug of freshwater may have entered the North Atlantic Ocean, interfering with ocean circulation and triggering the Younger Dryas cold period. ~~Â NOAA Science on a Sphere" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_1_globe.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="Laurentide Ice Sheet" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 373px;" title="About 20,000 years ago, the Laurentide Ice Sheet covered much of North America. As ice melted about 12,800 years ago, a slug of freshwater may have entered the North Atlantic Ocean, interfering with ocean circulation and triggering the Younger Dryas cold period. ~~Â NOAA Science on a Sphere" /></noscript> </div> But for more than a decade, one group of researchers has stirred up controversy by suggesting a cosmic cause for the sudden deep freeze. About 12,800 years ago, these researchers say, a comet â€” or perhaps its remnants â€” <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/ice-age-ends-smashingly-did-comet-blow-over-eastern-canada?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">hit or exploded over the Laurentide Ice Sheet</a> that once covered much of North America (<em>SN: 6/2/07, p. 339</em>).<p>Pieces of the comet most likely exploded in Earthâ€™s atmosphere, the researchers suggest, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.0706977104">triggering wildfires across North America</a>. Those fires would have produced enough soot and other compounds to block out the sun and cool the planet. Most scientists think that a similar aboveground explosion, known as an airburst, happened on a far smaller scale in 1908 over Siberiaâ€™s Tunguska region. That event produced as much energy as <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/comet-likely-culprit-tunguska-blast?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">1,000 Hiroshima bombs</a> (<em>SN Online: 7/28/09</em>). A similar but even larger cataclysm at the onset of the Younger Dryas, according to the hypothesisâ€™s proponents, would neatly solve several prehistoric puzzles, including what caused the extinctions of large animals and what happened to the Clovis people.</p><p>For more than a decade, scientific journals have been the battleground for skirmishes over this impact hypothesis. The idea has drawn opponents from a spectrum of scientific fields, including paleoclimatology, physics and archaeology. The critics contend that there is little to no reproducible or incontrovertible evidence for many of the key arguments of the hypothesis.</p><p>â€œOver and over and over, there are these things that are claimed to be proxies for an impact,â€ says Vance Holliday, an archaeologist and geologist at the University of Arizona in Tucson. â€œAnd theyâ€™re all debatable, every single one.â€</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_2_sticks_rev.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_2_sticks_rev.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 452px;" title="A 1908 airburst, probably from a comet exploding in Earthâ€™s atmosphere over Siberiaâ€™s Stony Tunguska River, flattened millions of trees.Â ~~Â Earthsound/Wikimedia Commons" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_2_sticks_rev.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 452px;" title="A 1908 airburst, probably from a comet exploding in Earthâ€™s atmosphere over Siberiaâ€™s Stony Tunguska River, flattened millions of trees.Â ~~Â Earthsound/Wikimedia Commons" /></noscript> </div> <p>Allen West, a retired geophysicist who owned GeoScience Consulting in Dewey, Ariz., has long been a lead proponent of the impact hypothesis. West acknowledges that the hypothesis has been battered on all sides. â€œWe have different battles with different disciplines,â€ he says. He compares these battles to the fights that raged in the 1980s over whether an asteroid struck Earth 66 million years ago, killing off all dinosaurs except birds â€” an idea that he notes is now widely accepted.</p><p>â€œThere were just vicious, nasty attacks for nearly a decade on that,â€ West says. â€œPeople said it just couldnâ€™t have happened, and then they found the crater. Thatâ€™s probably what it would take with us, too.â€</p><p>Indeed, no craters have been found dating to the Younger Dryas, and the landscape of North America â€” the likely ground zero for such an impact, proponents say â€” has been pretty thoroughly checked out. In the absence of direct evidence of an impact, West and colleagues have turned to indirect evidence, releasing a steady stream of papers outlining numerous possible signs of an impact, all dating to about 12,800 years ago.</p><p>The latest salvo came in March, when West and more than two dozen researchers published a pair of papers in the<em> Journal of Geology</em>. The papers include <a href="https://doi.org/10.1086/695703">data from ice cores</a> as well as <a href="https://doi.org/10.1086/695704">sediment cores from land and sea</a>. The cores contain signatures of giant wildfires that support the idea of a widespread burning event about 12,800 years ago, West says.</p><p>The papers promptly elicited exasperation from some opponents, including Holliday. â€œWe have 10 years of this we have to deal with. They keep building on their past record, ignoring the critiques,â€ he says. â€œIt just drives me crazy.â€</p><h4><strong>Birth of a hypothesis</strong></h4><p>The first formal description of the Younger Dryas impact hypothesis came in 2007, when four researchers sat in front of a gaggle of reporters at the American Geophysical Unionâ€™s spring meeting in Acapulco, Mexico. The researchers, including West, had taken a close look at about two dozen sites across North America showing a â€œboundary layerâ€ of sediments dating to the onset of the Younger Dryas. Half a dozen of the sites also have thin layers of organic-rich sediments called â€œblack matsâ€ immediately overlying the boundary layer. Several of those sites show signs of occupation by the Clovis people.</p><div class="inline-content inline-content-right clearfix"><h4>A line in the clay</h4><div class="inline-content-copy"><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_3_cave.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_3_cave.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 370px; height: 248px;" title="~~ Cave:Â R.B. Firestone et al/PNAS 2007; Spearpoint:Â Courtesy of Virginia Dept. of Historic Resources" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_3_cave.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 370px; height: 248px;" title="~~ Cave:Â R.B. Firestone et al/PNAS 2007; Spearpoint:Â Courtesy of Virginia Dept. of Historic Resources" /></noscript> </div> <p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_4.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_4.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" style="float: right; width: 100px; height: 261px;" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_4.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" style="float: right; width: 100px; height: 261px;" /></noscript> </div> At Arizonaâ€™s Murray Springs, an organic clay layer, or black mat, dating to around 12,800 years ago, sits on top of deposits containing Clovis artifacts (spearpoint, right) and skeletons of large game. Some researchers say the layer holds markers of an extraterrestrial impact.</div></div><p>The mats apparently mark the line between occupation and absence at the Clovis sites: For example, a black mat at a site called Murray Springs, in Arizona, sits above a trove of Clovis artifacts, a fire pit and an almost fully articulated skeleton of an adult mammoth. But above the mat, there are no such artifacts; at Murray Springs and elsewhere, the fluted stone spearpoints made by the Clovis culture disappear from the archaeological record, leading to speculation that the people mysteriously and abruptly vanished.</p><p>Those Younger Dryas boundary layers, West and colleagues reported in 2007, contain a variety of intriguing items, including tiny round magnetized grains called microspherules, other magnetized grains of sediment, little spherules of carbon, hollow round carbon molecules called fullerenes and nanodiamonds. Chemical analyses also revealed spikes in iridium and nickel concentrations and in charcoal and soot.</p><p>Taken alone, these items may or may not be signs of an extraterrestrial impact: Microspherules, for instance, form when a material heats up and then rapidly cools. They can form during a volcanic eruption, from industrial pollution or as a result of an extraterrestrial impact.</p><p>But when taken together, such a suite of markers could point only to an extraterrestrial impact, the researchers concluded: Something struck Earth and exploded in its atmosphere at the onset of the Younger Dryas, about 12,800 years ago. The soot and charcoal suggested that the impact triggered widespread burning that blocked out the sun and brought about a thousand years of near-glacial temperatures in the Northern Hemisphere.</p><p>Because no impact crater dating to this time has been found, the researchers suggested that the impactor was probably already fragmented when it entered Earthâ€™s atmosphere. Smaller fragments would have done plenty of damage as they exploded in the atmosphere over the retreating Laurentide Ice Sheet, but they wouldnâ€™t have left much of a smoking hole in the ground.</p><p>The news made a splash â€” and scientists were intrigued (<em>SN: 6/2/07, p. 339</em>). The prospect of layers rich in impact markers found scattered across a continent was definitely worth investigating further. Mark Boslough, a physicist at the University of New Mexico in Albuquerque, says that initially, he took the data at face value. â€œI thought, â€˜theyâ€™re on to something interesting.â€™ â€</p><h4><strong>Frustrations mount</strong></h4><p>Then scientists, Boslough included, began to do their own independent analyses. And questions arose. Some researchers claimed that they <a href="http://www.pnas.org/content/early/2009/10/09/0907857106">couldnâ€™t find strong evidence of some of the purported impact markers</a>, such as the microspherules and nanodiamonds. Others questioned the <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/jqs.2724">precision of the dating at many of the Younger Dryas boundary layer sites</a>, which would undermine the idea that one event affected them all simultaneously.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_5.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_5.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="microspherules" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 321px;" title="Researchers wrangle over the meaning of impact markers (microspherules shown) in black mats. ~~Â R.B. Firestone &lt;em&gt;et al/PNAS&lt;/em&gt; 2007" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_5.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="microspherules" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 321px;" title="Researchers wrangle over the meaning of impact markers (microspherules shown) in black mats. ~~Â R.B. Firestone &lt;em&gt;et al/PNAS&lt;/em&gt; 2007" /></noscript> </div> Boslough says he took issue with the physics of the proposed impact mechanisms, which have ranged from a single object striking the ice sheet to multiple fragments exploding in the atmosphere. But none of the scenarios make sense, Boslough says. Either the pieces of a fragmented comet would have been too small to generate much energy or <a href="http://www.pnas.org/content/109/34/E2241">they would have been too large not to leave craters</a>, he wrote in 2012.<p>Holliday, meanwhile, says that when it comes to the apparent disappearance of the Clovis culture, the Younger Dryas impact hypothesis is a solution to an archaeological problem that doesnâ€™t exist. Hunter-gatherers like the Paleo-Indian people who made Clovis points didnâ€™t stay at one site for long; itâ€™s no surprise that they would have moved on, Holliday says.</p><p>More important, he adds, â€œthere is no mysterious â€˜gapâ€™ in the archaeological record following the time that Clovis artifacts were made.â€ Immediately following the Clovis period, a different style of projectile points, called Folsom points, appeared. Paleo-Indian peoples probably just changed their spear technology due to a shift from hunting mammoth and mastodon to bison, Holliday says.</p><p>As for those large Ice Age animals such as mammoths, he adds, they were in decline, but their disappearance wasnâ€™t that sudden. â€œAll these animals running around and then, boom, at 12,800 years ago they just go away? Thatâ€™s just not the case,â€ Holliday says. â€œThese extinctions were global and happened at different times around the world.â€</p><p>The March papers focus mainly on the wildfires, a long-standing aspect of the original hypothesis. Greenland ice cores show peaks in ammonium dating to the onset of the Younger Dryas, which the researchers say, suggests large-scale biomass burning. These data were previously presented in 2010 by astrophysicist Adrian Melott of the University of Kansas in Lawrence and colleagues. They suggested that the ammonium ions in those ice cores could be best explained by an extraterrestrial impact. A similar spike dating to 1908 â€” the year of the airburst over Siberia â€” had also been found in those same cores. The papers also describe finding peaks in charcoal that date to the start of the cold snap.</p><p>â€œThe big thing here is a careful comparison of [many possible impact markers], normalized to the same dating method,â€ says Melott, one of the authors on the new impact papers. Those markers, including previously described evidence of microspherules, iridium and platinum dust, are consistent with having been caused by the same event, he says.</p><p>However, Jennifer Marlon, a paleoecologist and paleoclimatologist at Yale University and an expert on biomass burning, has taken her own look at sediments in North America dated to between 15,000 and 10,000 years ago. She sees no evidence for continent-wide fires dating specifically to the onset of the Younger Dryas.</p><p>â€œIâ€™ve studied charcoal records for many years now,â€ Marlon says. In 2009, she and colleagues <a href="http://www.pnas.org/content/106/8/2519">reported data on charcoal and pollen</a> in lake sediments across North America. Importantly, the sediment records in her study encompassed not only the years of the Younger Dryas cold episode, but also a few thousand years before and after.</p><p>Her team found multiple small peaks of wildfires, but none of them were near the beginning of the Younger Dryas. â€œForests burn in North America all the time,â€ she says. â€œYou canâ€™t find a cubic centimeter of sediment in any lake on this continent that doesnâ€™t have charcoal in it.â€</p><div class="inline-content inline-content-left clearfix" style="width:100%; float:none;"><h4>Missing peak</h4><div class="inline-content-copy"><p>Charcoal records from 15 lake sediment cores from across North America show how often fires occurred at each site over 5,000 years. The records show no peak in burning about 12,800 years ago, as would be expected if there were continent-scale fires.Â </p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_6_graph_730.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_6_graph_730.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" style="width: 730px; height: 263px;" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/070718_CG_dryas_inline_6_graph_730.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" style="width: 730px; height: 263px;" /></noscript> </div> <div style="color: rgb(170, 170, 170); text-transform: uppercase; line-height: 12px; font-size: 10px; height: auto; text-align: right;">T. Tibbitts; Source: J.R. Marlon<em> et al</em>/<em>PNAS</em> 2009</div></div></div><p>Such fires could be triggered by rapid climate change, when ecosystems are quickly reorganizing and more dead fuel might be available. â€œThat can cause major vegetation changes and fires,â€ Marlon says. â€œWe donâ€™t need to invoke a comet.â€</p><p>The problem with the data in the recent papers, Marlon says, is that the researchers look only at a narrow time period, making it difficult to evaluate how large or unusual the signals really were. From her data, there appeared to have been more burning toward the <em>end</em> of the Younger Dryas, when the planet began to warm abruptly again.</p><p>â€œThat speaks to my fundamental problem with the biomass burning part of the papers,â€ Marlon says. â€œI donâ€™t understand why theyâ€™re zooming in. Itâ€™s what makes me skeptical.â€</p><p>Holliday echoes that criticism. â€œMost of the time they sample only around this time interval,â€ he says. What would be more convincing, he says, are data from cores that span 15,000 to 20,000 years, sampled every five centimeters or so. â€œIf this is a unique event, then we shouldnâ€™t see anything like it in the last 15,000 years.â€</p><p>West says that other peaks are irrelevant, because the impact hypothesis doesnâ€™t imply that there was only one wildfire, just that one occurred around 12,800 years ago. He adds that the new papers suggest that Marlon and her colleagues didnâ€™t correctly calibrate the radiocarbon dates for their samples. When done correctly, he says, one spike in fires that Marlon estimated at around 13,200 years ago actually occurred several hundred years later â€” right around 12,800 years ago.</p><p>Radiocarbon dating for such old events is challenging regardless of calibration, Marlon says. Thatâ€™s why she analyzed and compared her sites in several different ways, yet still found no unusual peak at 12,800 years. In fact, she says, many of the sites show no signs of burning at that time.</p><p>As for whether the impact hypothesis proponents have ignored scientific criticisms, West rejects this. â€œWe have directly rebutted those criticisms multiple times,â€ he says. An upcoming paper he and others are preparing will describe in detail those rebuttals, such as errors he says previous critics made in properly reproducing the analyses West and his colleagues used to identify a key impact marker, the magnetic spherules.</p><p>Yet critics of the Younger Dryas impact hypothesis say that too many questions remain unanswered. Holliday says he and others are preparing a response to the <em>Journal of Geology</em> papers, outlining numerous points of contention.</p><p>â€œConfronting and dealing with critical reviews and contradictory data is a significant problem in this debate,â€ Holliday says. None of the rebuttals have dealt with various criticisms, he adds, such as the proper dating of rock layers and soils, and the contradictory data over animal extinctions and Paleo-Indian archaeology.</p><p>â€œWe all love a good debate,â€ Marlon says, â€œbut I know thereâ€™s a lot of frustration in the communityâ€ that this hypothesis persists. Like many opponents of the impact hypothesis, she says that the data presented in the new papers have done nothing to change her mind about the comet strike. â€œIt didnâ€™t happen.â€</p><p>All the same, Marlon understands the allure. â€œI have had pet theories, too. We are pattern-seekers. We tend to see things that look like a signal and so many times theyâ€™re not. A comet is simpler and more visually compelling â€” more appealing, in a way â€” than trying to sort out what Earthbound trigger might have caused such an abrupt climate change.</p><p>â€œI wish the evidence were stronger for [an impact],â€ she says. â€œItâ€™s not as much fun when it turns out to be a more complicated, nuanced story.â€</p><hr /><p><em>This article appears in the July 7, 2018 issue ofÂ </em>Science News<em>Â with the headline, "The impact hypothesis that won\'t die: Critics are still unconvinced that a comet caused a mysterious cold snap 12,800 years ago."</em></p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>Wendy S. Wolbach <em>et al</em>. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1086/695704">Extraordinary biomass-burning episode and impact winter triggered by the Younger Dryas cosmic impact ~12,800 years ago. 2. Lake, Marine, and Terrestrial Sediments</a>. <em>The Journal of Geology</em>. Vol. 126, March 2018, p. 185. doi: 10.1086/695703.</p><p>Wendy S. Wolbach <em>et al</em>. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1086/695703">Extraordinary biomass-burning episode and impact winter triggered by the Younger Dryas cosmic impact ~12,800 years ago. 1. Ice Cores and Glaciers</a>. <em>The Journal of Geology</em>. Vol. 126, March 2018, p. 165. doi: 10.1086/695703.</p><p>Vance T. Holliday <em>et al</em>. <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/jqs.2724">The Younger Dryas impact hypothesis: a cosmic catastrophe</a>. <em>Journal of Quaternary Science</em>. Vol. 29, August 8, 2014, p. 515. doi: 10.1002/jqs.2724.</p><p>M. Boslough. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1206739109">Inconsistent impact hypotheses for the Younger Dryas</a>. <em>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences</em>. Vol 109, August 21, 2012, p. E2241. doi: 10.1073/pnas.1110614109.</p><p>T.A. Surovell <em>et al</em>. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.0907857106">An independent evaluation of the Younger Dryas extraterrestrial impact hypothesis</a>. <em>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences</em>. Vol. 106, October 27, 2009, p. 18155. doi: 10.1073/pnas.0907857106.</p><p>R.B. Firestone <em>et al</em>. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.0706977104">Evidence for an extraterrestrial impact 12,900 years ago that contributed to the megafaunal extinctions and the Younger Dryas cooling</a>. <em>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences</em>. Vol. 104, October 9, 2007, p. 16016. doi: 10.1073/pnas.0706977104.</p><p>J.R. Marlon et al. <a href="http://www.pnas.org/content/106/8/2519">Wildfire responses to abrupt climate change in North America</a>. <em>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences</em>. Â Vol. 106, February 24, 2009, p. Â 2519. doi:Â 10.1073/pnas.0808212106.Â </p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>S. Perkins. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/once-upon-lake?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Once upon a lake</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 162, November 2, 2002, p. 283.</p><p>S. Perkins. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/ice-age-ends-smashingly-did-comet-blow-over-eastern-canada?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Ice Age ends smashingly: Did a comet blow up over eastern Canada?</a> <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 171, June 2, 2007, p. 339.</p><p>S. Perkins. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/signs-giant-comet-impacts-found-cores?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Signs of giant comet impact found in cores</a>. Science News Online. March 30, 2010.</p><p>E. Wayman. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/new-pathway-proposed-ancient-flood?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">New pathway proposed for ancient flood</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 182, December 29, 2012, p. 11.</p><p>B. Bower. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/shock-absorbing-spear-points-kept-early-north-americans-hunt?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Shock-absorbing spear points kept early North Americans on the hunt</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 191, May 13, 2017, p. 8.</p><p>B. Bower. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/footprints-put-people-canada-west-coast-13000-years-ago?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Footprints put people on Canadaâ€™s west coast 13,000 years ago</a>. Science News Online. March 28, 2018.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Why wonâ€™t this debate about an ancient cold snap die?" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        ');
