(23, 'How domestication changed rabbitsâ€™ brains', 'Study sizes up differences in the â€˜fear centersâ€™ of wild and tame bunnies', 'Tina Hesman Saey', '2018-06-25', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/science-ticker/how-domestication-changed-rabbit-brains?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'how-domestication-changed-rabbit-brains', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/062218_TI_bunny-brains_feat_FREE.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Study sizes up differences in the â€˜fear centersâ€™ of wild and tame bunnies </h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-openpublish-related-content view-id-openpublish_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-1514894dffbc68946ffc46cdc6d358ed">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-profile-photo">        <div class="field-content"><a href="/author/tina-hesman-saey"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/styles/author_thumbnail/public/profiles/photos/TS_250.jpg?itok=SgqxuS7w" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/styles/author_thumbnail/public/profiles/photos/TS_250.jpg?itok=SgqxuS7w" width="50" height="50" alt="Tina Hesman Saey" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/styles/author_thumbnail/public/profiles/photos/TS_250.jpg?itok=SgqxuS7w" width="50" height="50" alt="Tina Hesman Saey" /></noscript></a></div>  </div>     <div class="views-field views-field-title">    <span class="views-label views-label-title">by</span>    <span class="field-content">  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/tina-hesman-saey">Tina Hesman Saey</a></span> </div> </span>  </div>     <div class="views-field views-field-published-at">        <span class="field-content">3:00pm, June 25, 2018</span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/062218_TI_bunny-brains_feat_FREE.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/062218_TI_bunny-brains_feat_FREE.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/062218_TI_bunny-brains_feat_FREE.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="wild and domesticated rabbits" title="RABBIT REMODELING Domestication of wild rabbits (left) physically changed the animals over time, including their brains. A domesticated rabbit is shown on the right. ~~ FranciscoMarques/shutterstock (left); Grigorita Ko/shutterstock (right)" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/062218_TI_bunny-brains_feat_FREE.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="wild and domesticated rabbits" title="RABBIT REMODELING Domestication of wild rabbits (left) physically changed the animals over time, including their brains. A domesticated rabbit is shown on the right. ~~ FranciscoMarques/shutterstock (left); Grigorita Ko/shutterstock (right)" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/062218_TI_bunny-brains_feat_FREE.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>RABBIT REMODELING</strong> Domestication of wild rabbits (left) physically changed the animals over time, including their brains. A domesticated rabbit is shown on the right.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>FranciscoMarques/shutterstock (left); Grigorita Ko/shutterstock (right)</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-blog-post-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-blog-post-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-blog-post-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Domestic rabbits have <a href="http://www.pnas.org/cgi/doi/10.1073/pnas.1801024115">smaller brains relative to their body size</a> than wild rabbits do, a new study determined. And thatâ€™s not the only change <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/study-debunks-fishy-tale-how-rabbits-were-first-tamed?mode=blog&amp;context=108">getting tamed by humans</a> wrought on bunny brains.</p><p>Two â€œfear centersâ€ are the most altered brain regions between wild and domestic rabbits. Domestic rabbits have smaller amygdalae (emotion-processing centers that play a key role in the fight-or-flight response) and larger medial prefrontal cortices (thought to be involved in social behavior) than wild rabbits, an international group of researchers report online June 25 in the <em>Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences</em>.</p><p>Changes to the brain regions may have produced animals less fearful of humans.</p><div class="inline-content inline-content-left clearfix" style="width:100%; float:none;"><h4>Bunny brains</h4><div class="inline-content-copy"><p>Transparent images of rabbit brains illustrate that a wild rabbit, left, has larger amygdalae (yellow) and a smaller medial prefrontal cortex (blue) than a domestic rabbit, right. Those parts of the brain may have changed during domestication because they are involved in fear.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062218_TI_bunny-brains_inline_730.png?mode=blog&amp;context=108" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062218_TI_bunny-brains_inline_730.png?mode=blog&amp;context=108" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 222px;" title="~~ Image courtesy of Fabian Sinzinger/KTH Royal Institute of Technology, Stockholm " /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/062218_TI_bunny-brains_inline_730.png?mode=blog&amp;context=108" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 222px;" title="~~ Image courtesy of Fabian Sinzinger/KTH Royal Institute of Technology, Stockholm " /></noscript> </div> </div></div></span></div></div></div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="How domestication changed rabbitsâ€™ brains" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>                    '),
(24, 'Society names 50 Advocates to mentor underserved students', '', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sponsored/society-names-50-advocates-mentor-underserved-students?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'society-names-50-advocates-mentor-underserved-students', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/Advocates%202017-2018%20Claudio%20Photo%20World%20of%20Insects%207.jpg', '     <div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/Advocates%202017-2018%20Claudio%20Photo%20World%20of%20Insects%207.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/Advocates%202017-2018%20Claudio%20Photo%20World%20of%20Insects%207.jpg" width="840" height="560" alt="Photo credit: Michael Pham." /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/Advocates%202017-2018%20Claudio%20Photo%20World%20of%20Insects%207.jpg" width="840" height="560" alt="Photo credit: Michael Pham." /></noscript></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Photo credit: Michael Pham.</p></div></div></div><span property="dc:title" content="Society names 50 Advocates to mentor underserved students" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span><p><img alt="" class="caption" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/Advocates%202017-2018%20Douglas%20Photo%20Science%20Club%20Meeting%204.jpg" style="width: 400px; height: 477px; float: right;" title="Photo courtesy of Amy Douglas." />Society for Science &amp; the Public is excited to announce this year&rsquo;s 50 Advocates &mdash; educators, scientists and mentors &mdash; who will help underrepresented students find opportunities to participate and compete in science research competitions and will help inspire the students to engage in STEM fields.</p><p>Each Advocate will mentor a cohort of at least three students and help them navigate the often complicated process of entering science research competitions. The Advocates will support the students as they complete research projects and apply to compete in science fairs and contests.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>2018&ndash;2019 Lead Advocates, who will mentor groups of Advocates:</strong><br /><strong>Laurel Bingman</strong>, Houston, Texas<br /><strong>Charmain Brammer</strong>, St. George, Utah<br /><strong>Jennifer Claudio</strong>, San Jose, California<br /><strong>Priscilla Lumbreras</strong>, Granbury, Texas<br /><strong>Douglas Masterson</strong>, Hattiesburg, Mississippi<br /><strong>Elizabeth Proctor</strong>, Monticello, Georgia<br /><strong>Brenda Rubenstein</strong>, Providence, Rhode Island</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>2018&ndash;2019 Advocates:<br />Marvin Bayro</strong>, San Juan, Puerto Rico<br /><strong>Maya Bhagat</strong>, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania<br /><strong>Cheyenne Branscum</strong>, Shawnee, Oklahoma<br /><strong>Denise Caceres</strong>, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania<br /><strong>Celia Castellanos</strong>, Los Angeles, California<br /><strong>Carrie Cox</strong>, Chamberlain, South Dakota<br /><strong>Jennifer Donnelly</strong>, Union City, New Jersey<br /><strong>Amy Douglas</strong>, Shreveport, Louisiana<br /><strong>Creighton Edington</strong>, Albuquerque, New Mexico<br /><strong>Errik Ejike</strong>, Omaha, Nebraska<br /><strong>Conrad Faine</strong>, Hialeah, Florida<br /><strong>Lisa Franchetti</strong>, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania<br /><strong>Shannon Fraser</strong>, Priest River, Idaho<br /><strong>Mark Friedman</strong>, Inglewood, California<br /><strong>Constantina Green</strong>, Hopkins, South Carolina<br /><strong>Cynthia Hopkins</strong>, Corpus Christi, Texas<br /><strong>Tinika Jackson</strong>, Washington, D.C.<br /><strong>Merridith Joly</strong>, St. Paul, Minnesota<br /><strong>Stephanie Jones</strong>, Atlanta, Georgia<br /><strong>Vincent Joralemon</strong>, New York, New York<br /><strong>Kehkashan Khan</strong>, Chicago, Illinois<br /><strong>Frank LaBanca</strong>, Danbury, Connecticut<br /><strong>Mindy Levine</strong>, Kingston, Rhode Island<br /><strong>Jamie Ludwig</strong>, Lawrenceville, New Jersey<br /><strong>Reny Mathew</strong>, Tuba City, Arizona<br /><strong>Pradip Misra</strong>, Bagdad, Arizona<br /><strong>Andrew Moore</strong>, Port Huron, Michigan<br /><strong>Deborah Morgan</strong>, Monroe, Utah<br /><strong>Alexis Mychajliw</strong>, Los Angeles, California<br /><strong>Marteen Nolan</strong>, Crocker, Missouri<br /><strong>Lorraine O&rsquo;Shea</strong>, Grand Forks, North Dakota<br /><strong>Heather Overkamp</strong>, Portsmouth, Virginia<br /><strong>Pamela Patterson-Anhalt</strong>, Shawano, Wisconsin<br /><strong>Ashley Poloha</strong>, Pasadena, Texas<br /><strong>Chris Reeves</strong>, Camdenton, Missouri<br /><strong>Jeanne Richardson</strong>, Graham, Texas<br /><strong>Kimberly Ring</strong>, Eureka, Kansas<br /><strong>Devon Riter</strong>, Lower Brule, South Dakota<br /><strong>Sunada Roberts</strong>, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania<br /><strong>Tracy Rumbaugh</strong>, Omaha, Nebraska<br /><strong>Diana Techentien</strong>, Jacksonville, Florida<br /><strong>Kiwanna Wade</strong>, West Helena, Arkansas<br /><strong>Carolyn Walling</strong>, Iowa City, Iowa</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Learn more</strong> about the Advocate Grant Program at <strong><a href="http://www.societyforscience.org/advocate-grant">www.societyforscience.org/advocate-grant</a>.</strong></p>  '),
(25, 'How a squishy clam conquers a rock', 'It turns out that this molluskâ€™s boring organ is anything but', 'Susan Milius', '2018-06-22', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/how-squishy-clam-conquers-rock?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'how-squishy-clam-conquers-rock', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061918_SM_clams_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>It turns out that this molluskâ€™s boring organ is anything but </h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-e6a1bd8d35bcd120548dd36fe069aefd">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/susan-milius">Susan Milius</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">7:00am, June 22, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061918_SM_clams_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061918_SM_clams_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061918_SM_clams_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="a giant clam" title="JUST THE FRILLSÂ  Showy blue and green frills are the only visible parts of a kind of giant clam that traps itself for life inside the rocky mass of a reef by a process thatâ€™s been misunderstood for decades. ~~ Nhobgood/Wikimedia Commons (CC BY-SA 3.0)" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061918_SM_clams_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="a giant clam" title="JUST THE FRILLSÂ  Showy blue and green frills are the only visible parts of a kind of giant clam that traps itself for life inside the rocky mass of a reef by a process thatâ€™s been misunderstood for decades. ~~ Nhobgood/Wikimedia Commons (CC BY-SA 3.0)" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061918_SM_clams_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>JUST THE FRILLS</strong>Â  Showy blue and green frills are the only visible parts of a kind of giant clam that traps itself for life inside the rocky mass of a reef by a process thatâ€™s been misunderstood for decades.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Nhobgood/Wikimedia Commons (CC BY-SA 3.0)</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-5f8bd32003211986f6182472a67e9574">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">       </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Burrowing giant clams have perfected the ship-in-a-bottle trick, and the one big thing that scientists convinced themselves couldnâ€™t explain it, actually can.</p><p><em>Tridacna crocea</em>, the smallest of the 10 or so giant clam species, grows a shell that eventually reaches the size of a large fist. Starting as youngsters, the burrowers bore into the stony mass of an Indo-Pacific coral reef, trapping themselves behind a too-skinny exit for their entire decades-long lives.</p><p>Only the extravagantly colored upper edges of the clamâ€™s body can push out the thin slit in the reef. These protruding frills teem with algae related to those in corals. Basking in sunlight, the algae pay rent in the form of a substantial portion of a giant clamâ€™s nourishment.</p><p>The clams â€œactually have eyes in this tissue,â€ says environmental physiologist Richard Hill of Michigan State University in East Lansing. At the slightest shadow â€” a predator, perhaps â€” the clam yanks in such vulnerable parts through the very narrow crack. â€œItâ€™s as if the clam vanished,â€ he says.</p><p>The colors the clam creates on this extendable tissue approach the psychedelic and can bewitch aquarium hobbyists into paying three-figure sums. â€œThe ones that get the big money are turquoise,â€ Hill says, but heâ€™s seen indigo blue as well as yellow, crimson and even a boring brown.</p><p>The opposite rim of the clam body, hidden deep inside the coral crevice, looks anything but colorful. Â Through a hole near the shell hinge, a soft cream-colored mass called (quite unfairly) the â€œboring organ,â€ emerges. Like pulling on a gym sock, this tissue spreads upward over the shell. A sock embrace puts the tissue in touch with the cave wall that the clam must erode as it grows.</p><p>A leading mollusk biologist of the 20th century, <a href="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/42820310#page/365/mode/1up">Sir Charles Maurice Yonge</a>, proposed that boring organs gradually dissolve the rock by secreting acid. Yet he shot down his own theory (and fretted about it through the rest of his life) by adding a color-changing pH indicator to the clamâ€™s seawater. There was no sign of a surge in acidity.</p><p>Hill decided to reexamine the mystery. After some epic bouts of Googling the options for testing pH in a liquid, he suddenly wondered if direct clam contact mattered. He found a device measuring pH at lots of points across a flat piece of foil that a clam, he hoped, could be persuaded to press its boring organ against.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061918_SM_clams_inline_730.png?mode=topic&amp;context=87" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061918_SM_clams_inline_730.png?mode=topic&amp;context=87" alt="an acidity map of a giant clam\'s boring organ" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 425px;" title="&lt;b&gt;ACID KISS&lt;/b&gt;  Red zones indicating acidity measured by a flat pH detector (right) suggest that a giant clamâ€™s soft, pale boring organ (left) uses acid to carve its cave in coral. ~~ R. Hill &lt;em&gt;et al/Biology Letters&lt;/em&gt; 2018" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061918_SM_clams_inline_730.png?mode=topic&amp;context=87" alt="an acidity map of a giant clam\'s boring organ" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 425px;" title="&lt;b&gt;ACID KISS&lt;/b&gt;  Red zones indicating acidity measured by a flat pH detector (right) suggest that a giant clamâ€™s soft, pale boring organ (left) uses acid to carve its cave in coral. ~~ R. Hill &lt;em&gt;et al/Biology Letters&lt;/em&gt; 2018" /></noscript> </div> <p>The project required a trip to Japan plus world-class mollusk management to coax clams to touch organs to foil in the desired way. When they did, however, the detector revealed red blotches of acidity, like lipstick smudges on a napkin.</p><p>The clams may not be able to bring down the pH of a lot of alkaline seawater, but <a href="http://rsbl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/14/6/20180047">they can acidify a surface</a>, Hill and his colleagues report June 13 in <em>Biology Letters</em>. Turns out that this organ is boring in the very best sense of the word.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>R.W. Hill et al. <a href="http://rsbl.royalsocietypublishing.org/lookup/doi/10.1098/rsbl.2018.0047">Acid secretion by the boring organ of the burrowing giant clam, <em>Tridacna crocea</em></a>. <em>Biology Letters</em>. Published online June 13, 2018, 20180047. doi: 10.1098/rsbl.2018.0047.</p><p>C.M. Yonge. <a href="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/part/183507#/summary">Mode of life, feeding, digestion and symbiosis with zooxanthellae in the Tridacnidae</a>. Great Barrier Reef Expedition 1928â€“29. <em>Scientific Reports</em>.Â  Vol. 1. Published February 2, 1922, p. 283. London, The British Museum (Natural History.)</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>M. Neo et al. <a href="https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/e/9781351987592/chapters/10.1201%2Fb21944-5">Giant clams (Bivalvia: Cardiidae: Tridacninae): A comprehensive update of species and their distribution, current threats and conservation status</a>. <em>Oceanography and Marine Biology: An Annual Review</em>. Vol. 55, 2017, p. 87.</p><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/some-animals-%E2%80%98see%E2%80%99-world-through-oddball-eyes?mode=topic&amp;context=87">Some animals â€˜seeâ€™ the world through oddball eyes</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 189, May 28, 2016, p. 22.</p><p>S. Gaidos. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/defying-depth?mode=topic&amp;context=87">Defying depth</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 181, June 16, 2012, p. 26.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="How a squishy clam conquers a rock" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(26, 'Koko the gorilla is gone, but she left a legacy', '', 'Bruce Bower', '2018-06-21', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/koko-gorilla-gone-she-left-legacy?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'koko-gorilla-gone-she-left-legacy', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062118_BB_koko_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-eee39298fa661fe5d4fcd53f22935ecf">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/bruce-bower">Bruce Bower</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">5:35pm, June 21, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062118_BB_koko_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062118_BB_koko_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062118_BB_koko_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="Koko the gorilla" title="R.I.P.Â Â Koko, seen here showing Francine Patterson a flower, gained fame for learning sign language. The western lowland gorilla died June 19 at age 46. ~~ The Gorilla Foundation/Koko.org" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062118_BB_koko_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="Koko the gorilla" title="R.I.P.Â Â Koko, seen here showing Francine Patterson a flower, gained fame for learning sign language. The western lowland gorilla died June 19 at age 46. ~~ The Gorilla Foundation/Koko.org" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/062118_BB_koko_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>R.I.P.Â Â </strong>Koko, seen here showing Francine Patterson a flower, gained fame for learning sign language. The western lowland gorilla died June 19 at age 46.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>The Gorilla Foundation/Koko.org</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>When Koko died in her sleep in California on June 19, people throughout the world immediately began mourning the gorilla.</p><p>Koko was a charmer and undeniably smart. She took an unusual route to fame. Stanford University graduate student Francine Patterson started teaching Koko a version of sign language in 1972, the year after the infant ape was born. Patterson rapidly developed a <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/documentary-looks-meaning-koko-gorilla%E2%80%99s-life?mode=topic&amp;context=49">deep emotional connection to Koko</a>.</p><p>Pattersonâ€™s claims that Koko learned to communicate and converse with sign language in a humanlike way won the gorilla legions of fans but also attracted much scientific criticism. Pattersonâ€™s work with Koko came at a time when <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/archive/behavior-357?mode=topic&amp;context=49">captive chimps were also receiving sign language training</a>.</p><p><em>Science News</em> spoke with anthropologist Barbara King about Kokoâ€™s legacy. King, of the College of William and Mary in Williamsburg, Va., studies emotions and thinking in nonhuman animals. Her books include <em>How Animals Grieve</em>.</p><h3><strong>Q: What were your first thoughts upon hearing that Koko had died?</strong></h3><p><strong>A: </strong>My first response wasnâ€™t thoughts, but tears. After that, a reflection on how Koko taught us so much about the great ape mind, even while she paid a cost, in her own daily life, for our scientific curiosity.</p><h3><strong>Q: What is Kokoâ€™s scientific legacy, especially for understanding ape communication?</strong></h3><p><strong>A: </strong>How amazing Koko was, a creative and resourceful ape who could vibrantly show us that great apes think and feel, all because she understood how to use aspects of â€œourâ€ language. She could use signs of American Sign Language in meaningful ways to discuss not only her likes and dislikes but also her emotions. At one and the same time, she was an utterly special gorilla because of how she was raised and yet alsoÂ an exemplar of what all our closest living primate relatives do â€” reason, feel and negotiate daily life through a complex set of social interactions.</p><h3><strong>Q: Did Francine Patterson get too close to Koko to perform credible studies?</strong></h3><p><strong>A: </strong>Certainly there were cases of <a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/13.7/2015/12/10/459181304/famous-gorilla-s-climate-speech">over-interpretations</a> made throughout the years regarding Kokoâ€™s behavior and utterances that damaged the researchersâ€™ credibility. Parading Koko around to give a climate-change speech is just one example. What concerns me more are the <a href="http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2014/08/koko_kanzi_and_ape_language_research_criticism_of_working_conditions_and.html">ethics of confining her in a highly unnatural world</a>, one where she couldnâ€™t live in a social group with other gorillas and where she was treated in highly questionable ways regarding her diet and medical care.</p><h3><strong>Q: How do you explain Kokoâ€™s broad and lasting cultural appeal?</strong></h3><p><strong>A: </strong>Who among us hasnâ€™t wanted to know what gorillas think, and for that matter, elephants, dolphins, our dogs and cats, chickens and cows? Koko allowed us a glimpse into a marvelous mind. She reached us all one way or another, as when she touched childrenâ€™s hearts when a book went viral about her sadness at the death of her kitten.</p><h3><strong>Q: Should scientists pursue new sign language studies in apes like those conducted with Koko?</strong></h3><p><strong>A: </strong>Full stop, no. Over the 46 years of Kokoâ€™s life, we have learned enough to recognize that it is imperative to focus on getting funding to move chimpanzees and monkeys confined to biomedical laboratories to retirement in sanctuaries. The last thing we need is to confine a great ape and train him or her to adopt aspects of our language.</p></span></div></div></div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Koko the gorilla is gone, but she left a legacy" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(27, 'Each year painted lady butterflies cross the Sahara â€” and then go back again', 'They migrate 12,000 km annually, the longest known butterfly migration route', 'Leah Rosenbaum', '2018-06-20', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/painted-lady-butterflies-migration-sahara-africa?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'painted-lady-butterflies-migration-sahara-africa', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061818_LR_butterfly-est_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>They migrate 12,000 km annually, the longest known butterfly migration route</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-dba2a1cad49ed4448acfed29aec86a21">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/leah-rosenbaum">Leah Rosenbaum</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">7:00am, June 20, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061818_LR_butterfly-est_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061818_LR_butterfly-est_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061818_LR_butterfly-est_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="a painted lady butterfly (Vanessa cardui) resting on vegetation" title="GOING THE DISTANCE Â Painted ladies travel 12,000 km each year, farther than any known butterfly migration. ~~ Gerard Talavera" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061818_LR_butterfly-est_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="a painted lady butterfly (Vanessa cardui) resting on vegetation" title="GOING THE DISTANCE Â Painted ladies travel 12,000 km each year, farther than any known butterfly migration. ~~ Gerard Talavera" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061818_LR_butterfly-est_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><b>GOING THE DISTANCE</b> Â Painted ladies travel 12,000 km each year, farther than any known butterfly migration.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Gerard Talavera</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-d37b551486f2a58d30455be8be00e5c3">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">       </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Move over, monarchs. The painted lady butterfly (<em>Vanessa cardui</em>) now boasts the farthest known butterfly migration.</p><p>Though found across the world, the orange-and-brown beauties that live in Southern Europe migrate into Africa each fall, <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/painted-lady-butterflies%E2%80%99-migration-may-take-them-across-sahara?mode=topic&amp;context=76">crossing the Sahara on their journey</a> (<em>SN Online: 10/12/16</em>). But what happened after was a mystery because the butterflies disappeared. Researchers hypothesized that the insects either remained in Africa or made a round-trip, but there was no evidence either way.</p><p>A new chemical analysis of butterfly wings suggests that the butterflies head back to Europe in the spring. The round-trip, which usually plays out over several generations, is an annual journey of 12,000 kilometers, about 2,000 more than <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/flying-insects-tell-tales-long-distance-migrations?mode=topic&amp;context=76">successive generations of monarchs are known to travel in a year</a> (<em>SN: 4/14/18, p. 22</em>).</p><p>Researchers were surprised when they detected chemical markers from Africa on some European butterfliesâ€™ wings. Those markers told where an individual had eaten when it was still a caterpillar. The study, reported in the June 13 <em>Biology Letters</em>, <a href="http://rsbl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/14/6/20180274">provides evidence that the creatures return from Africa each year</a>. Some tenacious individuals even make the return trip in a single lifetime.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>G. Talavera <em>et al</em><a href="http://rsbl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/14/6/20180274">. Round-trip across the Sahara: Afrotropical Painted Lady butterflies recolonize the Mediterranean in early spring</a>. <em>Biology Letters</em>. Published online June 13 2018. doi: 10.1098/rsbl.2018.0274.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>S. Zielinski. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/painted-lady-butterflies%E2%80%99-migration-may-take-them-across-sahara?mode=topic&amp;context=76">Painted lady butterfliesâ€™ migration may take them across the Sahara</a>. Science News Online, October 12, 2016.</p><p>A. Witze. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/flying-insects-tell-tales-long-distance-migrations?mode=topic&amp;context=76">Flying insects tell tales of long-distance migration</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol 193, April 14, 2018, p. 22.</p><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/long-ignored-high-flying-arthropods-could-make-largest-land-migrations?mode=topic&amp;context=76">Long-ignored, high-flying arthropods could make up largest land migrations.</a> <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 191, February 4, 2017, p. 12.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Each year painted lady butterflies cross the Sahara â€” and then go back again" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        ');
INSERT INTO `news` (`id`, `title`, `subtitle`, `author`, `date`, `url`, `slug`, `image`, `content`) VALUES
(28, 'Madagascarâ€™s predators are probably vulnerable to toxic toads', '', 'Sarah Zielinski', '2018-06-19', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/madagascar-invasive-asian-common-toads-predators-toxin?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'madagascar-invasive-asian-common-toads-predators-toxin', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/061818_SZ_toads-wild-things_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-openpublish-related-content view-id-openpublish_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-91f35aab8c4fcdb1b4b435fd85d11eb9">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-profile-photo">        <div class="field-content"><a href="/author/sarah-zielinski"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/styles/author_thumbnail/public/2015/12/profiles/photos/SZ_2015_250x250.jpg?itok=cer16VBC" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/styles/author_thumbnail/public/2015/12/profiles/photos/SZ_2015_250x250.jpg?itok=cer16VBC" width="50" height="50" alt="" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/styles/author_thumbnail/public/2015/12/profiles/photos/SZ_2015_250x250.jpg?itok=cer16VBC" width="50" height="50" alt="" /></noscript></a></div>  </div>     <div class="views-field views-field-title">    <span class="views-label views-label-title">by</span>    <span class="field-content">  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/sarah-zielinski">Sarah Zielinski</a></span> </div> </span>  </div>     <div class="views-field views-field-published-at">        <span class="field-content">9:00am, June 19, 2018</span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/061818_SZ_toads-wild-things_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/061818_SZ_toads-wild-things_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/061818_SZ_toads-wild-things_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="Asian common toad" title="The skin of the Asian common toad is laced with a deadly toxin. A new study finds that most predators in Madagascar that might eat the toad lack the genetic mutations necessary to make them immune to the toxin. ~~ Benjamin Marshall" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/061818_SZ_toads-wild-things_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="Asian common toad" title="The skin of the Asian common toad is laced with a deadly toxin. A new study finds that most predators in Madagascar that might eat the toad lack the genetic mutations necessary to make them immune to the toxin. ~~ Benjamin Marshall" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/blogposts/061818_SZ_toads-wild-things_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>The skin of the Asian common toad is laced with a deadly toxin. A new study finds that most predators in Madagascar that might eat the toad lack the genetic mutations necessary to make them immune to the toxin.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Benjamin Marshall</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-blog-post-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-blog-post-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-blog-post-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>At some point eight to 10 years ago, some toads stowed away on a ship in Asia, <a href="http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/content/journals/10.1163/15685381-00003104">possibly Ho Chi Minh City</a>, and hitched a ride to Madagascar. Those invaders, Asian common toads, have been slowly spreading across the large island ever since.</p><p>The toadâ€™s skin contains a toxin that kills nearly anything that tries to eat the amphibian. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/invasive-toads-will-probably-overrun-madagascar?mode=blog&amp;context=116">Scientists have been warning</a> of the toadâ€™s danger to ecosystems for years, but theyâ€™ve lacked evidence of just how dangerous the toads could be. Now, a genetic study confirms that nearly all of Madagascarâ€™s predators would be vulnerable to the toadâ€™s toxin.</p><p><em>Duttaphrynus melanostictus</em> is one of many toad species that secrete potent toxins called bufadienolides. These chemicals disrupt the flow of sodium and potassium in cell walls, something that is particularly important for the function of muscles, and especially the heart.</p><p>â€œAnimals that are not resistant to the toads that take a mouthful of toad can die extremely quickly from heart failure,â€ says Wolfgang WÃ¼ster, a herpetologist at Bangor University in Wales.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061818_SZ_toads-wild-things_inline_370.jpg?mode=blog&amp;context=116" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061818_SZ_toads-wild-things_inline_370.jpg?mode=blog&amp;context=116" alt="Asian common toad in Madagascar village" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 323px;" title="The Asian common toad is now spreading across Madagascar, posing a threat to the islandâ€™s unique wildlife. ~~ Franco Andreone" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061818_SZ_toads-wild-things_inline_370.jpg?mode=blog&amp;context=116" alt="Asian common toad in Madagascar village" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 323px;" title="The Asian common toad is now spreading across Madagascar, posing a threat to the islandâ€™s unique wildlife. ~~ Franco Andreone" /></noscript> </div> There are species, including reptiles and mammals, that have evolved resistance to the toxin. And in 2015, WÃ¼ster and other scientists reported that these examples of resistance <a href="http://www.pnas.org/content/112/38/11911">shared a commonality</a>: They all had specific mutations in the gene for the sodium-potassium pump. â€œThatâ€™s a universal mechanism for being able to consume toads â€” and particularly to deal with the bufo toxins,â€ says WÃ¼ster.<p>Toxic toads are an invasive species in several places around the world. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/quick-moving-toads-take-straight-and-narrow-path?mode=blog&amp;context=116">Cane toads</a>, for instance, have been spreading across northern Australia for decades, leading to declines of species such as quolls and snakes. That invasion is well-studied, and so scientists know a lot about the species affected by it. Thereâ€™s little need there to start looking for species that are immune to the toxin. But in areas of more-recent invasions, such as Indonesia and Madagascar, such data could be helpful.</p><p>So WÃ¼ster and his colleagues looked at the gene for the sodium-potassium pump in 77 Malagasy species, including 28 birds, eight mammals and 27 snakes. Only one species, the <a href="http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/2991/0">white-tailed antsangy</a>, a type of rodent, had the mutations that would make it immune to the toad toxin. The mutations were the same as those found in the brown rat, which suggests that they might be a common feature among rodents. <a href="https://www.cell.com/current-biology/fulltext/S0960-9822(18)30452-4">The 76 other species studied are likely vulnerable to the toad toxin</a>, the researchers conclude June 4 in <em>Current Biology</em>.</p><p>This doesnâ€™t mean, however, that Madagascarâ€™s wildlife is entirely doomed. In Australia, scientists have documented behavioral changes in some predator species that have allowed them to safely eat toads. Some birds, for instance, have learned that toad tongues are safe to eat. Some Malagasy species could likewise figure out how to safely make a meal of the toads â€” or learn to not eat them at all.</p><p>People might help as well. Itâ€™s probably too late to eradicate the toads from Madagascar. Thereâ€™s too many, and thereâ€™s no good way to easily find and kill them. But this research may help scientists in Madagascar to take measures to protect certain species or sites from the invasive species, WÃ¼ster says. Â </p><p>â€œMadagascar has been isolated for tens of millions of years,â€ notes WÃ¼ster. â€œItâ€™s never had toads. Why would the local animals be resistant to toads? We always expected them to be sensitive. But now we have much better evidence that thatâ€™s really the case.â€</p></span></div></div></div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Madagascarâ€™s predators are probably vulnerable to toxic toads" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>                    '),
(29, 'The most ancient African baobabs are dying and no one knows why', 'After standing for a millennium or two, 9 of the 13 oldest trees have lost big chunks or died', 'Susan Milius', '2018-06-18', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/most-ancient-african-baobabs-are-dying-and-no-one-knows-why?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'most-ancient-african-baobabs-are-dying-and-no-one-knows-why', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061218_sm_baobab_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>After standing for a millennium or two, 9 of the 13 oldest trees have lost big chunks or died </h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-b4f2c08f05aae3f2613801169e425826">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/susan-milius">Susan Milius</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">7:00am, June 18, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061218_sm_baobab_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061218_sm_baobab_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061218_sm_baobab_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="a baobab tree" title="BEFORE THE FALLÂ  African baobab trees may be in trouble. After living some 1,400 years, this specimen in Botswana â€” called the Chapman tree â€” toppled and died in 2016. ~~ A. Patrut, Roxana Patrut" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061218_sm_baobab_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="a baobab tree" title="BEFORE THE FALLÂ  African baobab trees may be in trouble. After living some 1,400 years, this specimen in Botswana â€” called the Chapman tree â€” toppled and died in 2016. ~~ A. Patrut, Roxana Patrut" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061218_sm_baobab_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>BEFORE THE FALL</strong>Â  African baobab trees may be in trouble. After living some 1,400 years, this specimen in Botswana â€” called the Chapman tree â€” toppled and died in 2016.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>A. Patrut, Roxana Patrut</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-5971ba5870e5296b67553263e405e492">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/july-7-2018">Vol. 194, No. 1, July 7, 2018, p. 11</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>The last 13 years have been terrible for ancient African baobab trees.</p><p>Nine of the 13 oldest <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41477-018-0170-5">either lost trunks or died altogether</a> after having lived for longer than a millennium, researchers report June 11 in <em>Nature Plants</em>. But just what the demise means for the iconic species is up for debate.</p><p>Â â€œWhilst we are saddened about the death and collapse [of the old trees], current evidence does not indicate that this is affecting the whole population,â€ says plant scientist Sarah Venter, who was not part of the new study. Venter, with the University of the Witwatersrand in Johannesburg, does not see an immediate threat to the species as a whole. These trees of extreme age â€œwere probably more vulnerable to dry conditions,â€ she says. â€œTree mortality is complex and can be attributed to many causes, including climate change and droughts.â€</p><p>The <em>Adansonia digitata </em>species of the baobab group is the longest-living kind of flowering tree. With its mass of skinny branches dividing like rootlets over a fat trunk, the species sometimes gets teased as an upside-down tree. Long-stemmed brown fruits also encourage the nickname â€œdead-rat tree.â€ Yet people have long cherished the giant baobabs for food, medicine and spiritual value.</p><p>Of the 13 oldest known <em>A. digitata</em>, four have died since 2005, says study coauthor Adrian Patrut, who specializes in inorganic and nuclear chemistry at BabeÅŸ-Bolyai University in Cluj-Napoca, Romania. Five others of these ancient trees across the African continent have lost enormous chunks of their multiple trunks, Patrut and his colleagues report.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061218_sm_baobab_inline_730.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061218_sm_baobab_inline_730.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 387px;" title="&lt;b&gt;R.I.P. BAOBAB&lt;/b&gt;  The Chapman tree had grown 22 meters tall and to a diameter of almost 26 meters when its multiple trunks collapsed. It had been the 11th oldest known living baobab of its species. ~~ A. Patrut, Roxana Patrut" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061218_sm_baobab_inline_730.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 387px;" title="&lt;b&gt;R.I.P. BAOBAB&lt;/b&gt;  The Chapman tree had grown 22 meters tall and to a diameter of almost 26 meters when its multiple trunks collapsed. It had been the 11th oldest known living baobab of its species. ~~ A. Patrut, Roxana Patrut" /></noscript> </div> <p>The oldest to die, the Panke tree in Zimbabwe, had lived about 2,500 years before it collapsed over the course of 2010 and 2011. The other three trees that died, including the Chapman tree in Botswana, were just 1,250 to 1,500 years old. Â </p><p>Patrut does not think mere old age caused their demise. He worries something more troubling may be going on instead. â€œThere were no signs of an epidemic,â€ Patrut says. He suspects that a warming trend observed in southern Africa may be playing a role.</p><p>As world-famous as baobabs are, much of their drought biology and other basic matters remain mysterious. â€œDoes anyone really know the rooting structure of baobabs?â€ laments plant ecologist Eugene Moll of the University of the Western Cape in Bellville, South Africa. For understanding Africaâ€™s plants, â€œphilosophies and paradigms that originate north of 40Â° N do not necessarily apply down here in the Southern Hemisphere,â€ he says. â€œWe humans like symmetry but nature is certainly not always symmetrical.â€</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>A. Patrut et al. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41477-018-0170-5">The demise of the largest and oldest African baobabs</a>. <em>Nature Plants</em>. Published online June 11, 2018.Â  doi:10.1038/s41477-018-0170-50.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>D. Garisto. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/tree-rings-drought-mongolia-climate-change?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Tree rings tell tale of drought in Mongolia over the last 2,000 years</a>.Â  <em>Science News Online</em>.Â  March 19, 2018.</p><p>C. Gramling. Â <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/tropical-forests-have-flipped-sponges-sources-carbon-dioxide?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Tropical forests have flipped from sponges to sources of carbon dioxide</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 192, October 28, 2017, p. 9.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="The most ancient African baobabs are dying and no one knows why" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(30, 'Congratulations to the Regeneron Science Talent Search 2018 top winners!', '', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sponsored/congratulations-regeneron-science-talent-search-2018-top-winners?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'congratulations-regeneron-science-talent-search-2018-top-winners', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/04/preview.jpg', '     <div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/04/preview.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/04/preview.jpg" width="1200" height="846" alt="The top three winners of Regeneron STS 2018." /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/04/preview.jpg" width="1200" height="846" alt="The top three winners of Regeneron STS 2018." /></noscript></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>The top three winners of Regeneron STS 2018. Photo courtesy of Society for Science &amp; the Public/Chris Ayers.</p></div></div></div><span property="dc:title" content="Congratulations to the Regeneron Science Talent Search 2018 top winners!" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span><p>Teen scientists win $1.8 million at this year&rsquo;s competition.</p><p><strong>Benjamin &ldquo;Benjy&rdquo; Firester</strong>, 18, of New York City, won the top award of $250,000 for developing a mathematical model that uses disease data to predict how weather patterns could spread spores of late blight fungus, which caused the Irish Potato Famine. The plant disease still causes billions of dollars in global crop damages annually.</p><p><img alt="Benjamin Firester won first place at Regeneron STS 2018." class="caption" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/preview%20%281%29.jpg" style="width: 750px; height: 576px;" title="Benjamin Firester won first place at Regeneron STS 2018. ~~ Photo courtesy of Society for Science &amp; the Public/Chris Ayers." /></p><p>Second place honors and $175,000 went to <strong>Natalia Orlovsky</strong>, 18, of Chadds Ford, Pa. She examined the response of lung epithelial cells to fluids used in vaping, a practice often promoted as a safer alternative to smoking cigarettes.</p><p>Third place honors and $150,000 went to <strong>Isani Singh</strong>, 18, of Aurora, Colo., for her work toward determining if women with Turner syndrome, a rare disease in which all or part of a woman&rsquo;s second sex chromosome is missing, may have some cells with two X chromosomes.</p><p>Fourth Place: <strong>Muhammad (Shahir) Rahman</strong>, 17, of Portland, Ore., received a $100,000 award for engineering an internet-enabled microwave oven capable of simultaneously heating different foods on the same plate to optimal temperatures without requiring user input.</p><p>Fifth Place: <strong>David Wu</strong>, 17, of Potomac, Md., received a $90,000 award for his project studying the patterns of sequential prime numbers.</p><p>Sixth Place: <strong>Kyle Fridberg</strong>, 17, of Boulder, Colo., received an $80,000 award for discovering a new compound that may be useful in improving rechargeable battery technology.</p><p>Seventh Place: <strong>Vinjai Vale</strong>, 17, of Exeter, N.H., received a $70,000 award for creating a system that may improve the ability of convolutional neural networks to understand complex scenes.</p><p>Eighth Place: <strong>Skyler Jones</strong>, 17, of Ossining, N.Y., received a $60,000 award for her study of perovskite crystals used in solar cells. She identified key properties of the perovskite&rsquo;s atomic structure that make it a highly efficient semiconductor, despite its structural defects and low stability.</p><p>Ninth Place: <strong>Syamantak Payra</strong>, 16, of Friendswood, Texas, received a $50,000 award for creating a smart bionic leg brace that bends the knee automatically as the wearer walks.</p><p>Tenth Place: <strong>Raley Schweinfurth</strong>, 18, of Portland, Ore., received a $40,000 award for her study of honey, soil and tree contamination levels following an insecticide-spraying incident in 2013 in Oregon that killed more than 50,000 bees.</p><p>The remaining 30 finalists each received $25,000.</p>  '),
(31, 'Leaf-cutter ants pick up the pace when they sense rain', 'If their cargo gets wet, they will drop it and lose the dayâ€™s treasure', 'Yao-Hua Law', '2018-06-15', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/leaf-cutter-ants-pick-pace-when-they-sense-rain?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'leaf-cutter-ants-pick-pace-when-they-sense-rain', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/052118_YHL_leaf-cutter_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>If their cargo gets wet, they will drop it and lose the dayâ€™s treasure</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-ff8f0e1d1097abc35dcc23149c085ab0">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/yao-hua-law">Yao-Hua Law</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">7:00am, June 15, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/052118_YHL_leaf-cutter_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/052118_YHL_leaf-cutter_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/052118_YHL_leaf-cutter_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="leaf-cutter ants" title="STAY DRYÂ  When the rain starts falling in Central Americaâ€™s tropical forests, leaf-cutter ants (Atta cephalotes) hurry back to their nests â€” with or without their leafy cargo, which gets heftier when wet.Â  ~~ Pjt56/Wikimedia Commons (CC BY-SA 4.0)" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/052118_YHL_leaf-cutter_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="leaf-cutter ants" title="STAY DRYÂ  When the rain starts falling in Central Americaâ€™s tropical forests, leaf-cutter ants (Atta cephalotes) hurry back to their nests â€” with or without their leafy cargo, which gets heftier when wet.Â  ~~ Pjt56/Wikimedia Commons (CC BY-SA 4.0)" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/052118_YHL_leaf-cutter_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>STAY DRY</strong>Â  When the rain starts falling in Central Americaâ€™s tropical forests, leaf-cutter ants (<em>Atta cephalotes</em>) hurry back to their nests â€” with or without their leafy cargo, which gets heftier when wet.Â </p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Pjt56/Wikimedia Commons (<a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/">CC BY-SA 4.0</a>)</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-0b9c173170df45b4f823b8f22b3d08d6">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/june-23-2018">Vol. 193, No. 11, June 23, 2018, p. 5</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>In Central Americaâ€™s rain-drenched forests, leaf-cutting ants collect pieces of leaves on which they grow fungi for food. But the rain can hit hard, especially for a small ant. When leaf-cutting ants sense an incoming shower, they <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs00040-018-0605-z">hoof it back to their nests</a>, says a study in the May <i>Insectes Sociaux</i>.</p><p>Researchers from Argentina, Mexico and Peru tested how one species of leaf-cutting ants, <i>Atta cephalotes</i>, in Costa Rica deals with rain. The scientists placed hollow boxes filled with wet cotton on ant trails in the forest. When<i> A. cephalotes </i>walked through the boxes, they experienced higher relative humidity, as if it were about to rain. In another experiment, the researchers poured water on plants beside the trail to simulate falling raindrops. Both situations caused the ants to scramble to their nest up to 30 percent faster than normal, from about 1.21 meters per minute to 1.49.</p><p>The researchers think that leaf-cutter ants speed up to keep their cargo and themselves dry, with good reason: A wet leaf fragment weighs more than double a dry one. In the study, when the ants or leaves got wet, the insects readily dropped their harvest and returned to the nest. But by hurrying along at the first hints of rain, the ants could stay dry and hold onto the leaves.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>A.G. Farji-Brener <em>et al</em><a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs00040-018-0605-z"><em>.</em> Working in the rain? Why leaf-cutting ants stop foraging when itâ€™s raining.</a> <em>Insectes Sociaux</em>. Vol. 65, May, 2018. doi: 10.1007/s00040-018-0605-z.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>L. Hamers. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/ants-were-among-worlds-first-farmers?mode=magazine&amp;context=194583">Ants were among the worldâ€™s first farmers</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 192, November 11, 2017, p. 4</p><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/classic-view-leaf-cutter-ants-overlooked-nitrogen-fixing-partner?mode=magazine&amp;context=194583">Classic view of leaf-cutter ants overlooked in nitrogen-fixing partner</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 176, December 19, 2009, p. 8.</p><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/archive/old-macdonald-was-ant?mode=magazine&amp;context=194583">Old MacDonald was an ant</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 154, November 21, 1998, p. 334.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Leaf-cutter ants pick up the pace when they sense rain " class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        ');
INSERT INTO `news` (`id`, `title`, `subtitle`, `author`, `date`, `url`, `slug`, `image`, `content`) VALUES
(32, 'These newfound frogs have been trapped in amber for 99 million years', 'Bits of bugs and plants in the ancient goo provide a glimpse of the amphibiansâ€™ lives', 'Carolyn Gramling', '2018-06-14', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/frogs-fossils-amber-tropical-forest?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'frogs-fossils-amber-tropical-forest', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_CG_amber-frog_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Bits of bugs and plants in the ancient goo provide a glimpse of the amphibiansâ€™ lives</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-427796e11811948db0722c692bb28f24">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/carolyn-gramling">Carolyn Gramling</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">9:00am, June 14, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_CG_amber-frog_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_CG_amber-frog_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_CG_amber-frog_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="amber" title="ARRESTED IN AMBERÂ  Chunks of amber contain fossils of 99-million-year-old frogs that were roughly the size of a postage stamp. One chunk (left) holds a recognizably froggy leg and body. Another specimen (right) contains a juvenile with a partial skull. ~~ Lida Xing" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_CG_amber-frog_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="amber" title="ARRESTED IN AMBERÂ  Chunks of amber contain fossils of 99-million-year-old frogs that were roughly the size of a postage stamp. One chunk (left) holds a recognizably froggy leg and body. Another specimen (right) contains a juvenile with a partial skull. ~~ Lida Xing" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_CG_amber-frog_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>ARRESTED IN AMBER</strong>Â  Chunks of amber contain fossils of 99-million-year-old frogs that were roughly the size of a postage stamp. One chunk (left) holds a recognizably froggy leg and body. Another specimen (right) contains a juvenile with a partial skull.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Lida Xing</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-b4179dfe6c151306079a869402378d3d">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/july-7-2018">Vol. 194, No. 1, July 7, 2018, p. 4</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>About 99 million years ago, tiny frogs hopped through a wet, tropical forest â€” and an unlucky few ran afoul of some tree sap. Four newly described frog fossils, preserved in amber, offer the earliest direct evidence of ancient frogs living in a humid tropical clime â€” just as many modern amphibians do.</p><p>None of the frog fossils is complete, making it difficult to place the frogs within their family tree: One has a partial skull and another a froggy outline, although CT scanning revealed no remaining skeletal material inside the impression. So <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-018-26848-w">researchers dubbed all four fossils <em>Electrorana limoae</em></a> (<em>electrum</em> for â€œamberâ€ and <em>rana</em> for â€œfrogâ€) in a study published June 14 in <em>Scientific Reports</em>. Anatomy-wise, the ancient frogs most resemble a modern group that includes fire-bellied toads.</p><p>The fossil record contains relatively few frogs, despite the amphibiansâ€™ more than 200-million-year history. The frog fossils that do exist suggest that frogs have looked distinctly â€” well, froggy â€” for hundreds of millions of years, says study coauthor David Blackburn, an amphibian biologist at the Florida Museum of Natural History in Gainesville. â€œThe aspects that make them diverse are not their skeletons, itâ€™s their ecologies, natural histories, reproductive modes. Things that are really hard to find in the fossil record.â€</p><p>Thatâ€™s what makes the amber specimens so interesting: The chunks also contain preserved spiders, velvet worms and bamboo â€” all pointing to a tropical environment. Such paleoecological evidence offers scientists a rare glimpse into the life and times of tropical frogs of old.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>L. Xing <em>et al</em>. <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-018-26848-w">The earliest direct evidence of frogs in wet tropical forests from Cretaceous Burmese amber</a>. <em>Scientific Reports</em>. Published online June 14, 2018. doi: 10.1038/s41598-018-26848-w.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/some-frogs-may-be-bouncing-back-after-killer-chytrid-fungus?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Some frogs may be bouncing back after killer chytrid fungus</a>. Science News Online, March 29, 2018.Â </p><p>M. Rosen. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/dinosaur-tail-preserved-amber-feathers?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Dinosaur tail preserved in amber, with feathers</a>. Science News Online, December 9, 2016.</p><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/fossil-monstrous-fish-eating-amphibian-unearthed?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Fossil of monstrous fish-eating amphibian unearthed</a>. Science News Online, March 23, 2015.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="These newfound frogs have been trapped in amber for 99 million years" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(33, 'Hereâ€™s what narwhals sound like underwater', 'Submersible recorders pick up the animalsâ€™ clicks, calls and buzzes', 'Leah Rosenbaum', '2018-06-13', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/what-narwhals-sound-underwater?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'what-narwhals-sound-underwater', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_LR_narwhal_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Submersible recorders pick up the animalsâ€™ clicks, calls and buzzes </h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-e0c8742263b233e7f892a4c1a9d89929">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/leah-rosenbaum">Leah Rosenbaum</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">2:00pm, June 13, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_LR_narwhal_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_LR_narwhal_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_LR_narwhal_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="researchers with a narwhal" title="TURN IT UP Â Researchers put an acoustic tagging device on a male narwhal to record its underwater clicks, buzzes and calls. Â  ~~ S. Blackwell" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_LR_narwhal_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="researchers with a narwhal" title="TURN IT UP Â Researchers put an acoustic tagging device on a male narwhal to record its underwater clicks, buzzes and calls. Â  ~~ S. Blackwell" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/061318_LR_narwhal_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>TURN IT UP </strong>Â Researchers put an acoustic tagging device on a male narwhal to record its underwater clicks, buzzes and calls. Â </p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>S. Blackwell</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-485f0641dca1103015c3f7bf2dc2b8e5">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/july-7-2018">Vol. 194, No. 1, July 7, 2018, p. 14</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Narwhals are among the most elusive of whales. But for the first time, researchers have been able to eavesdrop on the creatures for days at a time as these unicorns of the sea dove, fed and socialized.</p><p>Biologist Susanna Blackwell and colleagues listened in on the clicks, buzzes and calls of the East Greenland narwhal (<em>Monodon monoceros</em>). The teamâ€™s findings, published June 13 in <em>PLOS ONE</em>, <a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0198295">provide a peek into the daily behavior</a> of the long-toothed whale. The research could help scientists determine how human-made noises may affect narwhals as the Arctic warms due to climate change and shipping lanes become more open.</p><p>Many whale sounds are recorded using hydrophones, underwater microphones that dangle in the water. But these acoustic devices have several drawbacks: They canâ€™t sense the depth or direction from which noise comes, and they canâ€™t detect which animal is making a sound.</p><p>Blackwell and colleagues skirted these issues by attaching an acoustic recording device to the narwhals themselves. â€œIt is really like sitting on the back of a narwhal for a few days and experiencing the world,â€ Blackwell says.</p><div class="inline-content inline-content-right clearfix"><h4>Narwhal noise</h4><div class="inline-content-copy"><p>Listen to two recordings of East Greenland narwhals collected by researchers from 2013 to 2016.</p><h3>Feeling chatty</h3><p>Several whales socialize with each other at a depth of 65 meters, using clicks, whistles and trumpet sounds.</p><iframe allow="autoplay" frameborder="no" height="100" scrolling="no" src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/457805985%3Fsecret_token%3Ds-YCSRb&amp;color=%23106185&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true" width="100%"></iframe><div style="color: rgb(170, 170, 170); text-transform: uppercase; line-height: 12px; font-size: 10px; height: auto; text-align: right;">Audio: S. Blackwell; Image: Glenn Williams/Wikimedia Commons</div><h3>On repeat</h3><p>A female narwhal communicates using pulselike sounds as she swims near the surface of the ocean.</p><iframe allow="autoplay" frameborder="no" height="100" scrolling="no" src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/457805991%3Fsecret_token%3Ds-RB8vA&amp;color=%23106185&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true" width="100%"></iframe><div style="color: rgb(170, 170, 170); text-transform: uppercase; line-height: 12px; font-size: 10px; height: auto; text-align: right;">Audio: S. Blackwell; Image: Glenn Williams/Wikimedia Commons</div></div></div><p>With the help of native Greenland hunters, the researchers tagged six of the skittish creatures from 2013 to 2016. The devices were attached with suction cups, and held in place for several days by a nylon string threaded through a ridge of cartilage on the narwhalsâ€™ backs. After three to eight days in the water, magnesium links to the string degraded and released the device, which the researchers retrieved using GPS.</p><p>Tagging <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/narwhals-react-certain-dangers-really-strange-way?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">was stressful for the narwhals</a>, says Blackwell, who works for Greeneridge Sciences, Inc., the Santa Barbara, Calif., company that manufactures the acoustic devices (<em>SN Online: 12/7/17</em>). But after a day of silence, the narwhals resumed their normal behavior.</p><p>Like other species of toothed whales, narwhals use echolocation to hunt in the dark arctic waters. â€œTheyâ€™re like wet bats,â€ says Kate Stafford, an oceanographer at the University of Washington in Seattle who did not participate in the study. The researchers found that the narwhals clicked while diving to locate their prey, often arctic and polar cod or squid. When closing in on a meal, the clicking sounds turned into a rapid buzzing noise. At the surface, the narwhals used whistle and trumpetlike calls to communicate with one another.</p><p>â€œWe were very surprised that they actually have a very specialized way of using sound,â€ says study coauthor Mads Peter Heide-JÃ¸rgensen, a biologist at the Greenland Institute of Natural Resources based in Copenhagen. The narwhalsâ€™ sounds varied not only with each activity the animals did, but also with their depth.</p><div class="inline-content inline-content-left clearfix" style="width:100%; float:none;"><h4>Narwhal diary</h4><div class="inline-content-copy"><p>Eistla, a female narwhal with a young calf, was one of six narwhals that researchers listened in on. She remained fairly silent immediately after having an acoustic device attached to her and being released. But by the second day, she became more vocal, clicking (blue lines) as she dove and buzzing (black circles) as she closed in on prey. Yellow squares mark calls made by Eistla or other nearby narwhals. The device detached on the fifth day.</p><h3 style="text-align: center;">Types of sounds used by a narwhal vary with depth and time of day</h3><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061318_LR_narwhal_inline_730.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061318_LR_narwhal_inline_730.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 378px;" title="~~ S. Blackwell &lt;em&gt;et al&lt;/em&gt;/&lt;em&gt;PLOS ONE&lt;/em&gt; 2018 " /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/061318_LR_narwhal_inline_730.png?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="" class="caption" style="width: 730px; height: 378px;" title="~~ S. Blackwell &lt;em&gt;et al&lt;/em&gt;/&lt;em&gt;PLOS ONE&lt;/em&gt; 2018 " /></noscript> </div> </div></div><p>â€œHaving some of this baseline data from an area that is relatively pristine is going to be really valuable going forward,â€ Stafford says.</p><p>Though the Scoresby Sound where the narwhal research took place is very remote, it wonâ€™t be for long. Human presence in the Arctic is increasing thanks to climate change, says Jens Koblitz, a bioacoustician at the University of Konstanz in Germany. Fishing boats, ships of oil prospectors and others are expected to spend more time in the Arctic <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/human-co2-emissions-put-arctic-track-be-ice-free-2050?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">as global warming reduces the extent of sea ice</a> in the region (<em>SN: 12/10/16, p. 15</em>)<em>.</em></p><p>â€œThis study is a great stepping-stone,â€ Koblitz says. If scientists discover that human sounds negatively affect the ways that the whales communicate, researchers might be able to protect some areas from human activity.</p> <style type="text/css"> <!--/*--><![CDATA[/* ><!--*/ iframe {min-width:100%!important;}  /*--><!]]>*/ </style></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>S. Blackwell et al. <a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0198295">Spatial and temporal patterns of sound production in East Greenland narwhals</a>. <em>PLOS ONE</em>. Published online June 13, 2018. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0198295.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>C. Gramling. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/seafloor-map-shows-why-greenland-glaciers-melt-different-rates?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Seafloor map shows why Greenlandâ€™s glaciers melt at different rates</a>. Science News Online, April 3, 2018.</p><p>M. Quintanilla. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/narwhals-react-certain-dangers-really-strange-way?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Narwhals react to certain dangers in a really strange way</a>. Science News Online, December 7, 2017.</p><p>T. Sumner. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/human-co2-emissions-put-arctic-track-be-ice-free-2050?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Human CO<sub>2</sub>Â emissions put Arctic on track to be ice-free by 2050</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 190, December 10, 2016, p. 15.</p><p>H. Thompson. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/narwhals-are-really-really-good-echolocation?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Narwhals are really, really good at echolocation</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 190, December 10, 2016, p. 16.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Hereâ€™s what narwhals sound like underwater" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(34, 'Bees join an exclusive crew of animals that get the concept of zero', 'Honeybees can pass a test of ranking â€˜nothingâ€™ as less than one', 'Susan Milius', '2018-06-07', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/bees-join-exclusive-crew-animals-get-concept-zero?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'bees-join-exclusive-crew-animals-get-concept-zero', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060718_SM_honeybees_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Honeybees can pass a test of ranking â€˜nothingâ€™ as less than one</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-6e6e17de8fde27c32153d6c0a42fe33e">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/susan-milius">Susan Milius</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">4:58pm, June 7, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060718_SM_honeybees_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060718_SM_honeybees_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060718_SM_honeybees_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="honeybee experiment" title="BEE CHOSES NOTHINGÂ  Bees show some sense of the idea of zero, researchers say. Tests required the insects to choose between images with various numbers of dark shapes. ~~ S. Howard" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060718_SM_honeybees_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="honeybee experiment" title="BEE CHOSES NOTHINGÂ  Bees show some sense of the idea of zero, researchers say. Tests required the insects to choose between images with various numbers of dark shapes. ~~ S. Howard" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060718_SM_honeybees_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>BEE CHOSES NOTHING</strong>Â  Bees show some sense of the idea of zero, researchers say. Tests required the insects to choose between images with various numbers of dark shapes.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>S. Howard</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-05fe6ac3b8e08f23d3512029391dc691">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/july-7-2018">Vol. 194, No. 1, July 7, 2018, p. 7</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>A little brain can be surprisingly good at nothing. Honeybees are the first invertebrates to pass a test of recognizing where zero goes in numerical order, a new study finds.</p><p>Even small children struggle with recognizing â€œnothingâ€ as being less than one, says cognitive behavioral scientist Scarlett Howard of the Royal Melbourne Institute of Technology in Australia. But honeybees trained to fly to images of greater or fewer dots or whazzits <a href="http://science.sciencemag.org/cgi/doi/10.1126/science.aar4975">tended to rank a blank image as less than one</a>, Howard and colleagues report in the June 8 <em>Science</em>.</p><p>Despite decades of discoveries, nonhuman animals still donâ€™t get due credit outside specialist circles for intelligence, laments Lars Chittka of Queen Mary University of London, who has explored various mental capacities of bees. For the world at large, he emphasizes that the abilities described in the new paper are â€œremarkable.â€</p><p>Researchers recognize several levels of complexity in grasping zero. Most animals, or maybe all, can understand the simplest level â€” just recognizing that the absence of something differs from its presence, Howard says. Grasping the notion that absence could fit into a sequence of quantities, though, seems harder. Previously, only some primates such as chimps and vervet monkeys, plus an African gray parrot named Alex, <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/animals-give-clues-origins-human-number-crunching?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">have demonstrated this level of understanding of the concept of zero</a> (<em>SN: 12/10/16, p. 22</em>).</p><p>The researchers first trained bees to visit a spot with either a Y-shaped maze or an upright display, both offering images with different numbers of elements, such as dark circles of different sizes. Some bees were trained to fly to the image with the lower numbers of objects, while other bees were taught to go to the higher-number image. The researchers offered the bees a sweet treat for the correct image, and a bitter quinine solution for a wrong answer.</p><p>â€œI was fairly afraid of bees when I began working with them,â€ Howard says. But learning their ways convinced her that a lot of what humans mistake for aggression from a foraging bee buzzing around is usually â€œjust curiosity.â€</p><p>The trained bees then performed a series of tests with no rewards. In one test that offered the bees a choice between a single shape image versus a blank image, bees trained to pick the lower number of objects flew to the blank image â€” the zero â€” 63 percent of time. Overall, the test results showed the bees treating zero as being less than one, Howard says.</p><p>The results convince evolutionary behavioral biologist Rafael RodrÃ­guez of the University of Wisconsinâ€“Milwaukee that honeybees are indeed getting the basics of zero. Now heâ€™s wondering about earlier studies that might hint that certain spiders would be worth testing, too.</p><p>Still, the most sophisticated sense of zero, using a symbol for it in mathematical calculation, is a feat only humans have demonstrated. So far. Howard muses about the possibility of someday testing beesâ€™ prowess on that harder feat.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>S.R. Howard et al. <a href="http://science.sciencemag.org/cgi/doi/10.1126/science.aar4975">Numerical ordering of zero in honey bees</a>. <em>Science.</em> Vol. 360, June 8, 2018, p. 1124. doi:10.1126/science.aar4975.</p><p>I.M. Pepperburg and J.D. Gordon. <a href="http://psycnet.apa.org/buy/2005-06515-008">Number comprehension by a grey parrot (<em>Psittacus erithacus</em>), including a zero-like concept</a>. <em>Journal of Comparative Psychology</em>. Vol. 119, May 2005, 197.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>P. Skorupski et al. <a href="http://rstb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/373/1740/20160513">Counting insects.</a> <em>Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B</em>. Vol. 373, February 19, 2018. doi:10.1098/rstb.2016.0513.</p><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/animals-give-clues-origins-human-number-crunching?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Animals give clues to the origins of human number crunching</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 190, December 10, 2016, p. 22.</p><p>D. Ansari and I.M. Lyons.Â <a href="http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11858-016-0782-z">Cognitive neuroscience and mathematics learning: how far have we come? Where do we need to go?</a>Â <em>ZDM</em>. Vol. 48, June 2016, p. 379. doi: 10.1007/s11858-016-0782-z.</p><p>M. Dacke and M.V. Srinivasan.Â <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10071-008-0159-y">Evidence for in counting in insects</a>.Â <em>Animal Cognition</em>.Â Vol. 11, October 2008, p. 683. doi: 10.1007/s10071-008-0159-y.</p><p>B. Bower.Â <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/tots-who-tote-babies-show-neural-signs-budding-number-sense?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Tots who tote: Babies show neural signs of budding number sense</a>.Â <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 173, February 9, 2008, p. 84.Â </p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Bees join an exclusive crew of animals that get the concept of zero " class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        ');
INSERT INTO `news` (`id`, `title`, `subtitle`, `author`, `date`, `url`, `slug`, `image`, `content`) VALUES
(35, 'In a conservation catch-22, efforts to save quolls might endanger them', 'After 13 generations isolated from predators, the northern quoll lost its fear of them', 'Leah Rosenbaum', '2018-06-07', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/conservation-catch-22-efforts-save-quolls-might-endanger-them?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'conservation-catch-22-efforts-save-quolls-might-endanger-them', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060618_lr_quoll_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>After 13 generations isolated from predators, the northern quoll lost its fear of them</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-906fa657a6f38572d4cc1abd46f89591">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/leah-rosenbaum">Leah Rosenbaum</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">12:33pm, June 7, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060618_lr_quoll_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060618_lr_quoll_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060618_lr_quoll_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="two northern quolls" title="UNAFRAID Â Conservationists isolated a population of northern quolls, such as these pictured, on a predator-free island to attempt to build back their numbers. After 13 generations, the quolls lost their fear response to predators. ~~ Jonathan Webb" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060618_lr_quoll_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="two northern quolls" title="UNAFRAID Â Conservationists isolated a population of northern quolls, such as these pictured, on a predator-free island to attempt to build back their numbers. After 13 generations, the quolls lost their fear response to predators. ~~ Jonathan Webb" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060618_lr_quoll_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>UNAFRAID</strong> Â Conservationists isolated a population of northern quolls, such as these pictured, on a predator-free island to attempt to build back their numbers. After 13 generations, the quolls lost their fear response to predators.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Jonathan Webb</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-b031a044da22f5a0fd78484f7cd82d50">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/july-7-2018">Vol. 194, No. 1, July 7, 2018, p. 7</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Conservationists are stuck in a catch-22: In trying to save some species, the would-be protectors may be giving the animals an evolutionary disadvantage. A new study describes how efforts to protect the endangered northern quoll, a spotted, kitten-sized marsupial native to Australia, by placing a population on a threat-free island may have actually undermined a key survival instinct.</p><p>After 13 generations â€” just 13 years â€” in isolation, the northern quolls (<em>Dasyurus hallucatus</em>) had <a href="http://rsbl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/14/6/20180222">lost their fear response</a> to native predators, researchers report June 5 in <em>Biology Letters</em>.</p><p>â€œEvolution can happen very rapidlyâ€ for animals with fast breeding times, says evolutionary biologist Rick Shine of the University of Sydney, who was not involved in the study.Â </p><p>Separating endangered species from predators is a common conservation technique, sometimes taking place in captive-breeding programs in zoos or fenced enclosures or on isolated islands. The approach allows a species to build up its population before eventually being reintroduced to the wild.</p><p>Populations of northern quolls have been drastically reduced in recent decades by <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/cane-toads-can-handle-cool?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">invasive poisonous cane toads</a> (<em>SN Online: 2/3/14</em>). In 2003, the Australian Northern Territory Government tried to preserve the quolls in part by moving 45 of them to toad-free Astell Island, off mainland Australiaâ€™s northern coast.</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060618_lr_quoll_toad_inline_370.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060618_lr_quoll_toad_inline_370.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="a cane toad" class="caption" style="width: 370px; height: 247px; float: right;" title="&lt;b&gt;INVADER&lt;/b&gt;  Northern quolls were isolated to protect them from poisonous cane toads, an invasive species responsible for killing many native animals. ~~ Chris Jolly" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060618_lr_quoll_toad_inline_370.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053" alt="a cane toad" class="caption" style="width: 370px; height: 247px; float: right;" title="&lt;b&gt;INVADER&lt;/b&gt;  Northern quolls were isolated to protect them from poisonous cane toads, an invasive species responsible for killing many native animals. ~~ Chris Jolly" /></noscript> </div> In 2016, biologist Christopher Jolly of the University of Melbourne and colleagues tried to reintroduce some quolls from Astell to the mainland. But the effort was quickly halted after <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/cats-and-foxes-are-driving-australia%E2%80%99s-mammals-extinct?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">dingoes and feral cats killed</a> many of the new arrivals (<em>SN Online: 2/11/15</em>).<p>In trying to figure out what happened, the researchers tested the fear responses of four populations of quolls: wild mainland quolls, island-born quolls and offspring from both groups. Quolls from each group were given boxes of mealworms; some had no scent and some were tainted with the scent of either feral cats or dingoes. While the wild quolls shied away from the predator-scented worms, the island quolls slurped the worms down. The quoll babies in each group showed the same behavior as the adults, suggesting the lost fear response was not learned but had evolved over 13 generations.</p><p>The studyâ€™s findings may have implications for other animals as well, as Australia grapples with how to conserve an increasing number of threatened and endangered species. â€œFor many of Australiaâ€™s mammals, the future is fenced,â€ says Alexandra Carthey, an ecologist at Macquarie University in Sydney who was not involved in the study.</p><p>There may be a few other solutions. Quolls could possibly be <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/aec.12551">trained to avoid the cane toad</a>, and then wouldnâ€™t need to be taken from their native habitat, according to a study by Jolly and colleagues published last October in <em>Austral Ecology</em>. Or, a small number of predators could be added to the isolation locations â€” not enough to threaten the quollsâ€™ proliferation, but enough to put the fear back into them.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>C. Jolly, J. Webb and B. Phillips. <a href="http://rsbl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/14/6/20180222">The perils of paradise: An endangered species conserved on an island loses antipredator behaviors within 13 generations</a>. <em>Biology Letters</em>. Published online June 6, 2018. doi: 10.1098/rsbl.2018.0222.</p><p>C. Jolly et al. <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/epdf/10.1111/aec.12551">Out of the frying pan: Reintroduction of toad-smart northern quolls to southern Kakadu National Park</a>. <em>Austral Ecology</em>. Vol 43, October 24 2017, p. 139-149. doi: 10.1111/aec.12551.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/running-quolls?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">The running of the quolls</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 187, March 21, 2015, p. 4.</p><p>S. Zielinski. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/cane-toads-can-handle-cool?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Cane toads can handle the cool</a>. <em>Science News</em> Online, February 3, 2014.</p><p>S. Zielinski. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/wild-things/cats-and-foxes-are-driving-australia%E2%80%99s-mammals-extinct?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Cats and foxes are driving Australiaâ€™s mammals extinct</a>. <em>Science News</em> Online, February 11, 2015.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="In a conservation catch-22, efforts to save quolls might endanger them" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(36, 'Conversations with Maya: Gideon Yu', '', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sponsored/conversations-maya-gideon-yu?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'conversations-maya-gideon-yu', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/03/Yu_Gideon.JPG', '     <div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/03/Yu_Gideon.JPG" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/03/Yu_Gideon.JPG" width="4896" height="3264" alt="Gideon Yu is the Executive Chairman at Bowers &amp; Wilkins and the co-owner of the San Francisco 49ers. Photo courtesy of the San Francisco 49ers." /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/03/Yu_Gideon.JPG" width="4896" height="3264" alt="Gideon Yu is the Executive Chairman at Bowers &amp; Wilkins and the co-owner of the San Francisco 49ers. Photo courtesy of the San Francisco 49ers." /></noscript></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Gideon Yu is the Executive Chairman at Bowers &amp; Wilkins and the co-owner of the San Francisco 49ers. Photo courtesy of the San Francisco 49ers.</p></div></div></div><span property="dc:title" content="Conversations with Maya: Gideon Yu" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span><p>Maya Ajmera, President &amp; CEO of Society for Science &amp; the Public and Publisher of <em>Science News</em>, sat down to chat with Gideon Yu, co-owner and former President of the San Francisco 49ers, Executive Chairman of Bowers &amp; Wilkins and former CFO at Facebook and YouTube. We are thrilled to share an edited summary of the conversation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>I would love to start by discussing your experience as an International Science and Engineering Fair (ISEF) finalist in 1989. </strong></p><p>Before I share my experience, I do want to make one acknowledgement to Professor David Wilson of Vanderbilt, who unfortunately passed away last year. He was a local legend in Nashville. He was a chemistry professor who gave back to the community by offering local students the ability to apply their math aptitude in the lab.</p><p>I had just won an Algebra 1 math contest, and this older gentleman came up to me and said: &ldquo;Hey, would you like to apply your math? There&rsquo;s this competition called the International Science and Engineering Fair, and if you can commit to me for a few years, when you&rsquo;re a junior or senior, you can apply to that competition. If you stick with me and give me your best, you will do well there.&rdquo;</p><p>So that summer we went through trigonometry, calculus and differential equations. When you&rsquo;re a kid, you don&rsquo;t appreciate the time that adults put into you. But now in hindsight, I don&rsquo;t know where he found the time or the energy to give me all that effort.</p><p><img alt="" class="caption" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/gideonyu.jpg" style="width: 750px; height: 500px;" title="Gideon Yu with his science fair awards. ~~ Photo courtesy of Gideon Yu." /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Mentors are so, so important in this work. You don&rsquo;t get anywhere without a mentor or teacher, especially when doing research. </strong></p><p>So, I just got finished winning the Tennessee state fair, which is a far cry from ISEF. Dr. Wilson sat me down and said, &ldquo;Look, the best projects from Tennessee have gotten third or second place, so you need to be happy with that.&rdquo;</p><p>I went to ISEF, which was in Pittsburgh that year, and was sitting in the Grand Awards Ceremony. Third place comes, no name. Second place comes, no name. Embarrassingly, I was very emotional that I didn&rsquo;t make it. I put my head down, and I had tears in my eyes. Some of the people at my table were consoling me.</p><p>There was a really awkward moment where the person sitting next to me said, &ldquo;Hey, didn&rsquo;t you say you were from Nashville?&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;Yeah.&rdquo; He said, &ldquo;I think they just called your name.&rdquo; I looked at him and said, &ldquo;That&rsquo;s not a funny joke.&rdquo; Then several of the other people around the table said, &ldquo;They just called you. Go up there!&rdquo; I went up to the stage with my hand covering my mouth, which was wide open. Everybody else was smiling, and I just looked like I was completely shocked and didn&rsquo;t think I belonged up there. I won the Grand Award in the environmental sciences category.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>You grew up the son of a minister in the South. You&rsquo;re Korean-American. Tell us about that, how those experiences and upbringing impacted your career path?</strong></p><p>In 1972, my parents decided to immigrate to Nashville from South Korea. I was 1 year old. In 2018, it&rsquo;s difficult to think back to what it was like in the Deep South at that time, but to put the region and time in context, the civil rights marches from Selma to Montgomery were in 1965, and they took place less than a day&rsquo;s drive from my home.</p><p>We immigrated with no money as an ethnic minority into the South when people were still facing discrimination regarding their civil rights. To have lived through that time, with my father as the pastor of my church and moral compass of our community &hellip; it was, how do I put it? It was tough. It was challenging, and it is something that I feel really shaped who I am today. More importantly, I would not have had it any other way.</p><p>I think when you grow up around racism, around racial and ethnic segregation, you realize that that the world is very aware of an individual&rsquo;s race. Adversity is a challenge, but it&rsquo;s also an opportunity and a fact of life.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>You&rsquo;ve had this incredible trajectory of working with the most well-known tech companies in the world. Yahoo, YouTube, Facebook. What was your guiding force along that path? Was it more about being at the right time at the right place or was there a larger plan?</strong></p><p>I wish that I could tell you that it was all planned out. And that I&rsquo;m smart enough to have figured that out, but that&rsquo;d be very imprecise.</p><p>Let me go backwards to answer this question a little bit. I got my undergraduate degree from Stanford and my MBA from Harvard. It was 1999 and I came out to Silicon Valley. I went to two start-ups as the CFO; both failed. I needed to figure out what my career path should be.</p><p>I realized that I didn&rsquo;t really feel passionate about either company and took those jobs because I thought they were good career moves. I decided that to the extent that I was lucky enough to have a choice, my future career moves would be consistent with things that I am passionate about.</p><p>Is it right place, right moment? Look, to the extent that that phrase indicates a humility and an understanding that you work really hard and then you get some good breaks, then absolutely, it was right place, right time. But I will tell you this: My overarching strategy was, if I&rsquo;m going to fail, I might as well fail doing something that I love.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>So, let&rsquo;s talk about football and how you ended up becoming president and co-owner of the San Francisco 49ers in 2012. </strong></p><p>The traditional career path to become a president in the NFL is certainly not science and finance. I&rsquo;ll tell you, Maya, that the comment I just made a little bit ago about following your passions is really what put me on the path to the NFL. I love football. I was on a charity board with the owners of the 49ers, and after a meeting commented that I had read they were having a difficult time raising the financing to build a new stadium. I offered to help, and a few months later they took me up on my offer. I made some suggestions, and they asked me to join them.</p><p>I took the plunge and was later named president of the team and was offered a chance to buy into the team. Although I&rsquo;m no longer president, I remain a co-owner of the team.</p><p>To become an owner in the NFL, or even a co-owner, you must be voted in by all the other NFL owners. When I was voted in, they noted that I was going to be the first ethnic minority president in the history of the NFL. After the vote, Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones shook my hand and said, &ldquo;Welcome to the club. This is history.&rdquo; That&rsquo;s the moment when all of the hard work is worth it.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Do you remember any books in high school that got you excited, and what are you reading now?</strong></p><p>In high school, the book that I read that just blew my mind was <em>A Brief History of Time</em> by Stephen Hawking. Outside of the Bible, I don&rsquo;t think there&rsquo;s been a book that&rsquo;s had more impact in my life. Reading Stephen Hawking&rsquo;s book made me realize that you can pull together all these topics you learn in high school &mdash; not just math and science, but also philosophy and religion. You realize the world is a cosmically big place.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Lastly, with so many challenges in front of us as a world, what keeps you up at night?</strong></p><p>I think we are forgetting how to be kind and compassionate to one another. In 2018, it&rsquo;s much more fashionable to show outrage, to be critical. Even though I have worked for some groundbreaking social media companies, I think social media tends to amplify this trend by highlighting the loudest and the craziest among us. Compassion and kindness don&rsquo;t get the headlines. If we don&rsquo;t watch out, this trend can get away from us. If we can&rsquo;t work together and be kind and understanding to each other, I don&rsquo;t see how we&rsquo;re going to have a chance to fix our biggest problems.</p>  '),
(37, 'Dogs carry a surprising variety of flu viruses', 'Thereâ€™s no evidence yet that the canine pathogens infect people', 'Tina Hesman Saey', '2018-06-05', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/dogs-carry-surprising-variety-flu-viruses?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'dogs-carry-surprising-variety-flu-viruses', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060518_TS_dog-flu_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Thereâ€™s no evidence yet that the canine pathogens infect people</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-3beba11041152b3139f1435b2ebbf74e">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/tina-hesman-saey">Tina Hesman Saey</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">2:37pm, June 5, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060518_TS_dog-flu_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060518_TS_dog-flu_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060518_TS_dog-flu_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="dog" title="DOGGING IT Â Some dogs in southern China carry flu viruses originally transmitted from pigs. The viruses probably spread most easily where animals are crowded, such as shelters, farms and markets. ~~ Lindsay Helms/Shutterstock" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060518_TS_dog-flu_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="dog" title="DOGGING IT Â Some dogs in southern China carry flu viruses originally transmitted from pigs. The viruses probably spread most easily where animals are crowded, such as shelters, farms and markets. ~~ Lindsay Helms/Shutterstock" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060518_TS_dog-flu_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><b>DOGGING IT</b> Â Some dogs in southern China carry flu viruses originally transmitted from pigs. The viruses probably spread most easily where animals are crowded, such as shelters, farms and markets.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Lindsay Helms/Shutterstock</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-b952a37c0c9c095c144a26ccc41e63c7">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/july-7-2018">Vol. 194, No. 1, July 7, 2018, p. 8</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Some dogs in China carry a mixed bag of influenza viruses. The discovery raises the possibility that dogs may be able to pass the flu to people, perhaps setting off a pandemic.</p><p>About 15 percent of pet dogs that went to the vet because of respiratory infections <a href="http://mbio.asm.org/content/9/3/e00909-18">carried flu viruses often found in pigs</a>, researchers report June 5 in <em>mBio</em>. Of the virus strains detected, three have recombined in dogs to form new varieties.</p><p>That mixing generates genetic diversity in the viruses that makes them potentially a pandemic threat, says study coauthor Adolfo GarcÃ­a-Sastre, a virologist who directs the Global Health and Emerging Pathogens Institute of the Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai in New York City.</p><p>Evolution of the flu viruses in dogs has been very rapid, occurring in just a few years, GarcÃ­a-Sastre says. Thereâ€™s no sign yet that the dog flu viruses can infect people, but that could change. â€œThe more diversity of viruses there is in an animal reservoir, the higher the chances that it will lead to a version of the virus that is able to jumpâ€ to humans, he says.</p><p>Pigs and birds remain the prime suspects for mixing up the next human pandemic influenza virus, says Amesh Adalja, an infectious disease physician at Johns Hopkins University and a spokesperson for the Infectious Diseases Society of America. Even if a dog flu virus infected a person, the pathogen may not be able to transmit easily from person-to-person â€” an important characteristic a virus must have before it can circulate around the world.</p><p>But because most people encounter dog noses far more frequently than those of pigs, itâ€™s worth keeping an eye on the pups, Adalja says. â€œKnowing that dogs could contribute is important for preparing for the next pandemic, because we donâ€™t know exactly what that virus will be,â€ he says.</p><p>The first flu virus in dogs was discovered in 2005 in the United States. That pathogen, <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/flu-horses-racing-among-dogs?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">from a horse flu virus called H3N8 that had jumped to canines</a>, sometimes spreads among pooches in shelters (<em>SN: 10/8/05, p. 237</em>). And, in 2010, some dogs in Asia were found carrying a version of the H3N2 virus from birds. (Cats can catch the dog H3N2 flu virus, but donâ€™t transmit it to other cats, as far as scientists know.)</p><p>In the new study, the team swabbed the noses of 800 dogs in the Guangxi region of southern China from 2013 to 2015. All of the dogs had respiratory illnesses, but only 116 were infected with influenza viruses. To the scientistsâ€™ surprise, the dogs had various swine H1N1 flu viruses. The researchers determined the genetic makeup of 16 of the samples and discovered that some of these swine viruses had previously circulated in people and pigs in Europe and Asia. Some are strains of bird flu that have infected pigs.</p><p>In pigs, the viruses swapped genes among themselves, creating new varieties, some of which were passed to dogs. A virus genetically similar to one of the swine viruses passed to dogs was found in a person in China, raising the possibility that some swine flus can strike both pups and people. Dogs remixed some of the viruses from the pigs with bits of the dog flu virus in Asia, creating the three new canine influenza virus strains, the researchers found.</p><p>Since the study collected samples from only one part of China, the team doesnâ€™t know how widespread flu is among dogs, or how many canine-infecting influenzas may be out there.</p><p>Finding flu viruses in dogs isnâ€™t cause for alarm. But researchers should monitor the situation and use vaccines, quarantine and other infection-control methods to limit outbreaks and keep the canine viruses from catching hold in humans, GarcÃ­a-Sastre says.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>Y. Chen <em>et al</em>. <a href="http://mbio.asm.org/content/9/3/e00909-18">Emergence and evolution of novel reassortant influenza A viruses in canines in Southern China</a>. <em>mBio</em>. Vol. 9, June 5, 2018. doi:10.1128/mBio.00909-18.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>L. Hamers. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/next-wave-bird-flu-could-be-worse-ever?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">The next wave of bird flu could be worse than ever</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 192, November 11, 2017, p. 9.</p><p>T.H. Saey. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/chickens-blame-spread-latest-deadly-bird-flu?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Chickens to blame for spread of latest deadly bird flu</a>. Science News Online. March 11, 2015.</p><p>T.H. Saey. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/new-swine-flu-virus-could-infect-people?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">New swine flu virus could infect people</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 182, October 20, 2012, p. 20.</p><p>L. Sanders. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/swine-and-men?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Of swine and men</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 177, February 27, 2010, p. 22.</p><p>B. Harder. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/flu-horses-racing-among-dogs?mode=magazine&amp;context=197053">Flu from horses is racing among dogs</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 168, October 8, 2005, p. 237.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Dogs carry a surprising variety of flu viruses" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(38, 'â€˜Outbreakâ€™ puts the life cycle of an epidemic on display', 'A new Smithsonian exhibit highlights how infectious diseases shape our world', 'Laurel Hamers', '2018-06-04', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/outbreak-exhibit-puts-life-cycle-epidemic-display?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'outbreak-exhibit-puts-life-cycle-epidemic-display', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060918_LH_exhibit_outbreak_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2> A new Smithsonian exhibit highlights how infectious diseases shape our world </h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-63c025e2205595355bc96e3d203546b3">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/laurel-hamers">Laurel Hamers</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">7:00am, June 4, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060918_LH_exhibit_outbreak_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060918_LH_exhibit_outbreak_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060918_LH_exhibit_outbreak_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="" title="SOCIAL EPIDEMICÂ  In a new Smithsonian exhibit, activist signs and buttons from the AIDS epidemic highlight some of the social consequences of infectious disease outbreaks. ~~ James Di Loreto and Lucia RM Martino/Smithsonian Institution" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060918_LH_exhibit_outbreak_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="" title="SOCIAL EPIDEMICÂ  In a new Smithsonian exhibit, activist signs and buttons from the AIDS epidemic highlight some of the social consequences of infectious disease outbreaks. ~~ James Di Loreto and Lucia RM Martino/Smithsonian Institution" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/06/main/articles/060918_LH_exhibit_outbreak_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>SOCIAL EPIDEMICÂ  </strong>In a new Smithsonian exhibit, activist signs and buttons from the AIDS epidemic highlight some of the social consequences of infectious disease outbreaks.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>James Di Loreto and Lucia RM Martino/Smithsonian Institution</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-f6a1fda026388501ca20953151026310">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/june-9-2018">Vol. 193, No. 10, June 9, 2018, p. 28</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>In 1918, a pandemic of Spanish flu killed as much as 5 percent of the worldâ€™s population. A hundred years later, scientists know much more about how to prevent and treat such diseases. But in some ways, the threat of a global outbreak is greater than ever. All it takes is one plane ride for a few localized cases of a disease to become an epidemic.</p><p>A new exhibit at the Smithsonian National Museum of Natural History in Washington, D.C., traces the way infectious diseases still shape our world. The exhibit, called â€œ<a href="http://naturalhistory.si.edu/exhibits/outbreak/">Outbreak: Epidemics in a Connected World</a>,â€ is centered around the concept of One Health â€” the idea that the health of humans, other animals and the environment are all intertwined, so <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/oral-vaccines-could-save-ethiopian-wolves-extinction?mode=topic&amp;context=76">protecting one requires protecting all</a> (<em>SN: 3/31/18, p. 20</em>).</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/060918_LH_exhibit_outbreak_inline_370.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=76" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/060918_LH_exhibit_outbreak_inline_370.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=76" alt="" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 554px;" title="&lt;b&gt;ONE HEALTH&lt;/b&gt;Â Â â€œOutbreakâ€ explains how the health of humans and other animals are interconnected. Tracking animal diseases before they jump to people is one way to prevent some future epidemics. ~~ James Di Loreto and Lucia RM Martino/Smithsonian Institution" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/060918_LH_exhibit_outbreak_inline_370.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=76" alt="" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 554px;" title="&lt;b&gt;ONE HEALTH&lt;/b&gt;Â Â â€œOutbreakâ€ explains how the health of humans and other animals are interconnected. Tracking animal diseases before they jump to people is one way to prevent some future epidemics. ~~ James Di Loreto and Lucia RM Martino/Smithsonian Institution" /></noscript> </div> News coverage of disease outbreaks often focuses on the deaths they cause, notes Jonathan Epstein of EcoHealth Alliance, the exhibitâ€™s chief science adviser. One goal of the exhibit, he says, is â€œto give the public a look at how these things get started.â€ With that in mind, â€œOutbreakâ€ highlights a handful of epidemics that have occurred in the last century, using each as a jumping off point to explore different aspects of preventing, tracing, treating and containing infectious diseases.<p>In addition to zeroing in on epidemics that have made international headlines, including <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/year-review-science-faces-ebola-epidemic?mode=topic&amp;context=76">Ebola</a> and SARS, the exhibit features lesser-known diseases. Nipah virus, for instance, has infected people in Bangladesh who have drunk sweet date palm sap contaminated by infected bats. Simple preventive measures like encouraging people not to drink the raw sap or to filter it, so far, have prevented the virus from sparking an epidemic.</p><p>â€œOutbreakâ€ is more focused on text and interactive screens than on artifacts, which makes sense given the microscopic subjects. But the exhibit does draw on the Smithsonianâ€™s extensive collections, showcasing arrays of preserved infectious disease vectors, such as ticks and mosquitoes, as well as bat and macaque specimens. As these display cases explain, monitoring the health of animal populations helps researchers put preventive measures in place before emerging infectious diseases can jump to humans.</p><p>As an entry point for discussing the social side of disease and the stigma that infected people can face, a collection of buttons and signs from AIDS activists recalls the fight for public recognition and government action in the 1980s and â€™90s.</p><div class="inline-content inline-content-right clearfix"><h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>â€œ<a href="http://naturalhistory.si.edu/exhibits/outbreak/">Outbreak</a>â€</strong></h4><div class="inline-content-copy"><h5 style="text-align: center;">Through 2021</h5><h5 style="text-align: center;">Smithsonian National Museum of Natural History |Â <em>Washington, D.C.</em></h5></div></div><p>The content on display might not be a good fit for very young children, but interactive games and activities throughout increase the exhibitâ€™s overall kid appeal. In one game, played on touch screens, players each pick from a variety of roles â€” such as epidemiologist, wildlife biologist or community worker â€” and then cooperate to complete tasks that stem the tide of a fictional outbreak. (Itâ€™s a good example of the broader message that stopping infectious diseases requires collaboration from many different kinds of experts.)</p><p>In case Washington isnâ€™t on your travel agenda, the Smithsonian is translating the content into multiple languages and sharing it with libraries, community centers and other institutions around the world to help them create their own pared-down versions of the exhibit.</p></span></div></div></div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="â€˜Outbreakâ€™ puts the life cycle of an epidemic on display" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        ');
