(39, 'The first land-walking vertebrates may have emerged from salty estuaries', 'An analysis casts doubt on views that the ancient creatures arose in freshwater', 'Carolyn Gramling', '2018-05-30', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/first-tetrapods-may-have-emerged-salty-estuaries?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'first-tetrapods-may-have-emerged-salty-estuaries', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_CG_tetrapod_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>An analysis casts doubt on views that the ancient creatures arose in freshwater</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-eb7ff2fef813ccf93207cdb634a96386">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/carolyn-gramling">Carolyn Gramling</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">5:29pm, May 30, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_CG_tetrapod_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_CG_tetrapod_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_CG_tetrapod_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="tetrapod illustration" title="SALTY SCENEÂ  The planetâ€™s earliest four-footed vertebrates called tetrapods (illustrated) lived in the brackish waters of an estuary or delta, new research suggests. ~~ Mazan" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_CG_tetrapod_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="tetrapod illustration" title="SALTY SCENEÂ  The planetâ€™s earliest four-footed vertebrates called tetrapods (illustrated) lived in the brackish waters of an estuary or delta, new research suggests. ~~ Mazan" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_CG_tetrapod_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><b>SALTY SCENE</b>Â  The planetâ€™s earliest four-footed vertebrates called tetrapods (illustrated) lived in the brackish waters of an estuary or delta, new research suggests.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>Mazan</p></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>Earthâ€™s earliest land-walking vertebrates didnâ€™t paddle about in freshwater lakes or rivers. Instead, these four-footed creatures, which appeared about 375 million years ago, lived in the brackish waters of an estuary or delta, researchers report online May 30 in <em>Nature.</em></p><p>Early tetrapods, such as <em>Ichthyostega</em> and <em>Acanthostega,</em> <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-018-0159-2">lived an amphibious existence between land and sea</a>: They had feet, but also gills and tails made for swimming. A new study by paleontologist Jean Goedert of UniversitÃ© Lyon in France and colleagues suggests that the animals also could have tolerated rapid changes in salinity, such as is found in an estuary.</p><p>The researchers analyzed sulfur and oxygen isotopes â€” forms of these elements with the same number of protons, but different masses â€” in 51 fossilized tetrapod bones from locations in whatâ€™s now Greenland and China. Compared with freshwater, seawater has a higher ratio of the sulfur-34 isotope relative to sulfur-32. The tetrapod bones tended to show elevated sulfur-34, the researchers report, suggesting that the creatures spent at least some time in seawater. But oxygen isotope analyses of the bones show that freshwater was also present, arguing against a purely salty environment such as an ocean.</p><p>The results challenge a long-held view that the earliest tetrapods emerged from freshwaters, such as rivers or lakes. In 1929, the first <em>Ichthyostega</em> fossils were found in a series of red sandstone layers in eastern Greenland that geologists once thought had been deposited in a freshwater environment. But later discoveries of tetrapod fossils found associated with known marine species suggested that the early walkers may have lived in saltier waters than once thought.</p><p>An ability to tolerate different salinity environments could have helped tetrapods â€” a group that includes todayâ€™s amphibians, reptiles and mammals â€” survive a mass extinction of ocean-dwellers that occurred by the end of the Devonian Period about 359 million years ago, the researchers say.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>J. Goedert <em>et al</em>. <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-018-0159-2">Euryhaline ecology of early tetrapods revealed by stable isotopes</a>. <em>Nature</em>. Published online May 30, 2018. doi:10.1038/s41586-018-0159-2.Â </p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>D. Garisto. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/wiring-walking-developed-long-fish-left-sea?mode=topic&amp;context=76">The wiring for walking developed long before fish left the sea</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 193, March 17, 2018, p. 10.</p><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/preteen-tetrapods-identified-bone-scans?mode=topic&amp;context=76">Preteen tetrapods identified by bone scans</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 190, October 15, 2016, p. 12.</p><p>S. Milius. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/hightailing-it-out-water-mudskipper-style?mode=topic&amp;context=76">Hightailing it out of the water, mudskipper style</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 190, August 6, 2016, p. 13.</p><p>S. Perkins. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/amphibious-ancestors?mode=topic&amp;context=76">Amphibious ancestors</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 169, June 17, 2006, p. 379.</p><p>R. Monastersky. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/archive/out-swamps?mode=topic&amp;context=76">Out of the swamps</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 155, May 22, 1999.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="The first land-walking vertebrates may have emerged from salty estuaries" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(40, 'Oldest known lizard fossil pushes groupâ€™s origins back 75 million years', 'CT scan reveals identity of ancient remains found years ago in the Italian Alps', 'Susan Milius', '2018-05-30', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/oldest-known-lizard-fossil-pushes-origins-back-75-million-years?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'oldest-known-lizard-fossil-pushes-origins-back-75-million-years', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_SM_lizard-fossil_feat.jpg', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>CT scan reveals identity of ancient remains found years ago in the Italian Alps</h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-bd54e55ae601643662485b3e5ad1d241">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/susan-milius">Susan Milius</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">4:24pm, May 30, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:associatedMedia schema:associatedMedia" resource="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_SM_lizard-fossil_feat.jpg"><div itemprop="image" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_SM_lizard-fossil_feat.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_SM_lizard-fossil_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="lizard-snake fossil" title="NEW OLDEST LIZARD Â New details revealed by a CT scan helped identify a 240-million-year-old fossil called Megachirella wachtleri (shown) as the oldest known member of the lizard-snake lineage. ~~ MUSE - Science Museum, Trento, Italy" /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_SM_lizard-fossil_feat.jpg" width="860" height="460" alt="lizard-snake fossil" title="NEW OLDEST LIZARD Â New details revealed by a CT scan helped identify a 240-million-year-old fossil called Megachirella wachtleri (shown) as the oldest known member of the lizard-snake lineage. ~~ MUSE - Science Museum, Trento, Italy" /></noscript><meta itemprop="url" content="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_SM_lizard-fossil_feat.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="860"><meta itemprop="height" content="460"></div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><b>NEW OLDEST LIZARD Â </b>New details revealed by a CT scan helped identify a 240-million-year-old fossil called <i>Megachirella wachtleri </i>(shown) as the oldest known member of the lizard-snake lineage.</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-sn-copyright field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>MUSE - Science Museum, Trento, Italy</p></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-b1eb305f0ce496a74f1ebeb0af1501c1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/june-23-2018">Vol. 193, No. 11, June 23, 2018, p. 6</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><p>A little animal that washed out to sea 240 million years ago off the coast of whatâ€™s now Italy turns out to be the oldest known fossil of a lizard.</p><p>The identification pushes back the fossil record of snakes and lizards by about 75 million years, says Tiago SimÃµes of the University of Alberta in Edmonton, Canada. He and colleagues used observations of the fossil, called <em>Megachirella wachtleri</em>, and of related living and extinct species plus genetic data <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-018-0093-3">to reconstruct the evolutionary history of squamates</a>, the reptile group that today includes snakes and lizards, the researchers report in the May 31 <em>Nature</em>.</p><p>â€œUnderstanding lizard and snake evolution has been a constant problem in paleontology,â€ says vertebrate paleontologist Stephanie Pierce of Harvard University who worked on the issue years ago but wasnâ€™t involved in the new study. The trouble comes largely from a lack of relevant fossils, she says. That dearth isnâ€™t just because little animals donâ€™t fossilize as readily as big ones do. â€œThings like giant dinosaurs â€” theyâ€™re pretty easy to spot,â€ she says. â€œBut if youâ€™re looking for something that can fit in the palm of your hand, that makes it very challenging.â€</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_SM_lizard-fossil_inline_370.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=194583" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_SM_lizard-fossil_inline_370.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=194583" alt="Megachirella wachtleri" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 483px;" title="&lt;b&gt;EARLY ITALIAN&lt;/b&gt;  The oldest known lizard &lt;em&gt;Megachirella wachtleri&lt;/em&gt; (seen in an artistâ€™s illustration) probably hunted insects among ancient plants in whatâ€™s now Italy. ~~ Davide Bonadonna " /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/053018_SM_lizard-fossil_inline_370.jpg?mode=magazine&amp;context=194583" alt="Megachirella wachtleri" class="caption" style="float: right; width: 370px; height: 483px;" title="&lt;b&gt;EARLY ITALIAN&lt;/b&gt;  The oldest known lizard &lt;em&gt;Megachirella wachtleri&lt;/em&gt; (seen in an artistâ€™s illustration) probably hunted insects among ancient plants in whatâ€™s now Italy. ~~ Davide Bonadonna " /></noscript> </div> A collector found <em>M. wachtleri</em> almost 20 years ago in a part of the Italian Alps that had once been underwater. But researchers didnâ€™t categorize itÂ as a full member of the squamate branch of reptiles, until now. The sole specimen is partly embedded in rock, which obscured some of the creatureâ€™s telltale features. Now a CT scan has revealed previously unknown squamate details of its palate, braincase, limbs and shoulder, SimÃµes says.<p><em>M. wachtleri</em> was a small, terrestrial animal with teeth appropriate for snapping up insects, he says. Yet a catastrophe such as a tropical storm apparently swept it out to sea along with masses of leaves.</p><p>Besides taking a closer look at <em>M. wachtleri</em>, SimÃµes and some colleagues traveled to 17 countries from Brazil to China to reexamine the other known squamate fossils. Combining all of the new fossil measurements with DNA data, the researchers reconstructed the evolutionary tree of squamates. Among the new insights: Geckos appear to be the most ancient of still-surviving lizards, the team found. And iguanas, a hard-to-place group on the tree, have a more recent origin than some other studies have found.</p><p>â€œThe picture is coming together,â€ says study coauthor Oksana Vernygora, an evolutionary biologist also at the University of Alberta.</p><p>Previously, the oldest known squamate fossils dated back about to 168 million years ago. Adding <em>M. wachtleri</em> to the mix means that the squamates are so ancient that they arose before the mass extinction at the end of the Permian Period 252 million years ago, notes herpetologist and evolutionary biologist Jeff Streicher ofÂ the Natural History Museum in LondonÂ who was not involved in the study. That cataclysm came the closest (yet) to wiping out life on Earth. How the ancestors of modern lizards and snakes made it is still a matter of debate.</p></span></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"><div class="field field-name-field-article-citation field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Citations</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>T.R. SimÃµes <em>et al</em>. <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-018-0093-3">The origin of squamates revealed by a Middle Triassic lizard from the Italian Alps</a>. <em>Nature</em>. Vol. 557, May 31, 2018, p.706.Â  doi:10.1038/s41586-018-0093-3.</p></div>       </div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-article-reading field-type-text-long field-label-above">       <div class="field-label">Further Reading</div>     <div class="field-items">           <div class="field-item even"><p>J.W. Streicher and J.J. Wiens. <a href="http://rsbl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/13/9/20170393">Phylogenomic analyses of more than 4000 nuclear loci resolve the origin of snakes among lizard families</a>. <em>Biology Letters</em>. Vol. 13, September 13, 2017. doi:10.1098/rsbl.2017.0393.</p><p>A. McDermott. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/reptile-scales-share-evolutionary-origin-hair-feathers?mode=magazine&amp;context=194583">Reptile scales share evolutionary origin with hair, feathers</a>. <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 190, July 23, 2016, p. 13.</p><p>L. Hamers. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/why-turtle-got-its-shell?mode=magazine&amp;context=194583">Why the turtle got its shell</a>.Â  <em>Science News</em>. Vol. 190, August 6, 2016, p. 15.</p><p>K. Baggaley. <a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/search?st=snakes%20Jurassic%20dinosaurs&amp;mode=magazine&amp;context=194583">Snakes crawled among Jurassic dinosaurs, new timeline says</a>.Â  <em>Science News.</em> Vol. 187, February 21, 2015, p. 11.</p></div>       </div> </div> </div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Oldest known lizard fossil pushes groupâ€™s origins back 75 million years" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(41, 'Readers respond to pesticides, Hawking radiation and more', 'Your letters and comments on the April 14, 2018 issue of Science News', 'Science News Staff', '2018-05-30', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/article/readers-respond-pesticides-hawking-radiation-and-more?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'readers-respond-pesticides-hawking-radiation-and-more', 'https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as', '             <div class="field field-name-field-sn-subtitle"> 	<div class="field-items"> 		<div class="field-items-even">   			<h2>Your letters and comments on the April 14, 2018 issue of <em>Science News</em></h2>   		</div> 	</div> </div> <div class="field field-name-field-op-author field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="rnews:creator schema:creator"><div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-9fccac7c62934be69a0fa58149b26570">             <div class="view-header">       By    </div>                <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">          <span>        <span>  <div itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"> <span itemprop="name"><a href="/author/science-news-staff-0">Science News Staff</a></span> </div> </span>  </span>  </div>     </div>             <div class="attachment attachment-after">       <div class="view view-article-related-content view-id-article_related_content view-display-id-attachment_1">                      <div class="view-content">         <div>                  <span class="field-content">7:00am, May 30, 2018</span>    </div>     </div>                   </div>    </div>             </div></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-magazine-ref field-type-node-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><div class="view view-article-issue-info view-id-article_issue_info view-display-id-block view-dom-id-79524637fc2b02bdeda3e15fbdfec7a0">                      <div class="view-content">         <div class="views-row views-row-1">          <div class="views-field views-field-field-magazine-ref">    <span class="views-label views-label-field-magazine-ref">Magazine issue: </span>    <span class="field-content"><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/june-9-2018">Vol. 193, No. 10, June 9, 2018, p. 30</a></span>  </div>  </div>     </div>                   </div></div></div></div><div class="node addthis-block"><div class="block block-addthis block-addthis-block block-addthis-addthis-block even block-without-title" id="block-addthis-addthis-block">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style addthis_32x32_style addThisShow service-links"><ul class="links"><li class="service-links-EMail first"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_email service-links-EMail">Email</a> </li><li class="service-links-Print"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_print service-links-Print">Print</a> </li><li class="service-links-twitter"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_twitter service-links-twitter">Twitter</a> </li><li class="service-links-facebook"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_facebook service-links-facebook">Facebook</a> </li><li class="service-links-reddit"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_reddit service-links-reddit">Reddit</a> </li><li class="service-links-google-plus last"><a href="https://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=300" class="addthis_button_google_plusone_share service-links-google-plus">Google+</a> </li></ul></div>     </div>   </div> </div></div><div class="block-sn-ad-blog-wrapper"> <div class="block-sn-ad-blog-inner"> <div class="ad">Sponsor Message</div><div class="block block-sn-ad block-openpublish-article-node-ad block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad odd block-without-title" id="block-sn-ad-openpublish-article-node-ad">   <div class="block-inner clearfix">                  <div class="content clearfix">       <!-- AdSpeed.com Serving Code 7.9.5 for [Zone] SN-Drupal-300 300x250 --><iframe width="300" height="250" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=html&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;target=_top" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"   ><a href="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=clk&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" target="_top"><img style="border:0px;" src="https://g.adspeed.net/ad.php?do=img&amp;zid=47245&amp;wd=300&amp;ht=250&amp;pair=as" alt="i" width="300" height="250"/></a></iframe><!-- AdSpeed.com End -->    </div>   </div> </div> </div> </div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="rnews:articlebody schema:articleBody"><span itemprop="description"><h4><strong><a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/sn-magazine/april-14-2018?mode=topic&amp;context=43"><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/060918_feedback_cover.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=43" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/060918_feedback_cover.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=43" alt="April 14, 2018 issue of Science News" style="float: left; width: 150px; height: 194px;" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/060918_feedback_cover.jpg?mode=topic&amp;context=43" alt="April 14, 2018 issue of Science News" style="float: left; width: 150px; height: 194px;" /></noscript> </div> </a>Pesky pesticides</strong></h4><p><em>Researchers are tracking tiny insects to learn how animals move around the planet, <strong>Alexandra Witze</strong> reported in â€œ<a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/flying-insects-tell-tales-long-distance-migrations%5C?mode=topic&amp;context=43">Flying insects tell tales of long-distance migrations</a>â€ (</em>SN: 4/14/18, p. 22<em>). </em></p><p>â€œThere are several uncritical references to using pesticides to combat insect pestsâ€ in the story, reader <strong>Christina Gullion</strong> wrote.</p><p><strong>Gullion</strong> noted that pesticides can be harmful not just to pests, but also to the beneficial insects that provide crucial ecosystem services. â€œUse of pesticides is selecting for resistant pests, as well as an important factor in the decline of beneficial insect populations,â€ she wrote. â€œThis was not mentioned as one of the factors in their decline, yet it is the factor that is most easily within the control of growers and gardeners.â€ <strong>Gullion</strong> thought that <em>Science News</em> should report more on important developments in conservation and pest management in agriculture and horticulture.</p><div class="inline-content inline-content-right clearfix"><h4>Lost in translation</h4><div class="inline-content-copy"><p>A new calculation using the 1961 Drake Equation indicates that if signals from an alien civilization ever reach Earth, itâ€™s likely that the aliens will already be dead, <strong>Lisa Grossman</strong> reported in â€œ<a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/drake-equation-alien-extraterrestrial-civilizations?mode=topic&amp;context=43">We probably wonâ€™t hear from aliens. But by the time we do, theyâ€™ll be dead.</a>â€ (<em>SN: 4/14/18, p. 9</em>).</p><p>Twitter user <strong>@gparkeruk</strong> poked fun at alien dispatches, referencing gold-plated records (one shown) that carried messages from earthlings into space in the 1970s: â€œI worry that our first message from aliens will be on a big gold disc, and nobody will have a player.â€</p><p></p><div class="lz-cont">   <img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/060918_feedback_inline_370.png?mode=topic&amp;context=43" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/060918_feedback_inline_370.png?mode=topic&amp;context=43" alt="The Golden Record" class="caption" style="width: 370px; height: 370px;" title="~~ NASA/JPL" /><noscript><img src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/05/main/articles/060918_feedback_inline_370.png?mode=topic&amp;context=43" alt="The Golden Record" class="caption" style="width: 370px; height: 370px;" title="~~ NASA/JPL" /></noscript> </div> </div></div><h4><strong>Black hole puzzles</strong></h4><p><em>After Stephen Hawkingâ€™s death in March, scientists reflected on the famed cosmologistâ€™s theories, including Hawking radiation, <strong>Emily Conover</strong></em> <em>reported in â€œ<a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/how-physicists-will-remember-stephen-hawking?mode=topic&amp;context=43">How physicists will remember Stephen Hawking</a>â€ (</em>SN: 4/14/18, p. 12<em>). </em></p><p>In theory, Hawking radiation occurs when one member of a particle-antiparticle pair becomes trapped inside of a black hole, allowing the partner to escape. Many readers wondered how Hawking radiation could cause a black hole to evaporate over time. â€œIt seems the black hole would be increasing in mass by the amount of energy contained in the particle it has just captured,â€ reader <strong>Larry Gioannini</strong> wrote.</p><p>A particle can escape only if its trapped partner has negative energy, <strong>Conover </strong>says. â€œWhen a black hole absorbs a negative energy particle, that particle actually takes away some of the black holeâ€™s energy,â€ she says. â€œBecause energy and mass are equivalent in physics, according to Einsteinâ€™s theory of special relativity, the black hole loses mass. So it will disappear if this process continues long enough.â€</p><h4><strong>Scientists get real</strong></h4><p><em>In her editorâ€™s note â€œ<a href="https://www.sciencenews.org/article/how-many-scientists-do-you-know-real-life%5D?mode=topic&amp;context=43">How many scientists do you know in real life?</a>â€ (</em>SN: 4/14/18, p. 2<em>), </em>Science News <em>Editor in Chief <strong>Nancy Shute</strong> wrote that the scientific and science journalism communities have more work to do to connect the public with scientists. </em></p><p><strong>Shuteâ€™s</strong> note resonated with readers.</p><p>â€œGreat to see that the organization recognizes the separation between scientists and the general public,â€ reader <strong>Charles Martin</strong> wrote. â€œAlso great to see that <em>SN</em> recognizes that it is the scientific communityâ€™s place to change that. Presentations at schools are great but donâ€™t really reach the general public. <em>SN</em> issues are one way, but why not consider a â€˜know a scientistâ€™ program nationwide? Think of the possibilities.â€</p><p>The editorâ€™s note stirred up memories for reader <strong>Carolee Metcalfe Wende</strong>. She recalled explaining to her young son that his father, a solar physicist, was a â€œdoctor of the sun.â€ â€œMy sonâ€™s face lit up with this most wonderful news! I think for the next year or so, he thought that his awesome father had something to do with the sun rising every morning,â€ she wrote. <strong>Metcalfe Wende</strong>, a microbiologist, also recalled a plaster test-tube holder that her son made for her. â€œI had it with me at work every day for the rest of my career,â€ she wrote. â€œThank you so much for bringing it to peopleâ€™s attention that even though not all scientists are as notable as those mentioned in the article, we indeed are all around, all the time, living normal, everyday lives.â€</p></span></div></div></div><span property="rnews:name schema:name" content="Readers respond to pesticides, Hawking radiation and more" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>        '),
(42, 'Why I Volunteer at the Intel International Science and Engineering Fair', '', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sponsored/why-i-volunteer-intel-international-science-and-engineering-fair?mode=topic&amp;context=76', 'why-i-volunteer-intel-international-science-and-engineering-fair', 'https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/03/2012-3.jpg', '     <div class="field field-name-field-op-main-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><img typeof="foaf:Image" data-echo="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/03/2012-3.jpg" data-icon="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/03/2012-3.jpg" width="840" height="630" alt="In 2012, judge and alumnus Scott Duke Kominers poses with Intel ISEF alumni Sara Volz (left) and Jonah Kallenbach (middle). Photo courtesy of Ellen Dickstein Kominers." /><noscript><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/2018/03/2012-3.jpg" width="840" height="630" alt="In 2012, judge and alumnus Scott Duke Kominers poses with Intel ISEF alumni Sara Volz (left) and Jonah Kallenbach (middle). Photo courtesy of Ellen Dickstein Kominers." /></noscript></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-op-caption field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p>In 2012, judge and alumnus Scott Duke Kominers (right) poses with Intel ISEF alumni Sara Volz (left) and Jonah Kallenbach (middle). Photo courtesy of Ellen Dickstein Kominers.</p></div></div></div><span property="dc:title" content="Why I Volunteer at the Intel International Science and Engineering Fair" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span><p>By Scott Duke Kominers</p><ul><li>Intel ISEF 2005, Intel STS 2005</li><li>MBA Class of 1960 Associate Professor of Business Administration, Harvard Business School</li><li>Faculty Affiliate: Harvard Department of Economics and Harvard Center of Mathematical Sciences and Applications</li><li>Co-chair: Mathematics Grand Awards Judging, Intel ISEF</li></ul><p>My Intel ISEF project back in 2005 was in quadratic form representation theory &mdash; and a world expert in the field was on one of the judging panels.</p><p>Before judging started in earnest, he dropped by just to tell me how excited he was that I was studying quadratic forms. We had a high-bandwidth conversation about recent developments in the field. It was electrifying. This judge treated me like a colleague. I was in high school &mdash; he was tenured faculty at a top research university &mdash; yet he recognized me as a mathematician.</p><p><img alt="" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/sites/default/files/images/scott1.jpg" style="width: 300px; height: 386px; float: right;" title="" /><strong>Judge after judge engaged me as a scholar,</strong> learning about my work and simultaneously welcoming me into the mathematics community. What a gift.</p><p>I signed up to be an Intel ISEF judge as soon as I became eligible so that I could give that same gift to the next generation of scholars. I judge at Intel ISEF every year I can and recruit my friends and colleagues as judges too.</p><p><strong>Judging is a great way to give back.</strong> It lets you be part of the community of research competitions &mdash; and of student science more generally.</p><p>I&rsquo;ve had the honor of serving on judging panels alongside people who judged me back in 2005. And many of the students I&rsquo;ve met in my years as a judge have stayed in touch, reaching out to me for course and career advice. I&rsquo;m sure some of them will be judging alongside me one day.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Intel ISEF 2018 | May 11&ndash;18 in Pittsburgh</strong></p><p>Sign up to volunteer today!</p><p>E-mail: <a href="mailto:isefvolunteer@societyforscience.org">isefvolunteer@societyforscience.org</a><br />Website: <a href="http://student.societyforscience.org/volunteer2018" target="_blank">student.societyforscience.org/volunteer2018</a></p>  ');
